<FIRST>u a AM-ShipAground     11-02 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ship Aground,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>475-Foot Yugoslavian Freighter Pulled Off Shoal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tugboats successfully dragged a 475-foot
Yugoslavian freighter from a sandy shoal off the Florida Keys late
Thursday after the ship's fuel oil was pumped off to a barge to
lighten the vessel, the Coast Guard said.
   The Mavro Vetranic, which ran aground on the shoal containing
fragile coral last Monday, was refloated at 9:04 p.m. EST ``with
the assistance of tugs _ we don't know how many,'' said Coast Guard
spokesman Steve Sapp.
   ``They're moving it to safe anchorage in deeper water. What
they're going to do is perform a survey inside the ship to see how
much damage was done,'' Sapp said.
   ``There was no leaking or pollution of any kind'' from the
freighter, he added.
   Sapp said the freighter was pulled free shortly after crews
completed the two-day operation to unload the ship's fuel as the
tide was coming in.
   The hull was not damaged when the ship ran aground early Monday
in the Dry Tortugas about 60 miles west of Key West, but state
officials estimate the ship caused tens of millions of dollars
damage by carving a 500-foot swath through coral patches.
   The state expected to file suit for reef damage Friday in Monroe
Circuit Court.
   Coast Guard Capt. Henry D. Jacoby flew to Key West on Thursday
to convene a fact-finding board of inquiry to determine the cause
of the grounding.
</TEXT>
