<FIRST>u w AM-GuatemalanNun     11-02 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Guatemalan Nun,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Missing in Guatemala</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic American nun was reported
missing in Guatemala on Thursday, the State Department said
Thursday night.
   Spokesman Dave Denny said after a telephone conversation with
the U.S. Embassy in Guatemala City that the embassy did not have a
confirmed identity of the missing nun.
   Denny said he thus could not confirm a report that it was Sister
Diana Ortiz of the Ursuline order, as reported in Kentucky.
   The Louisville Courier-Journal in Friday editions quoted members
of the order as saying Ortiz disappeared from the Ursuline retreat
house at Antigua, about 15 miles west of Guatemala City, between 8
a.m. and 9 a.m. while praying alone in a courtyard. Her shawl was
found in the courtyard by her two colleagues who lived with her
there on a teaching assignment in the village of San Miguel Acatan.
   Ortiz had received at least seven threatening letters this year
warning her to leave the country and her colleagues fear she has
been kidnapped, Sister Mary Elizabeth Dallard of the Ursuline
convent in Maple Mount, Ky. told the newspaper.
   But no group has claimed responsibility for a kidnapping.
   Denny said the Guatemalan police had been given a missing person
report. Police do not act on such reports for 24 hours while
waiting to see if the missing person turns up, he said.
   A nun from the Antigua retreat house is to visit the embassy on
Friday to provide more information, Denny said.
   Ortiz, a native of Grants, N.M., had taught school in Owensboro
and Hawesville, Ky., before going to Guatemala two years ago.
</TEXT>
