<DOCNO> AP891102-0008 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 0034EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-OrtegaEditorial     11-02 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ortega Editorial,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ortega to Bush: If You're A `Big Man,' Disband Contras</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega, in an
article published in The New York Times, pledged to hold ``free and
democratic'' elections next year and defended his decision to end a
cease-fire with the Contra rebels.
   Ortega also lashed out at President Bush for delivering a
``torrent of personal invective'' against the Central American
leader during a meeting of hemispheric leaders in Costa Rica last
week.
   ``He accused me of spoiling the `garden party' in Costa Rica,''
Ortega said in the op-ed piece published in Thursday's editions.
   ``Well, life in my country is no `garden party.' Eight years of
war financed and directed by the Reagan and Bush adminstrations
have seen to that.''
   Ortega defended his move to end the cease-fire, which he
announced last week in at the democracy celebration in San Jose,
Costa Rica, provoking outrage from Bush and other Latin American
leaders.
   The only way to peace in Nicaragua is to disband the
U.S.-supported rebels, Ortega wrote.
   ``We do not consider it an acceptable cease-fire when we cease
and the Contras fire,'' he said. ``For peace to be achieved, the
war itself must be stopped. There is no other way to end the war
than to start immediately the demobilization of the Contras.''
   ``A truly `big man' would have no difficulty making the right
choice,'' he wrote, in an apparent reference to Bush's
characterization of him as a ``little man.''
   Ortega said halting the cease-fire was necessary because the
rebels' aim through repeated violations was to subvert the
electoral process in Nicaragua, which has elections scheduled for
Feb. 25.
   ``During October, Contra units newly supplied and infiltrated
from Honduras closed more than 50 voter registration centers,
preventing thousands of citizens from registering to vote,'' Ortega
said. ``They targeted for assassination known Sandinista supporters
_ prominent community leaders, party activists and candidates for
municipal offices _ and slit their throats.''
   He cited other attacks, including one in which 19 reservists
were killed in an Oct. 21 ambush on their way to register to vote.
   ``Why the upswing in Contra violence? The success of our
electoral process has made them desperate. They fear that free
elections, duly recognized by the international community, will end
their flickering hopes of continuing the way,'' Ortega said.
   He also made a ``solemn pledge'' that his country would
``celebrate free, fair and democratic elections.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
