<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 0037EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Quake     11-02 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Quake,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>Powerful Temblor Jolts Northern Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHIL BROWN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nation that nervously watched the California
earthquake on television and then sent more than $7 million in aid
received a scare and a shaking from an equally powerful tremor
today.
   No casualties or major damage were reported in today's quake,
which measured an estimated 7.1 on the Richter scale and whose
impact was blunted by its epicenter's distance from Japan's Pacific
coast _ about 80 miles.
   Nevertheless, 6,165 people from six coastal towns and villages
were evacuated to town halls and school gymnasiums for fear of
tsunami, or waves generated by the quake, said Toshihara Kon, a
fire department official in Iwate prefecture, about 300 miles
northeast of Tokyo.
   The evacuation order was lifted 3{ hours after the quake hit at
3:26 a.m., Kon said. Shortly after that, all tsunami warnings were
lifted, the Central Meteorological Agency reported.
   As felt in northern Honshu, Japan's main island, the quake was
strong enough to shake buildings and topple unstable objects.
   Waves of up to two feet were reported in some areas, and about
400 boats, mostly fishing craft, put out to sea from Hachinohe to
avoid being caught in the harbor by tsunami. They later returned.
   Kon said a small landslide briefly blocked traffic on a local
road, but fallen dirt and rocks were cleared and traffic soon
returned to normal.
   Officials briefly closed the main expressway through the
affected region for inspection and overnight trains were stopped so
rails could be inspected.
   Japan's meteorological agency estimated the quake's magnitude at
7.1 on the Richter scale, nearly the same as that of the quake that
devastated much of the San Francisco Bay area on Oct. 17.
   The U.S. Geological Survey in Colorado estimated the Japanese
quake's magnitude at 7.3. Don Finley, a spokesman for the survey,
said it was the strongest in the region since a 7.7 quake on March
9, 1931.
   Toshio Akiyama, head of the Japanese agency's earthquake and
tsunami observation division, said that although distance weakened
the effect of today's quake, authorities were concerned because a
series of quakes have occurred in the area in recent months.
   On Sunday, a quake registering 6.5 and centered about 95 miles
off the coast hit the area without causing casualties or damage.
   Like California, Japan sits atop a major fault and is frequently
shaken by earthquakes. Although few cause casualties, fears of a
major temblor prompt regular national disaster-prevention drills
and newer buildings are designed to withstand quakes of up to 8 on
the Richter scale.
   Many Japanese had immediate word of the San Francisco quake as
they tuned in for a satellite telecast of the World Series.
   The Foreign Ministry said it knew of at least $7.2 million in
government and private contributions from Japan for San Francisco
quake victims.
   After that quake, Japanese experts rushed to the area, hoping to
learn why some buildings collapsed and others stood.
   Akiyama said Japan had a second quake today at 4:57 a.m. in
Tottori prefecture, about 300 miles southwest of Tokyo. He said
there were no casualties or damage reported from that 5.7-magnitude
quake, and today's two temblors were not related.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. A quake of magnitude 6 can cause severe damage in
populated areas, and a quake of 7 is capable of widespread, heavy
damage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891102-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 0028EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Contras Bjt   11-02 0869</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Contras, Bjt,0897</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Contras Refuse To Fade Away</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY7</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Contra guerrillas fighting the Sandinista
government in Nicaragua have said it again and again: they don't
recognize the Central American peace accords and they won't accept
demobilization.
   That stubborn stand now has become a stumbling block to peace in
the region and to democratic elections in Nicaragua, leading to
President Daniel Ortega's announcement Wednesday that he was
suspending a 19-month truce and resuming the war.
   ``The problem here is not the cease-fire; the problem here is
the demobilization,'' said Ortega.
   He said he was ending the unilateral cease-fire, which began in
March 1988, because of increasing attacks by the Contras in
defiance of agreements signed by five Central American presidents
in Tela, Honduras on Aug. 7.
   The presidents called for voluntary demobilization, repatriation
or resettlement of Contra fighters, most of them based at camps in
Honduras. In exchange, Ortega agreed to democratize the electoral
process and hold elections on Feb. 25 with international observers.
   Battle-hardened Contra troop commanders who had taken over
leadership of the movement quickly said the peace process would not
work without their participation and vowed to move back into
Nicaragua with their men.
   ``We will say thank you and good-bye to Honduras,'' said
Commander `Dima,' a member of the Contra general staff, in an
interview at one of the camps on Aug. 25.
   U.S. officials said they would prefer that the Contras remain in
Honduras to guarantee the fairness of the Feb. 25 vote, and said
they feared the small groups of Contras would be wiped out by the
vastly larger Sandinista army.
   But the angry commanders, feeling betrayed both by the United
States and by other nations in the region, weren't listening.
   They also expressed contempt for Contra ``office soldiers'' who
spent the long years of war in Miami or Washington instead of the
jungle. They expressed bitterness about U.S. support, which one
compared to a balky cigarette lighter that ``works when it wants
to.''
   But they also felt a sense of freedom from restraints imposed by
U.S. policy as well as the taint of being U.S. mercenaries.
   Contra army commander Israel Galeano, in a speech at the
Contras' main camp at Yamales in Honduras, outlined a classic
guerrilla strategy for the future.
   ``If we fight for the people we have to gain their support,'' he
said. ``We are the peasants of Nicaragua.''
   He said that neither the Sandinistas nor the rest of the world
had ever acknowledged that the Contras were real people, poor
people, with real grievances against the Sandinista government.
   The bulk of the Contra army was in fact made up of sharecroppers
and small farmers who resented Sandinista land reform and attempts
to collectivize agriculture or force farmers to sell to the state
at fixed prices.
   ``We know we have made mistakes,'' said Defense Minister
Humberto Ortega, Daniel Ortega's brother, during a September
interview in Mexico City. Ortega said he thought Contras
infiltrating from Honduras would try to move into
Sandinista-controlled zones.
   ``We'll attack them so that we understand each other,'' he said.
   When the Aug. 7 agreements were announced, there were about
12,000 Contra fighters in Honduras, many of them accompanied by
their families.
   Some were already looking for ways to fade out of the war _
moving to Canada, finding work in Honduras or simply returning
quietly to their homes in Nicaragua.
   The numbers of those actually returning to Nicaragua as members
of fighting units is unclear.
   Enrique Bermudez, the only ``outside'' Contra commander who
retained respect among the fighters, said Wednesday that 6,000 had
returned. Daniel Ortega said 1,100 had returned in the last three
weeks; U.S. sources put total Contra forces in Nicaragua at 4,000.
   The United States has been providing non-lethal aid to the
Contras since military aid was suspended in February 1988. The
so-called ``humanitarian'' aid includes boots, tents and uniforms
that Contras can use in Nicaragua.
   But no weapons or ammunition were received, and U.S. sources in
Washington said they refused pleas to provide food in smaller
packages that would be easier to pack into the jungle.
   Nevertheless, the Contras said they would fight on, seizing
weapons and ammunition where they could. ``We started with .22s and
shotguns,'' said Dima.
   That fierce determination, foolish or not, finally led
Nicaragua's Sandinistas to the realization that the Dec. 5 deadline
for demobilization would not be met.
   The Sandinistas vowed to proceed with elections no matter what
the Contras did, but added that renewed U.S. military aid might be
cause for cancellation.
   Both Sandinistas and Contras on Wednesday announced escalating
clashes in the jungles and mountains of northern and eastern
Nicaragua, where the Contra troops were fighting for survival.
   As the fighting flared, Bermudez said in a telephone interview
that the Contras had not received ``even a single cartridge'' from
the United States, and admitted that prospects for renewed military
aid were grim.
   ``Faced with this reality, we can't do anything except save our
own lives and defend ourselves as best we can,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Herzfelder is The Associated Press' news
editor for Central America.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
