<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 0028EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-MissingBoyRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0767 11-02 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missing Boy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0767,0620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hope Dwindles in Searches for Missing Oregon Boys</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with body identified as that of
missing 4-year-old. Picks up 6th graf pvs, `There had...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A hunter Wednesday found the nude, strangled body of a
4-year-old Oregon boy missing since Sunday, and rescuers elsewhere
in the state ended their search for a 9-year-old boy and his pony
after 10 fruitless days.
   In St. Joseph, Minn., meanwhile, the parents of 11-year-old
Jacob Wetterling, who was abducted 11 days ago by a masked gunman,
said they planned a nationwide mailing of fliers with their son's
photo and description. The search for Jacob continued.
   A hunter in Clark County, Wash., found the body of Lee Joseph
Iseli, 4, of Portland around 8:30 a.m. in bushes along a road near
Vancouver Lake, just across the Columbia River from Portland,
authorities said.
   The boy was strangled and his body was nude when found, said
Clark County Coroner Arch Hamilton. He declined to provide further
details about its condition.
   Portland police picked up copies of Lee's fingerprints from his
father for use in helping to identify the body.
   There had been growing fear a kidnapper might have taken the
boy, who disappeared Sunday afternoon from a playground where he'd
gone with his 9-year-old brother. Authorities prepared a drawing of
a man seen at the playground around that time.
   Dogs tracked the boy's scent from the playground to a street
curb, indicating the child might have gotten into a car.
   In central Oregon, searchers broke camp, ending the search of
snowy woods along the Little Deschutes River for Nathan Madsen, 9,
of Veneta, who disappeared with his pony Oct. 22 during a family
cattle roundup.
   Rescue units ran out of places to look for Nathan, said Klamath
County Sheriff Carl Burkhart.
   Burkhart said in a statement that there had been numerous
unsubstantiated rumors about the boy and his horse, a sorrel named
Tony, but authorities had no leads on where they were.
   At the height of the search last week, 350 people tramped over
an area nearly 30 miles square. The number of searchers dropped to
52 Monday after officials urged volunteers to return to their homes
and jobs.
   The investigation into Nathan's disappearance will continue,
Burkhart said.
   In St. Joseph in central Minnesota, Jerry and Patty Wetterling
held a news conference outside their home to announce the mailings
containing a description and photograph of their son.
   The first batch, about 30,000 fliers, is to go out Thursday, and
organizers hope to send millions in the next few weeks, said Vern
Iverson, a friend of the Wetterlings. They are being sent to fire
and police stations, military bases, hospitals, city governments
and social agencies, and to such national groups as the American
Medical Association, in hopes the groups will insert the fliers in
their own mailings.
   In an appearance Wednesday on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America,''
Stearns County Sheriff Charlie Grafft said authorities have
received ``hundreds and hundreds'' of calls since Jacob's abduction
on a rural road near his home Oct. 22. Grafft said the number of
tips and offers of help was ``mind-boggling.''
   Mrs. Wetterling said on the program that she wants everyone's
attention focused on Jacob to give him strength and to make his
face familiar so that his abductor has no option other than
returning him.
   She said she hasn't lost hope Jacob will be found.
   ``I just keep myself going by playing a tape in my head, `He's
OK, he's coming home soon, this is really wrong and he will be home
soon,''' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
