<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 2352EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-PayRaise     11-02 0165</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pay Raise,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Speaker, GOP Leader Ask Bush To Back Pay Raise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House's two top party leaders asked
President Bush to back a pay raise for high-ranking government
officials, but the meeting did not produce an immediate
presidential endorsement, The Washington Post reported Friday.
   House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., and Minority Leader
Robert Michel, R-Ill., told the president that without his support,
a pay raise for federal judges, members of Congress and senior
executive branch employees is dead, the newspaper reported.
   An unidentified White House official told the newspaper that the
president has not ruled out the possibility of a pay raise, but as
part of the package he wants Congress to adopt tighter ethics
restrictions.
   The Post said that Foley and Michel both back a pay raise
proposal that would phase in a 35 percent salary boost.
   A public uproar caused Congress to kill a pay proposal last year
that would have raised salaries by 51 percent.
</TEXT>
