<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 0143EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FrontPageResignation     11-02 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Front Page Resignation,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Editor Sticks Resignation on Front Page</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: BayTimes cq in 7th graf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DILLINGHAM, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The managing editor of the Bristol Bay
News glued his resignation notice to more than 1,000 copies of the
weekly newspaper, then went to work for the paper's competitor.
   David McElroy said he resigned after one month on the job
because his former boss, Publisher John Lindauer, is planning to
run for governor and gave him no control over the newspaper.
   ``It's really unethical for a journalistic operation to be
controlled by a politician,'' McElroy said Wednesday. ``He's more
or less stated that he intends to control political news. I told
him that's unethical and I wouldn't be a part of that.''
   Lindauer, a former Republican state legislator, said from
Anchorage that he had not yet decided whether to run for governor
in 1990. He said he resigned Wednesday as president and chief
executive officer of his company, Lindauer Newspapers and Radio, to
pursue other interests including politics.
   He denied that his politics had anything to do with McElroy's
resignation.
   ``He only worked for us for about 30 days. I was gone almost all
that time in California,'' Lindauer said. ``Let me put it this way:
It was bizarre behavior under any circumstance.''
   McElroy, 37, joined the Bristol BayTimes as a reporter less than
a week after his 3-by-5 resignation notice was glued to copies of
the Oct. 20 edition of the Bay News. McElroy said he pasted the
notice on the paper to underscore his lack of authority.
   Dillingham is a fishing port of 2,100 residents along Bristol
Bay on the southern coast of Alaska.
</TEXT>
