<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891102-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 0152EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     11-02 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Closes Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed higher against the Japanese yen
Thursday, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange edged
downward.
   The dollar ended at 143.75 yen, up 0.67 yen from Wednesday's
143.08-yen finish. It opened higher at 143.93 yen and ranged
between 143.65 yen and 144.15 yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 69.57 points, or 0.20
percent, closing at 35,494.86. It had gained 14.99 points the
previous day.
   Dealers said the index fell as market players were discouraged
by the yen's weakness against the dollar, as well as by an uptrend
in domestic short-term interest rates.
   Nikko Securities dealer Yoshio Shimoyama said, ``Market players,
especially institutional investors, were reluctant to make major
moves prior to the U.S. jobless rate release later Friday and a
three-day weekend.''
   The United States is to release the nation's unemployment figure
for October on Friday in Washington. Japanese financial markets
will close Friday for Culture Day, a national holiday.
   In currency dealings, the dollar started higher following a
similar upswing on overseas markets overnight.
   ``Market players were afraid of the Bank of Japan's
intervention, and started selling the currency in early trading,
which pushed down the dollar a bit temporarily. But the dollar rose
back as investment trust companies bought it back,'' said a trader
with Mitsubishi Bank.
   Japan's central bank sold dollars to support the yen, but the
amount of its intervention was unclear. The Bank of Japan does not
comment on its monetary actions.
   Speaking anonymously, the Mitsubishi Bank trader said Japanese
investors are buying the dollar because they think U.S. interest
rates will not fall soon, even though U.S. economic growth has
slowed.
   ``Even if U.S. interest rates fall, they will still be much
higher than Japanese rates, and more profitable,'' the trader said.
   Higher interest rates tend to support the price of a country's
currency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
