<FIRST>r i PM-Iran-US     11-02 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-US,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Khamenei Calls For ``Perpetual Struggle'' Against U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As a wave of anti-Americanism sweeps Iran,
the country's supreme leader, Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, called on
citizens ``to wage perpetual struggle'' against the United States.
   Khamenei addressed hundreds of students Wednesday, the same day
Parliament passed a law giving the government powers to arrest
Americans anywhere and put them on trial if they seek to harm
Iranians or the Islamic republic.
   The move came three days before expected mass anti-American
demonstrations to mark Saturday's 10th anniversary of the seizure
of the U.S. Embassy.
   Militants stormed the sprawling embassy complex Nov. 4, 1979 and
held 52 diplomats and other embassy personnel hostage for 444 days.
   ``The dismay and shame resulting from this humiliation will
always remain on the face of the oppressor ringleaders of the
United States,'' said Khamenei, a former president and successor to
the late Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   Iran's state-run television network broadcast Khamenei's
address. It showed students punching the air with their fists and
chanting ``Death to America!'' and ``Khamenei is our leader. We
obey your orders, Khamenei.''
   Western and Third World diplomats believe anti-American feeling
is being whipped up by radicals to undermine reported efforts by
President Hashemi Rafsanjani, leader of Iran's so-called
pragmatists, to improve relations with the West and end the
country's isolation.
   The new law was enacted in response to the U.S. Justice
Department's action earlier this year authorizing the FBI to arrest
people wanted by U.S. courts anywhere in the world, without seeking
permission of the countries where they are located, and bring them
to trial in the United States.
   The U.S. action did not specify Iran. But the Islamic republic
is one of several states Washington considers to support and
encourage terrorism, including the kidnapping of Americans and
other Westerners in Lebanon, assassinations and hijackings.
   Iranian radicals saw the Justice Department's action as aimed at
the Islamic republic and an opportunity to exploit anti-U.S.
sentiment to counter Rafsanjani's policies, diplomats said.
   ``U.S. citizens and their agents, and countries which
collaborate with the United States in kidnapping or endangering
Iranian citizens or the interests of the Islamic republic, will be
tried by Iranian courts according to Islamic justice,'' the new law
declares.
   Hundreds of students packed the covered lawn in the grounds of
Khamenei's official residence in downtown Tehran on Wednesday.
Among them were representatives of some of the main groups that
have called for a massive protest outside the former embassy
Saturday.
   These include the ``Students following the Imam's line,'' the
group that stormed the embassy, the Association of Militant Clergy,
and Students of the Intelligence Ministry College.
   A leading cleric, Ayatollah Ahmad Jannati, declared: ``As long
as the Islamic revolution exists, U.S. hostility will not cease. As
long as our enemy is America, the struggle against it tops all our
efforts.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
