<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake 2ndLd-Writethru a0433 11-02 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0433,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bay Area South to Watsonville Rocked Again by Aftershock</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with quotes; picks up next-to-last graf; ADDS byline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake-South of the Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ``awesome'' aftershock to the
devastating Oct. 17 earthquake jolted Northern California late
Wednesday, panicking people from San Francisco to Watsonville.
   The tremor caused some minor damage but there were no immediate
reports of injuries.
   The aftershock hit shortly before 10 p.m. and was felt in San
Francisco, Santa Cruz and Watsonville.
   ``It rattled pretty good at first and then kept on kind of
rolling. You could feel the foundation swaying,'' said Ani
LeRitz-Murphy of Watsonville.
   The 9:50 p.m. aftershock measured 4.4 on the Richter scale of
ground motion and was centered slightly north of the epicenter of
last month's magnitude-7.1 quake, said Pat Jorgenson, spokeswoman
for the U.S. Geological Survey in Menlo Park.
   San Francisco police said there was only minor damage in the
city's Marina district, which was devastated by the main quake.
   ``We've had a couple of reports of minor stuff nothing major at
this time, just bricks falling, people calling in sheer panic
saying, `The big one is on the way.' We try to console them and
tell them it's an aftershock,'' said Officer Gordon Clark.
   ``Awesome,'' said Santa Cruz County sheriff's dispatcher Kevin
Fink. ``Shook pretty good. We were sweating bullets for a few
seconds.''
   There have been thousands of aftershocks and 84 have had Richter
readings of at least 3.0 and 21 of magnitude-4.0 or greater. The
strongest registered 5.2, just 37 minutes after the initial jolt.
   ``This is one of the biggest I've felt since I got here on the
19th,'' said Lt. Jeffrey Babineu at the National Guard Armory in
Watsonville, which is housing 100 people left homeless by the quake.
   ``We heard a rumbling, then everything started rolling and the
cars in the parking lot started jumping around,'' he said. ``A few
of the people in the shelter screamed out, but then it stopped.''
   Watsonville police received about a dozen calls from people who
were worried about any additional damage the aftershock might have
caused their already damaged homes, said dispatcher Terry Hernandez.
   ``Apparently a lot of people ran out into the street,'' she
said. ``We got a call from an apartment complex and they said
everyone ran out.''
   She said there were no immediate reports of damage.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude.
   An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause slight
damage in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage,
6 severe damage. A 7 reading is a ``major'' earthquake, capable of
widespread heavy damage.
</TEXT>
