<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     11-02 0862</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,860</SECOND>
<HEAD>USDA: Off-Farm Earnings Sets Record</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jobs in town for years have been vital for
thousands of farm families whose paychecks often exceed what they
earn from the land.
   The Agriculture Department says off-farm earnings in 1988 were a
record $51.7 billion, up from the previous high of $46.8 billion in
1987. Total U.S. net cash income from farming last year was also a
record _ $59.9 billion, up from $57.7 billion in 1987.
   Last year's off-farm income, which includes that of all family
members as well as the farm operator, exceeded net cash income from
farming in all years prior to 1986, according to department
analysts.
   In some years, most recently 1984, off-farm earnings were more
than net farm cash income, which is the difference between annual
cash expenses and gross cash income from farming operations.
   State-by-state income, off-farm earnings and other data were
reported by USDA this week in a new 240-page report, part of an
annual financial series about the agricultural sector.
   Robert P. Williams of the department's Economic Research Service
said Wednesday no attempt was made to rank the states according to
off-farm income. But he did compile at the request of The
Associated Press the top 10 off-farm earners in 1988.
   Farm income surpassed off-farm income last year in only three
states of the top 10 _ California, Illinois and Iowa. Off-farm
earnings exceeded farm income in the remaining seven: Texas, Ohio,
Missouri, Indiana, Kentucky, Tennessee and Oklahoma.
   Texas, which leads the nation in the number of farms _ an
estimated 188,000 last year _ also led in 1988 off-farm earnings
with more than $5 billion. That was well above the state's net cash
farm income last year of less than $3.9 billion.
   Others in the top 10 in 1988 off-farm income, in order, included:
   _California, $2.66 billion off the farm and a net cash farm
income of $6.54 billion; the state was reported to have an
estimated 84,000 farms.
   _Ohio, $2.36 billion in off-farm income and a net cash farm
income of $1.44 billion; an estimated 85,000 farms.
   _Missouri, $2.22 billion in off-farm income and $1.48 billion
net cash farm income; an estimated 110,000 farms.
   _Indiana, $2.12 billion in off-farm income and $1.48 billion net
cash farm income; an estimated 74,000 farms.
   _Kentucky, $2.1 billion in off-farm income and $1.09 billion net
cash farm income; an estimated 97,000 farms.
   _Tennessee, $2 billion in off-farm income and $818.1 million net
cash farm income; an estimated 91,000 farms.
   _Illinois, $1.95 billion in off-farm income and $2.63 billion
net cash farm income; an estimated 88,000 farms.
   _Oklahoma, $1.84 billion in off-farm income and $1.23 billion
net cash farm income; an estimated 70,000 farms.
   _Iowa, $1.81 billion in off-farm income and $3.44 billion net
cash farm income; an estimated 107,000 farms.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDS: Cathleen 3rd graf cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mechanical digester is being developed to
safely dispose of waste water after farm sprayers are flushed to
rid them of pesticides, says the Agriculture Department.
   The department's Agricultural Research Service said Wednesday
that the portable treatment uses ozone gas and soil microorganisms
to break down unused pesticides before disposal.
   Cathleen J. Somich, a chemist at the agency's Beltsville, Md.,
research facility, said the goal is to turn unused pesticides into
innocuous carbon dioxide instead of converting them into other
toxic compounds that are disposed of by burning.
   ``We don't want to take the risk of substituting air pollution
for water pollution,'' she said in an agency report.
   Ciba-Geigy Corp. of Greensboro, N.C., has entered into a
cooperative agreement with the agency to continue with the
development of the procedure and the device to see if it can handle
larger volumes of pesticide, officials said.
   The treatment was originated at Beltsville. Somich and agency
colleagues a year ago tested the original apparatus with seed money
from Ciba-Geigy, using it on 150 gallons of ``typical pesticide
soup'' consisting of detergent and water used to clean corn
herbicides from spray tanks.
   Within three days, the treatment destroyed between 46 percent
and 96 percent of the chemicals used in the sprayer by subjecting
them to a digestion process aided by the ozone gas.
   Somich said that pesticides are resistant to microbial digestion
but the ozone treatment oxidizes and makes them more biodegradable.
   The technology is far from the commercial stage, but Steve
Dumford, Ciba-Geigy's director of new technology and basic
research, said he envisions the device one day being transported
from farm to farm for the treatment of pesticides and waste water
left over from cleaning chemical sprayers.
   Department officials said the process might also be used by lawn
care companies.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says the United
States in August exported an estimated 13 billion cigarettes valued
at $317.1 million.
   A report by the department's Foreign Agricultural Service said
August shipments were up 32 percent in volume and 42 percent in
value from a year earlier.
   But exports of unmanufactured tobacco in August totaled 10,777
metric tons worth $57.9 million, down 6 percent in volume and 17
percent in value from the year-earlier level, the agency said.
</TEXT>
