<FIRST>r w PM-BowlandRejected     11-02 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bowland Rejected,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Blocks Bush Nominee to Wage Post</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's nomination of Debra R.
Bowland to head the Labor Department's wage and hour division will
not get to the Senate floor because of a Senate panel's vote
against her confirmation.
   The Labor and Human Resources Committee voted 9-6 on Wednesday
not to send her nomination to the full Senate.
   Opponents focused on Bowland's campaign to repeal Louisiana's
prevailing wage law, the state equivalent of the federal
Davis-Bacon law that sets wage scales for work on government
construction contracts. The law is a favorite of organized labor.
   Prevailing wages are the going pay and benefits in a geographic
area, and usually are tied to union scales. Critics of the law say
it artificially raises the cost of construction.
   Committee Chairman Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., criticized the
nomination, holding up copies of the federal and state laws and
saying they were ``virtually identical.''
   ``This is the law she would have to implement and this is the
law she could not implement,'' Kennedy said.
   Bowland, 45, began fighting the Louisiana law while she was
state labor secretary from 1980 to 1982 under Gov. David Treen, a
Republican. She later campaigned against the law as a lobbyist.
   Bowland told senators at a hearing last week that she could
enforce the federal law.
   But Democrats said her vigorous past lobbying proved her deep
philosophical objection to government involvement in wage and hour
matters.
   ``This is putting the fox in charge of the chicken coop,'' said
Sen. Brock Adams, D-Wash.
   Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., added, ``We shouldn't put somebody in
charge of a law that they don't believe in _ period.''
   But Sen. James M. Jeffords, R-Vt., said Bowland opposed the
Louisiana law because of problems with implementation and
regulations.
   They noted it was repealed after her involvement and under a
Democratic administration.
   Bowland has been with the Labor Department since 1985 and heads
the Women's Bureau.
</TEXT>
