<FIRST>r w PM-FetalTissue     11-02 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fetal Tissue,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ban to be Continued on Federally Funded Fetal Tissue Research</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is allowing the rising
fever over abortion politics to get in the way of scientific
research, say critics of a ban on the use of federal money for
fetal tissue research.
   A top federal health official said Wednesday he intends to
extend indefinitely the ban on using tissue from intentional
abortions in federal research. Assistant Health Secretary James
Mason contended Wednesday such testing could create a demand for
more abortions.
   ``I see this as suppression of legitimate science in the federal
sector,'' said John C. Fletcher, director of the Center for
Biomedical Ethics at the University of Virginia. ``When political
considerations dominate science, it concerns me very, very much.''
   Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., chairman of the House Energy and
Commerce health subcommittee, said continuing the ban would be an
indication that the Bush administration ``is giving up any pretense
about caring about research or treating sick people or curing
chronic disease.''
   He added: ``The whole administration has become paralyzed by
fear of the abortion issue, when that's not the main issue before
us.''
   Waxman called on Health and Human Services Secretary Louis
Sullivan to reverse a decision planned by Mason to extend the ban.
He said Sullivan's job as secretary is ``to lead, not hide.''
   But HHS sources who spoke on the condition of anonymity said
Sullivan will concur with Mason's decision. An announcement was
expected today.
   Conservatives have pressed the administration to continue the
ban, warning that lifting it would create a firestorm of protest
from anti-abortion groups.
   The ban was imposed a year ago by Mason's predecessor as
assistant secretary for health, Robert Windom, when he rejected a
proposed project at the National Institutes of Health in which
scientists would transplant fetal tissue into patients with
Parkinson's disease.
   Windom also formed a special advisory committee to study whether
such federally funded research should continue. Late last year, the
committee recommended lifting the ban.
   The ban does not include fetal tissue from spontaneous abortions
and does not constrain privately financed research using tissue
from induced abortions.
   Scientists believe that research using tissue from aborted
fetuses could help treat Parkinson's disease and other incurable
conditions. The tissue is valued for its unique properties and
quick growth, allowing it to adapt quickly to new environments.
   The focus of fetal tissue research so far has been on
Parkinson's disease, but experts say it may also be useful in
treating other neurological degenerative diseases.
   ``NIH is supposed to be a partner with science in the private
area,'' said Fletcher, who was chief of the bioethics program at
the clinical center at NIH for a decade. ``This is the only area in
our scientific life that is being systematically suppressed in the
federal sector.''
   Mason, a strong abortion foe, said he opposes using federal
money to support research on fetal tissue from induced abortions
for moral reasons, saying it could lead to more abortions.
   Ultimately, he said, society would have to trade off the rights
of a fetus for those of a patient suffering from Parkinson's
disease or other condition that might benefit from fetal tissue.
   ``Even those that strongly favor fetal tissue transplantation
acknowledge that a strict wall would have to be erected between the
abortion decision and the decision to use fetal tissue in
transplantation research,'' Mason said. ``Such a distinction is
easy to theorize, but I just don't believe that such a neat
separation can be accomplished.''
   ``For anyone who believes that a fetus has some rights, then I
just find that this is unacceptable public policy,'' he said.
</TEXT>
