<FIRST>r w PM-JudgeNixon     11-02 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Judge Nixon,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Moving Toward Decision in Mississippi Impeachment Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate is closing its doors for the second
time in two weeks to debate the ouster of a federal judge as it
moves toward a decision in the impeachment trial of Walter L. Nixon
Jr. of Mississippi.
   ``The evidence against Judge Nixon is overwhelming,'' Rep. Don
Edwards, D-Calif., said Wednesday as Senate floor action got under
way. ``To maintain the integrity of the judiciary he must be
removed.''
   Nixon, currently living in a New Orleans halfway house for
former prisoners, would be the seventh federal official removed by
impeachment and the second judge ousted in two weeks if convicted
by the Senate.
   As a U.S. District judge, he continues to collect an $89,500
government salary and says he would like to return to the bench and
preside over trials despite his 1986 conviction for lying under
oath to a federal grand jury.
   The House on May 10 approved 417-0 three articles of impeachment
against the 61-year-old judge. Conviction in the Senate on any one
of them would automatically remove him from the bench.
   The Senate planned to go into closed session today to debate the
matter after hearing final arguments on Wednesday. Lawmakers were
likely to put off a vote until Friday.
   The Senate on Oct. 20 ousted Alcee L. Hastings from the U.S.
District Court in Miami on charges he plotted to obtain a bribe and
lied to a jury that acquitted him of that charge in 1983.
   Nixon was convicted of lying to a federal grand jury in denying
he talked with a local prosecutor and old friend, Paul Holmes,
about marijuana-smuggling charges against Drew Fairchild, the son
of a wealthy contractor.
   Holmes was district attorney of Forrest County, Miss., at the
time and the marijuana charges became inactive after the
discussion, prosecutors said.
   Nixon took the Senate floor and denied any wrongdoing. He said
witnesses against him lied and that overzealous prosecutors held
him to an unfairly high standard of accuracy in his sworn
statements.
   ``I had nothing to hide,'' Nixon said. ``I had done nothing
wrong. I had not committed any corrupt act ... why would I lie
about something that I hadn't done?''
   He assured lawmakers he had always acted fairly in his courtroom
in accord with advice from ``my good friend, Sen. John C. Stennis.''
   Stennis retired in 1988 after representing Mississippi in the
Senate for four decades.
   ``I have served honestly and faithfully as a federal judge for
21 years,'' Nixon said. ``I have always been mindful that I was
appointed, not anointed.''
   Defense counsel David Stewart acknowledged forgetfulness in
Nixon's testimony but said there was no attempt to deceive the
government.
   One of the House managers of the case, Rep. James Sensenbrenner,
R-Wis., scoffed at that notion. ``Are they deceits or just a series
of mistakes?'' he said in an incredulous voice. ``Fourteen
mistakes.''
   Stewart also told the Senate the charges against Nixon did not
accurately reflect the actual words of the judge when he was under
oath.
   ``They are asking you to send him to dishonor in history for
lying about statements that he didn't make,'' Stewart said.
   Nixon said it would be understandable if senators believed
``something is wrong'' merely because the case has come before them.
   ``There is something wrong with this situation,'' Nixon said.
``But what is wrong is that I am paying a debt that is not owed ...
From the very beginning the goal of the federal prosecutors was to
get the federal judge, no matter what it took, and it took plenty.''
</TEXT>
