<FIRST>r w PM-US-Afghan     11-02 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Afghan,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghan Rebels Say More U.S. Support Promised</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is telling exile
leaders of the Afghan resistance it will keep sending them arms to
fight the Soviet-backed government in Afghanistan, officials say.
   ``They assured us of their continued support,'' said Farooq
Azam, the education minister of the Afghan Interim Government,
which is based in Peshawar, Pakistan, near the border with
Afghanistan.
   Azam led a delegation that met Wednesday with Vice President Dan
Quayle and on Tuesday with Secretary of State James A. Baker III.
   A spokesman for the vice president, David Beckwith, said
``Quayle assured them of our continuing support. We continue to
support an independent and representative government for
Afghanistan.''
   U.S. military assistance to the mujahedeen guerrillas slackened
after Soviet troops withdrew last February, hampering efforts to
dislodge government forces from heavily fortified cities, Azam said
in an interview.
   ``This year, we did not even receive the amount we received last
year,'' he said. ``Our friends have slowed down their assistance.''
   Deliveries have resumed, say U.S. officials who spoke on
condition they not be identified. They declined to discuss details
of the covert program, which was estimated at close to $600 million
last year.
   Asked whether the aid was sufficient to dislodge government
forces from fortified cities they have occupied, Azam said, ``we
will see.''
   The mujahedeen need more weapons now, he said, because they are
mounting offensives and sieges against fortified military
positions, a tactic which generally requires more armaments than
the guerrilla warfare used earlier.
   ``We need support now more than ever,'' he said.
   U.S. and mujahedeen sources say Moscow has continued to send
huge quantities of arms to the regime the Russians left behind even
though Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze said last
week the 1979 Red Army intervention in Afghanistan violated moral
and civilized behavior.
   ``We believe that since the Soviet withdrawal, there has been a
kind of thinking in the United States that the war is over,'' Azam
said.
   In talks with Quayle and Baker, he said, ``we made our point
that the war is not over.''
   The Soviets left $2 billion worth of military hardware when they
withdrew, and have sent an additional $3 billion since then, said
Azam.
   The increase in Soviet aid and drop in U.S. assistance
frustrated mujahedeen efforts to take cities such as Jalalabad, in
eastern Afghanistan, he said.
   The Dec. 2-3 meeting between President Bush and Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev was not discussed in the meetings with
administration officials, said Azam.
   ``We don't think that the United States will reach an agreement
with the Soviet Union that would harm the resistance,'' he said.
</TEXT>
