<HEAD>Garry Trudeau Sues Writers Guild</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cartoonist Garry Trudeau has sued the Writers
Guild of America for $10 million, claiming the union harassed him
because he refused to participate in a strike against a company he
co-owns.
   The creator of the ``Doonesbury'' comic strip said his
independent television production company, Darkhorse Productions,
was caught up in the union's 1988 strike against the television and
motion picture industry.
   He said the guild did not serve Darkhorse with a 60-day notice
of intent to strike as required by law, and he refused to
participate in what he termed ``the unlawful strike against
Darkhorse.''
   The lawsuit contends the union launched a deliberate campaign to
harass and punish Trudeau, a guild member, for his association with
Darkhorse and his refusal to participate in the strike.
   Marty Waldman, a spokesman for the union, said it would have no
comment until its lawyers reviewed the suit.
   The suit was filed Tuesday in U.S. District Court.
