<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 0320EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-S&amp;Ls-Wall     11-02 0713</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls-Wall,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wall Answers Critics With Complaint of Unfair Attacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal savings and loan regulator M. Danny
Wall says his congressional critics aren't giving him a fair chance
to respond to charges he mishandled the nation's largest thrift
institution failure.
   ``Fair play clearly has not been evident, much less due
process,'' he said Wednesday in an interview at his office a block
from the White House.
   The House Banking Committee is investigating the collapse of
Lincoln Savings and Loan Association, an Irvine, Calif., thrift
controlled by Phoenix, Ariz., millionaire Charles H. Keating Jr.
   In three hearings, the committee has collected reams of
testimony critical of Wall's handling of the collapse, which is
expected to cost taxpayers between $1.5 billion and $2 billion,
making it the nation's costliest S&amp;L failure.
   Committee aides say the panel will hear from Wall later this
month. But a firm date hasn't been set and Wall said he is
concerned public opinion will harden and Congress may even recess
until next year before he gets a chance to tell his side of the
story.
   ``The public sees silence as being an admission of guilt. ... I
clearly ... will be eager to respond to every question that is
asked,'' Wall said.
   The committee is focusing on why Wall, as chairman of the
Federal Home Loan Bank Board _ now called the Office of Thrift
Supervision _ rejected a 1987 recommendation from his agency's San
Francisco office to take over Lincoln and instead ordered a second
examination, supervised by regulators from Washington, which
delayed the seizure of the institution until this April.
   Michael Patriarca, director of the thrift agency's San Francisco
office, and William K. Black, counsel in the office, told the
committee they had uncovered sufficient losses and irregularities
at Lincoln to justify its seizure two years ago.
   However, Wall said the San Francisco examiners only had enough
information to justify an order restricting some of Lincoln's
activities. The new examination supervised by different regulators
avoided a lawsuit blocking access to records of Lincoln's parent
company, American Continental Corp., he said.
   And the second examination eventually produced the evidence
needed by the government to seize the S&amp;L, Wall said.
   ``It's absolutely crystal clear what would have occurred other
than our having used the approach of a clean set of examiners. We
may have been delayed further,'' he said.
   Wall called Patriarca a ``very competent regulator'' and noted
he had recently reappointed him. But asked why he did not dismiss
him for presenting what he considered one-sided testimony to the
House panel, Wall said, ``We will consider all of what needs to be
considered at an appropriate time.''
   ``I'm not threatening anybody,'' he said. ``I'm clearly not
rushing to judgment just as I don't want anyone to rush to judgment
on me.''
   Patriarca has complained that Wall, without informing examiners
in San Francisco, met with Keating three times. Wall said the
sessions did not influence his thinking, but conceded, ``It's very
difficult to prove the negative.''
   He also said he was unimpressed that Keating was able to
persuade two senators and a member of the House Banking Committee
to intervene on behalf of Lincoln.
   ``I'm not blase about senators, don't misunderstand me,'' Wall
said. ``On the other hand, I'm not impressed by the fact that
someone can talk to X number of senators.''
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., called Wall soon after he began a
four-year term as the nation's top thrift regulator in July 1987,
after leaving a post as chief Republican aide on the Senate Banking
Committee. Cranston was attempting to prod the agency into deciding
whether or not to take action against Lincoln.
   Early this year, Cranston, Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., and
Rep. Carroll Hubbard, D-Ky., called to urge speedy consideration of
Keating's proposal to sell Lincoln, he said.
   Cranston and DeConcini are among five senators who received
large campaign contributions from Keating.
   Wall brushed off a call from the chairman of the House
committee, Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas, to step aside, saying
he wanted to see his agency through its reorganization as a wing of
the Treasury Department
   ``I have a job to do here, I believe, and I want to see it
through,'' he said.
</TEXT>
