<FIRST>r a PM-Ortega-NYTimes     11-02 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ortega-NYTimes,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ortega, in New York Times, Insists Elections Will Be Held</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaragua's President Daniel Ortega says in an
article on the Op-Ed page of today's New York Times that President
Bush has blocked all efforts to demobilize and disarm the Contras.
   ``He has kept the Contras intact militarily by continuing to
provide them with non-lethal assistance,'' Ortega writes.
   And, concerning the presidential elections scheduled in
Nicaragua in February, Ortega says:
   ``I shall continue doing everything I can to insure that the
current electoral process remains democratic and that, as in 1984,
our elections are judged free and fair by the international
observers.''
   He said Bush delivered a ``torrent of personal invective''
against him at the meeting of hemispheric leaders in Costa Rica
last week.
   ``He accused me of spoiling the `garden party' in Costa Rica''
by announcing he would end the cease-fire, Ortega said. ``Well,
life in my country is no `garden party,''' he continued. ``Eight
years of war financed and directed by the Reagan and Bush
adminstrations have seen to that.''
   Ortega defended his decision to cancel the cease-fire, saying
the Contras had stepped-up their military activity, threatening the
election process.
   The only way to achieve peace in Nicaragua is to disband the
U.S.-supported rebels, he wrote.
   ``We do not consider it an acceptable cease-fire when we cease
and the Contras fire,'' he said.
