<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     11-02 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up In Tokyo, Stocks Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar gained strength against the Japanese yen
today, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange declined.
   The dollar closed at 143.75 yen, up 0.67 yen from Wednesday's
143.08-yen finish. It opened higher at 143.93 yen and ranged
between 143.65 yen and 144.15 yen.
   The U.S. currency's higher opening in Tokyo followed a similar
uptrend on overseas markets overnight, traders said.
   ``But the dollar didn't rise much after surpassing the 144-yen
mark, when the majority of market players became cautious about
buying ahead of the (release of) the U.S. jobless rate report and a
three-day-weekend,'' said Masafumi Koyama, a Bank of Tokyo trader.
   ``Japanese investors wanted to figure out whether the dollar was
in a continuous uptrend or its recent strength has been just a
temporary movement,'' he said.
   Japanese financial markets will be closed for Culture Day, a
national holiday, Friday.
   On the stock exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost
69.57 points, or 0.20 percent, closing at 35,494.86. It gained
14.99 points Wednesday.
   The index, which lost 139.93 points at the end of morning
trading, erased some of its early losses in the afternoon on
bargain hunting, dealers said.
   ``The yen's weakness largely discouraged investors,'' said
Masahiro Umemori, a Nomura Securities Co. analyst.
   Many investors remained on the sidelines awaiting the U.S.
jobless figures, he said.
   Trading was moderate, with an estimated 800 million shares
changing hands, down from Wednesday's 900 million.
</TEXT>
