<FIRST>r w PM-SovietCutbacks     11-02 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Cutbacks,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Appear to be Fulfilling Eastern Europe Pledge, Aspin Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the House Armed Services
Committee says Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev appears to be
carrying out his pledge to make sizeable cuts in Soviet forces in
Eastern Europe.
   But Rep. Les. Aspin, D-Wis., added that Soviet forces have also
increased artillery strength in Eastern Europe. Gorbachev has said
8,500 artillery pieces would be cut from eastern Europe and
adjacent Soviet territory.
   It is still not certain Gorbachev will fulfill a promise to
reduce Soviet troops overall by half a million men, Aspin said
Wednesday night.
   ``We don't see that yet,'' Aspin said at the Carnegie Endowment
for International Peace, a private research group. ``It's just hard
for us to understand when they will do that.''
   Gorbachev, in a speech last December at the United Nations,
promised to withdraw six tank divisions from East Germany,
Czechoslovakia, and Hungary within two years and reduce Soviet
forces in the Warsaw Pact countries by 50,000 men.
   He said the Soviet Union would also reduce the overall size of
its armed forces by 500,000 men.
   ``A lot of unanswered questions remain about the force
reductions west of the Urals (within Soviet territory). But the
rest of the reductions seem to be taking place,'' Aspin said.
   Aspin said three of the six tank divisions have been withdrawn
from eastern Europe and ``a big chunk'' of the troops left with
them.
   He said the pullout contradicts ``the general impression that
we're still waiting for something to happen.''
   However, Aspin said, the Soviets have also increased their other
military vehicles in Eastern Europe by about 20 percent and were
adding more than 1,000 artillery pieces, or a boost of about 15
percent.
   ``The net result of all of that is that the capability of their
forces in Eastern Europe would be reduced on the order of 20
percent'' by December 1990. ``That's on track and irreversible,''
he said.
   Aspin and other members of the Armed Services Committee went on
a two-week trip to the Soviet Union and East Germany in August.
   ``He's halfway delivered in half of the time,'' Aspin said of
Gorbachev, who will meet with President Bush in a summit meeting
off the Mediterranean island of Malta Dec. 2-3.
</TEXT>
