<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     11-02 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>HUD Report: McGann Broke Agency's Rules of Conduct</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Housing and Urban
Development has concluded that the former acting administrator of
HUD's New York regional office violated the agency's standards of
conduct by voting on HUD programs as a trustee of Island Park, N.Y.
   The internal case against Geraldine McGann has been closed and
she has been reassigned to a lower-level job at HUD headquarters in
Washington, according to a HUD audit and other documents obtained
under the Freedom of Information Act.
   HUD spokesman Jack Flynn said Wednesday that McGann continues to
be paid the same salary she made as regional administrator, $68,500
a year.
   The internal investigation of McGann stemmed from her dual role
as a HUD employee and a trustee of the village of Island Park, Long
Island. Minutes of the Island Park board meetings indicated that
McGann voted on HUD-related resolutions from 1982 to 1989, a
violation of HUD's code of conduct.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Toy Retailer Recalls Crib Play Sets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of crib play sets sold nationwide
are being voluntarily recalled by a toy retailer because small
parts of the sets may pose a potential choking hazard for young
children.
   Toys `R' Us is recalling 15,000 Crib Pals ``Play Shapes'' sets
because the small shapes fail to meet the Consumer Product Safety
Commission's mandatory standard for baby rattles, the commission
said Wednesday.
   The sets are imported from Taiwan and marked SKN 157198. They
contain four plastic pieces _ one is a circle with a ball that
rattles _ in different shapes and colors.
   The play sets, which were sold nationwide for ages 1 and up
during 1988 and 1989, are considered a rattle and must satisfy a
more stringent choking standard than items classified as toys.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Bush to Give Occasional Radio Interviews</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will start giving occasional
interviews to radio reporters, the White House says.
   Bush intends to give the radio interviews on Friday afternoons,
but it will be up to the participating outlet when the broadcast
airs, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Wednesday.
   It will be ``not every week, but occasionally,'' he added.
   The interviews will be with radio reporters who regularly cover
the White House, Fitzwater said.
   Bush has given numerous one-on-one interviews with newspapers in
his first 10 months in office, but had not made a habit of granting
radio interviews.
