<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 0442EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-VaGovernor     11-02 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Va Governor,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coleman Challenges Wilder to Showdown at Capitol</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   L. Douglas Wilder, vying to become the
nation's first black elected governor, and opponent J. Marshall
Coleman began an intense new round of character attacks less than a
week before the gubernatorial election.
   Wilder, a Democrat and the state's lieutenant governor, released
a television commercial Wednesday accusing Coleman, a Republican
former attorney general, of ``not telling the truth'' about
abortion, a key issue in the race.
   Coleman, who trailed Wilder by 15 percentage points in a recent
poll, challenged Wilder to a showdown at the Capitol today to
explain why he ``directly and shamelessly'' misled voters about his
position on a state law banning compulsory union membership.
   The candidates have raised questions throughout the campaign
about each other's fitness for office, but both were more pointed
in the latest exchange. Wilder's TV advertisement shows a portion
of a Coleman ad that began airing Tuesday, a week before the
election. In the portion of the ad, Coleman says, ``Let's set the
record straight. I'm not going to restrict abortions for rape or
incest.''
   The Wilder ad goes on to say that Coleman, an abortion opponent
except to save the life of the mother, has long campaigned on a
pledge to ban the procedure and repeated the promise earlier this
year in a letter to a group of clergymen.
   ``Marshall Coleman is not telling the truth about abortion,''
Wilder's ad says. ``That's why we just can't trust Marshall
Coleman.''
   In a letter, Coleman challenged Wilder to show up this afternoon
at the Capitol to listen to a tape recording of a private meeting
between Wilder and United Mine Workers.
   At the July 31 meeting, Wilder said he supported a
``free-rider'' amendment to Virginia's right-to-work law. The law
forbids labor contracts requiring workers to join a union, but the
amendment could force non-union employees to pay dues to unions
that negotiate agreements for them.
   Coleman contends the amendment would gut the right-to-work law.
He wrote Wilder that he would play the tape for reporters today
whether Wilder showed up or not.
   ``Either way, the people of Virginia are going to know how
directly and shamelessly you tried to deceive them,'' Coleman wrote.
   B.J. Northington, Wilder's deputy press secretary, said Wilder
had no plans to meet Coleman at the Capitol.
   ``It's just another negative attack,'' Ms. Northington said.
   Wilder, at a meeting with Richmond business leaders, pledged to
keep the right-to-work law ``as it is'' and to veto any effort to
weaken it.
   ``I don't go one place and say one thing and another place and
say another,'' Wilder said. He said the remark at the UMW meeting
did not contradict his position of support for the law _ and he
said that support left the miners ``very upset with me.''
</TEXT>
