<FIRST>r p PM-NYCMayoral     11-02 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NYC Mayoral,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Candidates to Debate as Polls Show Dinkins with 11 and 13-Point Lead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAUL REYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With less than a week to go before the mayoral
election, Democrat David Dinkins and Republican Rudolph Giuliani
have agreed to face each other in at least two televised
appearances.
   The appearances, one of which is billed as a debate, were
announced Wednesday and include a third, lesser-known candidate
whose participation Dinkins had insisted upon.
   While the candidates were negotiating on other possible joint
appearances, a poll of registered voters published in New York
Newsday today showed Dinkins leads Giuliani by 11 points _ 49-38
percent.
   Another poll showed Dinkins was favored over the former U.S.
attorney 47-34 percent. The survey was released by Barry Feinstein,
Teamsters Local 237 president and a strong Dinkins backer.
   Giuliani's consent to let Right to Life candidate Henry Hewes
join in the debate marked a victory for Dinkins, who had insisted
that all candidates be allowed to participate in a debate if they
chose.
   The decision by the Giuliani campaign to allow the inclusion of
other candidates came after a debate Wednesday in which Dinkins and
Hewes participated. Giuliani was represented on the stage by an
empty chair.
   Asked why he had changed his mind, Giuliani said:
   ``In order to make certain that these issues got out before the
public, we're going to do it on his terms. And, we're going to
show, even on his terms, that this man is not qualified to be mayor
of this city.''
   Also today, Giuliani picked up an endorsement from the New York
Post, in an editorial in today's editions. Dinkins was endorsed
Wednesday by Newsday and The Village Voice.
