<FIRST>r p PM-NewHavenMayoral     11-02 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-New Haven Mayoral,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Frontrunner Fights Complacency in Bid to Become First Black Mayor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state senator heavily favored to
become this city's first black mayor is battling voter complacency
rather than his tough-talking opponent as he strives to fulfill a
20-year-old dream.
   Sen. John Daniels said his easy victory in the Democratic
primary, over a candidate who had won the party's endorsement,
electrified his supporters but also left many with the mistaken
impression that the race was over.
   ``I was out in a neighborhood the other day and when I knocked
on the door, a woman answered, `Senator Daniels, you again? Didn't
we just vote you into office? We have to do that again?'
   ``A lot of people think I'm already the mayor. There is a lot of
apathy out there,'' Daniels said in a recent interview as his
campaign staff prepared for a final get-out-the-vote push.
   Apathy was not a problem on primary day, when 53 percent of the
city's registered Democrats voted, the highest turnout in 10 years.
Daniels scored well in all but a few wards to defeat former city
administrator John DeStefano in the race to succeed retiring
five-term Mayor Biagio DiLieto.
   Democrats outnumber Republicans by nearly 10-to-1 in this city
of 127,000, where blacks make up about 35 percent and Hispanics
about 12 percent of the population.
   Daniels, 53, is a five-term state senator and former city
alderman with a majority interest in a New Haven plumbing business.
A former high school football standout who went to Villanova on an
athletic scholarship, he is still active in sports as a college
football referee.
   His Republican opponent is Alderwoman Robie Pooley, who says the
senator is more interested in making history as the first black
mayor of Connecticut's third largest city than in committing
himself to working full time in the job.
   When Daniels suggested early on that he might want to hold on to
his Senate seat while serving as mayor _ only to learn later that
it was not legally possible _ he showed he did not appreciate the
``the totality of the job,'' she said.
   Daniels said he will retain his financial stake in the plumbing
company but will not work at the business. He has no intention of
giving up his job as a referee, which requires him to work 10 games
a year.
   ``It doesn't interfere with my governing the city,'' he said,
adding, ``some mayors go out and play golf every day.''
</TEXT>
