<HEAD>Misplaced Note Led to Murder Charge Against Methodist Pastor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ELLAVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A preacher admitted killing his first wife
when police questioned him about a crumpled note allegedly
describing plans to kill his second wife, authorities said.
   James P. Chastain was arrested after his wife, Luanne Chastain,
found the note in their bedroom. It contained notes on how he
planned to kill his wife, an ordained minister, said Georgia Bureau
of Investigation agent Ed Ricks.
   She alerted authorities who arrested her husband and charged him
with burglary and arson in a fire Oct. 13 at his sister-in-law's
house.
   Then Colquitt County Sheriff Billy Howell began questioning him
about a 1979 mobile home fire in which Teresa Chastain died.
   ``He owned up to it. He said his wife was asleep in the trailer
when he set fire to it,'' Howell said.
   Chastain was charged Oct. 24 with murder in his first wife's
death.
   Teresa Chastain was planning to leave her husband after four
years of marriage when she died in the fire, said her sister Doris
Griffin. The fire had been ruled accidental.
   Chastain served four months in prison for breaking into a
neighbor's mobile home and stealing a gun in 1982.
   ``When he went to prison, he said he found Jesus,'' said his
mother, Beatrice Chastain of Moultrie.
   He entered the United Methodist ministry in 1984.
   As an unordained lay minister, he served as pastor of small
congregations in southern Georgia, usually three or four at a time.
   His wife, an ordained United Methodist minister, was pastor of
Berlin and Wesley Chapel churches in southern Colquitt County.
   ``When they first came here, he spoke to the men's club and said
he had served time in prison,'' said Jeanette Layfield of the
Kimball United Methodist Church, where Mrs. Chastain was the pastor
for a time. ``He also told them about having his wife die in a
fire.''
   He met his second wife in 1984 when she was suffering from a
back injury and she asked him to preach for her at a church where
she was pastor.
</TEXT>
