<FIRST>r a PM-GulfPower     11-02 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gulf Power,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Widow of Utility Executive Files Wrongful Death Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The widow of a Gulf Power Co. executive
killed in a mysterious plane crash has filed a wrongful death
lawsuit against a related company that owned the aircraft.
   Frances W. Horton filed the suit against Southern Company
Services Inc. on Wednesday, a day after Gulf Power pleaded guilty
to federal charges of conspiring to make illegal political
contributions.
   Gulf Power officials and federal prosecutors said the
contributions were arranged by her husband, Jacob ``Jake'' Horton,
the utility's senior vice president.
   The defendant company and Gulf Power are subsidiaries of the
Atlanta-based Southern Co.
   Horton died April 10 in the crash that also killed two Southern
Company pilots from Mississippi within minutes after it took off
from Pensacola Regional Airport en route to Atlanta.
   The suit alleges that Southern Company and the pilots were
negligent in maintaining and operating the aircraft.
   The crash's cause officially remains under investigation, but
the National Transportation Safety Board has determined a fire
broke out in the cabin before the crash.
   The suit alleges the fire resulted from negligent maintenance
and operation of the airplane and directly contributed to the crash.
   The pilots allegedly failed to properly respond to the fire and
lost control of the plane, causing the crash, according to the suit.
   Federal investigators say they have reached no conclusions on
the causes of either the fire or the crash.
   No dollar amount is specified in the suit, but it demands
compensation for the Mrs. Horton's loss of her husband's support,
services, compansionship and protection, funeral costs and her
mental pain and suffering.
   Horton was told that a Gulf Power audit committee had
recommended his dismissal just hours before the crash. Before
boarding the plane, Horton told his lawyer that he thought he was a
target of a federal grand jury in Atlanta that was investigating
Gulf Power.
   Gulf Power also pleaded guilty to impeding the Internal Revenue
Service and paid a $500,000 fine as part of a plea bargain. The
pleas were entered in U.S. District Court in Atlanta.
   Utility officials and federal prosecutors said that Horton
orchestrated the scheme in which Gulf Power vendors would make
contributions to politicians and submit phony invoices to the
utility to obtain the money.
   However, an attorney who previously represented Gulf Power,
accused the utility and the federal government of using Horton as a
scapegoat.
   Fred Levin, a lawyer in Pensacola, said the plea agreement was a
gutless move designed to justify a costly federal investigation and
to draw attention from the utility onto the deceased executive.
   ``There's no question he (Horton) is taking the blame,'' Levin
said. ``He has no choice because he can't talk back.''
   Carter Haynes, a Gulf Power spokesman, expressed surprise at
Levin's reaction. And U.S. Attorney Robert L. Barr Jr. of Atlanta
said Horton was not being blamed unjustly, saying the government
had a substantial amount of evidence against him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
