<HEAD>Arctic Air Sends Temperatures Plummeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   An arctic air mass left snow and subzero wind chill readings
today as it crossed from the northern Plains into the southern
Plains.
   Temperatures were in the 60s and 70s ahead of the cold front on
Wednesday; behind it, readings were in the teens this morning.
Northerly winds gusting to 40 mph ushered cold air into Texas.
   Light snow and flurries continued today in parts of North
Dakota, Minnesota and Wisconsin. Strong northerly winds continued
to send cold air into the central Plains region and the middle
Mississippi Valley.
   Showers and thunderstorms were in southeastern Texas and also
extended across southern Louisiana into southern Mississippi.
   Southern California and western Arizona had strong and gusty
winds. A wind advisory was posted for today for the mountains of
Southern California and for areas below Cajon Pass.
   High temperatures Wednesday were mostly in the 30s from the
northern and central Rocky Mountain region to the upper Mississippi
Valley and remained below freezing across North Dakota.
   Temperatures warmed above 70 degrees in the southern Atlantic
Coast region, with 80s in much of Florida. It warmed above 70
degrees across most of California and southern Arizona, with 80s in
southern California and southwest Arizona.
   The nation's high Wednesday was 88 at Fort Myers, Fla., Miami
and San Gabriel, Calif.
