<FIRST>r i PM-CocaineSeizure     11-02 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cocaine Seizure,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexican Police Arrest Suspected Smuggler in Record U.S. Cocaine Seizure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CIUDAD JUAREZ, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities said they arrested the
leader of a ring that smuggled 60 tons of cocaine into the United
States during the past year, including a record 21 tons seized near
Los Angeles.
   At least 50 federal police officers stormed a downtown motel
Wednesday and arrested Rafael Munoz Talavera. But a half-hour after
later, his attorneys served federal officials with a court order
restraining police action against their client.
   Federal prosecutor Rolando Aguilera said the order required that
authorities release Munoz, who lives in this border city, by this
afternoon unless he is formally charged with a crime.
   On Sept. 28, U.S. officials seized 21.4 tons of cocaine at a
suburban Los Angeles warehouse in what authorities called the
world's largest cocaine seizure ever. Officials also raided six
warehouses in El Paso, Texas, believed to have been a staging area
for the cocaine.
   Six men have been arrested in the United States in connection
with the case and all have pleaded innocent to drug charges. One of
the six identified Munoz as the mastermind of the smuggling
operation, authorities said.
   Munoz had been hiding out three days at Motel Colonial Las
Fuentes, federal police said.
   According to the court order, the suspect's relatives claim that
Juarez police were about to fly Munoz to Mexico City for
prosecution.
   The order blocked such action, Aguilera said.
   Earlier this week, Mexican officials seized Restaurant Florida,
a popular restaurant in Ciudad Juarez owned by Munoz.
</TEXT>
