<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     11-02 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Steady, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was steady against most major foreign
currencies in quiet European trading today and dealers said they
expect little movement before Friday's release of the latest U.S.
unemployment figures.
   Gold prices were higher.
   Dealers said the market is looking to October's unemployment
data for additional clues about the strength of the U.S. economy.
   ``If the data show the economy is sluggish, we can see some
activity,'' said one trader in Rome.
   Traders said the dollar was holding steady despite reports that
the Bank of Japan sold dollars, presumably about $100 million, when
the U.S. currency was trading around 143.85 yen.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.67 yen to a closing 143.75 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at a lower rate of 143.39 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Wednesday:
   _1.8475 West German marks, up from 1.8377
   _1.6210 Swiss francs, down from 1.6132
   _6.2675 French francs, up from 6.2305
   _2.0867 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0790
   _1,355.00 Italian lire, up from 1,348.50
   _$1.1725 Canadian, down from $1.1742
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.5662 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.5815 late Wednesday.
Dealers said the pound fell on reports that a senior member of the
government was involved in insider trading.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $373.60 a troy ounce,
down from late Wednesday's $374.25. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a higher recommended price of $373.85.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $373.65, up from $373.40 late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $.12 to close at a bid $374.04.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.17 a troy
ounce, down from Wednesday's $5.18.
</TEXT>
