<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 0647EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e BC-Theater 1stLd-Writethru a0808 11-02 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0808,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Sid Caesar &amp; Company' Opens on Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS four grafs on critics' reviews; no PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Sid Caesar &amp; Company: Does Anybody Know What
I'm Talking About,'' a Broadway revue starring the legendary
television comedian, is mostly Caesar but not much company.
   The show is a collection of hit-and-miss sketches that look and
sound as if they would play better on a 10-inch Philco than at the
Golden Theater _ which is where the revue opened Wednesday night.
   The skits, uncredited in the program, are designed to show off
Caesar's unique talent at mime, mimicry and general comic lunacy.
Occasionally, they succeed.
   It's fun to watch Caesar portray a gum machine that evolves into
a slot machine and eventually is demoted to a towel machine in a
men's room. He also does a pretty fair impersonation of a baby,
complete with whines, tantrums, coos and burps.
   He's dandy at playing a mortally wounded Jewish matador in a
scene reminiscent of his big dying number, ``Goodbye,'' in the
musical ``Little Me.'' But there is no overall form to the evening.
At the beginning of the show, Caesar, looking remarkably relaxed
and fit, announces that his favorite type of comedy is rooted in
truth. The ``truths'' that follow meander from obvious jokes about
a man's thoughts as he walks down the aisle on his wedding day to
an overlong argument between husband and wife mimed to the first
movement of Beethoven's Fifth Symphony.
   Caesar also resurrects his German professor, who spritzes the
audience with double talk and a variety of accents, dialects and
languages. He plays the same love scene in German, Italian and
Japanese. And the results are equally hilarious.
   The large supporting cast _ seven players in all _ has little to
do except occupy the stage during Caesar's brief costume changes.
Director Martin Charnin injects a little fizz into their interludes
by giving them some peppy but nondescript revue tunes to cover up
Caesar's brief absences.
   The production designs by Neil Peter Jampolis are meager and
unnecessary, looking as if they were an afterthought, added only to
spruce up the show for its move to Broadway after a run of several
months at a Greenwich Village nightclub.
   Caesar has not had much luck on Broadway during his long career.
``Little Me'' was a wonderful show with a terrific score by Cy
Coleman and Carolyn Leigh, but it ran only about six months. His
last appearance on Broadway was in the flop comedy ``Four on a
Garden'' in 1971. The man has always been better than his material.
   You are better off renting a videotape of ``Ten from `Your Show
of Shows,''' a collection of his best television sketches with
Imogene Coca, Carl Reiner and Howard Morris. On Broadway, the
mighty Caesar is again in a mouse of a show.
   In other reviews, critics generally praised Caesar but rejected
the show's length and attempt at being a review.
   The New York Times' Frank Rich said Caesar was in fine form but
there was ``good reason to worry about his show, for it is so
misconceived that it turns the guest of honor into a beggar at his
own feast.''
   Leo Seligsohn of New York Newsday said ``although the show makes
for and uneven evening, when it's good, it's very, very good.''
   Don Nelson of the Daily News called the show ``uneven,'' and
despite a solid supporting cast, ``disappointing.'' The New York
Post's Clive Barnes was more charitable, saying Caesar is a
``clowning genius'' who could have used better material.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891102-0060 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 0724EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-JessicaMcClure 1stLd-Writethru a0431 11-02 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jessica McClure, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0431,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jessica McClure Steals Spotlight From Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts dates of incidents in top 2 grafs and graf 13, Mrs.
McClure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jessica McClure, the toddler pulled from an
abandoned well two years ago as the nation watched rescuers
struggle for 58 hours, is now 3 years old and capable of stealing
the spotlight from even President Bush.
   Bush scooped the Midland, Texas, girl into his arms Wednesday
during a White House ceremony honoring Sioux City, Iowa, for its
response to the crash of a United Airlines jumbo jet last July 19.
   Jessica grabbed Bush's glasses off his face and faced the
clicking cameras with them balanced on her nose.
   Even as he walked into the Roosevelt Room to present the Midland
Community Spirit Award to Sioux City, Jessica did not appear
impressed.
   ``Who's that, mama?'' asked the blue-eyed girl in a red corduroy
smock with Winnie the Pooh on the front, tossing her ponytail.
   Later, as she returned his glasses to Bush's breast pocket,
Jessica discovered the president's white handkerchief.
   ``This may make that _ what do you call it? _ the blooper of the
week,'' said the president after Jessica tried to drape the
handkerchief over his head and dabbed his nose.
   ``I'm sorry about that. You can go to your mother,'' he said,
laughing and handing the wriggling girl to her mother, 20-year-old
Reba ``Cissy'' McClure.
   After paying tribute to Sioux City as an example of his
``thousand points of lights'' volunteerism, Bush said, ``Thank you
all and as for you, Jessica, where's my handkerchief?''
   And as the audience howled, Bush asked: ``How old are you now?''
   She held up three fingers.
   ``C'mon Jessica. You want to see where I work?'' Bush said, and
the two, with her parents trailing behind, bounded off to the Oval
Office.
   Mrs. McClure said the Oct. 16, 1987 rescue of her daughter, who
was 18 months old at the time, was similar to the rescue of
passengers trapped inside Flight 232.
   ``Everybody pulled together to save the people,'' she said.
``There were people trapped in that plane and couldn't get out _
mothers and fathers and children and they couldn't find them. And
that's exactly how I felt _ I was running through the back yard
looking for my child and I couldn't find her.''
   Mayor Carroll Thomas said the Midland Community Spirit Award
would be given annually to recognize ``the community that best
exemplifies volunteerism and compassion and concern for their
fellow citizens.''
   There were 85 entries for the award, with the words: ``Nothing
the heart gives away is gone; it is kept in the hearts of others''
around a bronze reproduction of a plaque at Midland's civic center
that shows rescuers bringing Jessica out of the well.
   The United DC-10 crashed in Sioux City after its rear engine
disintegrated in flight, severing the plane's hydraulic system and
making it virtually impossible to control. The crew almost landed
the plane, but it crashed on the runway, killing 112 people.
Another 184 passengers survived.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
