<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 0739EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     11-02 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Gets Shoot-on-Sight Orders Against Armed Tamils</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government troops have been ordered to
shoot on sight anyone carrying arms in areas being vacated by
Indian peacekeeping troops, the foreign minister said today.
   Young Tamils armed with AK-47 assault rifles and wearing
military-style uniforms have been seen in such areas.
   Indian troops, who are scheduled to leave Sri Lanka by the end
of December, withdrew from one such area, the east coast's Ampara
district, last week.
   Foreign Minister Ranjan Wijeratne spoke to reporters at a weekly
Cabinet briefing, where he was asked whether a ``Tamil national
army'' had been armed and trained by the departing Indian soldiers.
   ``We do not believe this Tamil army exists, but if they do, they
are strongly advised to surrender their arms to law enforcement
authorities without further delay,'' said Wijeratne, who is also
deputy defense minister.
   ``If they do not, they will be destroyed by Sri Lankan armed
forces and police wherever they are found,'' he added.
   The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, the most powerful of the
Tamil militant groups in northern and eastern Sri Lanka, issued a
statement Tuesday claiming: ``Under the pretext of defending the
Tamils and Moslem people, the Indian government is organizing an
army of cronies.''
   The Tigers are engaged in a power struggle with other Tamil
groups that have been friendly with India.
   A spokesman for the Indian High Commission, or embassy, denied
Indian troops had trained anyone other than a civil volunteer force
that is supposed to help Sri Lankan police. He spoke on condition
of anonymity.
   An Associated Press reporter who visited eastern Sri Lanka last
week saw trucks loaded with young armed Tamils heading out of
Batticaloa on the road to Ampara.
   Local Tamil militant leaders said the youths were part of a
militia that claims 10,000 recruits and is separate from the
civilian volunteer force. They said the militia was needed to
ensure that the Tamil-dominated provincial council is given the
powers promised it by the central government.
   Indian troops were sent to northeastern Sri Lanka in July 1987
to enforce a peace plan designed to end a separatist war by
guerrillas from the Tamil minority. Since then, more than 1,100
Indian soldiers have been killed in ambushes and battles with
Tamils who refused to surrender their weapons.
   The Sri Lankan government, which is dominated by the Sinhalese
majority, has been trying to work out a peace agreement with the
Tamil Tigers.
   Tamils make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people and
are mostly Hindus. Sinhalese account for 75 percent of the
population and are mostly Buddhists.
   India got involved in the internal affairs of its small island
neighbor through its role as the region's biggest power and the
sympathies of its own politically powerful minority of 60 million
Tamils for their Sri Lankan brethren.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
