<FIRST>r a PM-PSNHBankruptcy     11-02 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-PSNH Bankruptcy,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Utility Withdraws Bid for Lead Seabrook Owner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Massachusetts utility has withdrawn a $2 billion
offer for the financially troubled Public Service Company of New
Hampshire and its share of the stalled Seabrook nuclear plant.
   John Rowe, president of New England Electric System, said
Wednesday that other utilities' competing bids and the rates that
would be needed to support those offers are too high.
   Public Service, New Hampshire's largest power company with
nearly 400,000 customers, owns 36 percent, the single largest
share, of Seabrook. The plant is fighting for a license as its
price climbs, standing now at about $6.3 billion.
   Emergency planning obstacles contributed to delays at the plant,
which originally was scheduled for commercial operation 10 years
ago, and sent the utility into bankruptcy protection in 1988.
   The other bidders for PSNH are United Illuminating Co. of New
Haven, Conn., and Northeast Utilities of Hartford, Conn. United
Illuminating has offered a bid it values at $2.29 billion.
Northeast Utilities bid $2.25 billion.
   New Hampshire Gov. Judd Gregg had endorsed the offer by New
England Electric. On Wednesday he said he hoped another bidder
would meet the state's criteria of sound management, adequate
electricity supply and affordable rates.
   ``I still feel there are enough players at the table to meet
those criteria, and we're still working very hard with those
players ... to reach that sort of agreement,'' he said.
