<HEAD>Ballet Dancers Getting Poison Pen Letters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dancers of the State Ballet of Rhode Island
have been receiving phony letters telling them to quit for being
fat, old or disruptive, and the artistic director blames another
dance company.
   Police said Wednesday they were checking fingerprints on the
letters, which are typed on stationery resembling the ballet
company's and bear artistic director Herci Marsden's forged
signature.
   ``This is more than a prank,'' said Detective David S. Ethier.
``It's (Marsden's) business and personal reputation that has a
chance of being destroyed.''
   Marsden charged that another dance company that she would not
identify sent the poison pen letters in an attempt to steal her
dancers.
   Ethier said police had no suspects but did not believe anyone in
Marsden's company was sending the letters.
   The letters ordered the dancers to quit for reasons ranging from
being overweight to being too old. One letter to an 11-year-old
apprentice accused her of being disruptive.
   ``You are upsetting my girls and causing trouble in my school
and in the ballet company,'' the letter said. ``Your family is also
upsetting people. You are not to return here.''
   Marsden said a 20-year-old ballerina quit after receiving a
letter, despite Marsden's insistence it was phony.
   About a dozen apprentices and members of Marsden's 30-year-old
semiprofessional dance company received the letters, postmarked in
Providence Sept. 4.
   The non-profit company has 50 to 60 dancers. Only guest artists
and principal dancers get paid.
   Marsden said that she has dismissed one dancer in five years and
that if she has a complaint, company members ``have to face me and
I tell them to their faces what they have to do.''
   ``But I'm a very easy person to live with,'' she said.
</TEXT>
