<DOCNO> AP891102-0068 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 0933EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon     11-02 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Security Arrangements for Presidential Election Completed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lebanese policemen and Algerian military
observers will form a one-mile security zone around Parliament
headquarters this week to protect lawmakers electing a new
president, an Arab League envoy said today.
   Arrangements call for a safe area around the Villa Mansour in
the area of of Beirut's dividing Green Line, which separates Moslem
and Christian forces, envoy Lakhdar Ibrahimi was quoted as saying
by the independent newspaper An-Nahar.
   A police spokesman, who cannot be named in line with
regulations, said police will begin patrolling Friday evening.
   Parliament speaker Hussein Husseini, defying opposition from
Christian leader Gen. Michel Aoun, summoned the 73 surviving
legislators to three consecutive sessions Saturday.
   The first session will be to elect a new house speaker, the
second to ratify an Arab League-brokered peace plan to end the
nation's 14-year-old civil war and the third to elect a new
president.
   The peace plan was worked out by 63 parliamentary deputies in 23
days of deliberations in Taif, Saudi Arabia, in October.
   The accord raises the 99 seats of the unicameral house to 108,
to be evenly distributed between Moslems and Christians; increases
the speaker's term to four years and strips the president of the
authority to appoint and dismiss prime ministers.
   Under the previous governing arrangement, the Christians held
the edge in political power.
   The plan also called for a partial Syrian military withdrawal
from Moslem west Beirut and its environs within two years.
   The peace plan, according to the constitution, must ratified by
a parliamentary session in Lebanon to become legally binding. But
it also must be accepted by the militia leaders to have any effect.
   Aoun, 54, a Maronite Christian, rejects the plan because it does
not include a clear timetable for the withdrawal of Syria's 40,000
troops.
   The accords, however, have won wide support in Lebanese and
international circles. Syria's Moslem and leftist allies said no
moves would be taken to obstruct its implementation.
   The permanent members of the U.N. Security Council _ Britian,
China, France, the Soviet Union and the United States _ have
praised the peace plan.
   Aoun, in a statement released by his press office today,
welcomed the statement issued by the five, terming it ``a positive
stand.''
   Aoun also urged President Bush to reconsider American policy on
Lebanon. He did not refer to specific elements he wanted changed.
   The United States has called the Taif accord a positive
development. It evacuated ambassador John McCarthy and 29 other
American diplomats from Lebanon Sept. 6 after saying security
around the embassy was inadequate.
   Aoun accuses the Syrians of betraying a 1976 peacekeeping
mandate from the 22-nation Arab League by siding with Moslems
against Christians in the civil war.
   Aoun, who heads an interim Christian military cabinet vying for
power with the Moslem government of acting Prime Minister Salim
Hoss, has threatened to dissolve Parliament to block implementation
of the peace plan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891102-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 0934EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ScarfoShot     11-02 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scarfo Shot,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigators Look at Gangster Son's Role in Mob</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators offered three possible motives
for the botched Halloween night shooting of a son of jailed mob
boss Nicodemo ``Little Nicky'' Scarfo _ revenge against the father
or battles for power or turf.
   Nicodemo Scarfo Jr., 24, was recuperating under police guard
today at Thomas Jefferson University Hospital after being shot by a
masked man as he dined at an Italian restaurant. Scarfo was knocked
out of his chair, falling face down in a pool of blood and tomato
sauce.
   Dr. Jerome Vernick, director of the hospital's trauma center,
said Scarfo was hit by at least four bullets, in the arm, behind
the ear, in the shoulder and in the chest. He said Scarfo was in
fair condition.
   Police said he may have been shot for revenge against the
failure of his father, who headed the Philadelphia-southern New
Jersey mob for nearly a decade, to keep his Mafia members from
becoming government informants.
   At least five already have given the authorities information
that has helped result in the convictions of the elder Scarfo and
about two dozen of his men on assorted charges, including
racketeering, murder and extortion.
   When the 60-year-old Scarfo was sentenced to 69 years in the
federal penitentiary at Marion, Ill., some sources said his middle
son, Nicodemo Jr., sought to take over his father's gambling and
loan sharking activities.
   Young Scarfo, known for his wraparound sunglasses and
slicked-back hair, was said by acquaintances to relish his
closeness to the mob throne.
   Louis Pichini of the U.S. Organized Crime Strike Force said
there were three possibilities of why young Scarfo was shot.
   ``One is that he could have been the victim of an internal
struggle to take over what was left of Scarfo's organization,''
Pichini said.
   ``Second, he could have been the victim of outside mob forces
from New York trying to move in and he was representative of the
existing group here, or what was left of it.
   ``And the third possibility is that those mobsters in New York
were upset about the number of defectors in the Philadelphia
organization and Scarfo's lack of control, and were retaliating
with a deadly message to show they didn't like it one bit.''
   A half-dozen police officers guarded Scarfo in the hospital.
</TEXT>
