<SECOND>PM-Doctor Indicted,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Physician Indicted on Illegal-Abortion Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANDERSON, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gynecologist accused of romancing three
patients and getting them pregnant has been indicted on charges he
performed or attempted abortions on them without their consent.
   Dr. Pravin D. Thakkar, 38, of Frankton _ who also faces several
lawsuits, professional ethics charges and federal financial charges
_ surrendered Wednesday, pleaded innocent and was freed on $100,000
bail.
   Defense attorney Jeffrey A. Lockwood said of the indictment, ``I
haven't read these. but I listened to the judge read them, and I'm
at a loss to find anything that's new in all of this.''
   Thakkar was indicted on charges including two counts of
performing illegal abortions and one of attempting to perform an
illegal abortion. He could receive up to 42{ years in prison if
convicted on all counts, said Prosecutor William Lawler Jr.
   Cathy D. Collins and Carmen Brutchen Hertzinger of Anderson had
accused Thakar of impregnating them and performing abortions on
them without their consent in 1988 and 1983 respectively.
   Prosecutors said he also got Bonnie Coffey-Myers of Indianapolis
pregnant and administered an injection intended to induce an
abortion in 1987. She aborted six days later.
   Thakkar was charged with attempting an abortion in that case.
   ``I think justice is being served,'' said Ms. Coffey-Myers. ``If
anything, I'm disappointed that more counts couldn't have been
handed down. But I'm hoping what was handed down was enough to put
him away for a while.''
   Allegations against Thakkar, a native of India who set up his
medical practice at Frankton in 1981, became public in February
when Collins and Hertzinger sued.
   That same month, nearly a dozen former patients went before the
state Medical Licensing Board with allegations of sexual misconduct
and abuse. The board has suspended his license.
   Thakkar goes on trial Monday on charges he violated financial
reporting requirements by withdrawing more than $132,000 from bank
accounts in chunks of just under $10,000.
   Transactions of $10,000 or more must be reported by financial
institutions to the IRS.
