<SECOND>PM-Obit-Blumberg,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former B'nai B'rith Official Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David M. Blumberg, a former president of the
Jewish fraternal organization B'nai B'rith International, died at a
Washington hospital Wednesday. He was 78.
   Blumberg, who moved from Knoxville, Tenn., to Washington eight
years ago, served as the B'nai B'rith president from 1970 to 1978.
He also was president of the National Association of Life
Underwriters from 1962 to 1963.
   In Knoxville, Blumberg served a member of the city council and
the chamber of commerce. From 1942 to 1945 he was a lieutenant in
the Navy.
   During his career, he was honored with a number of awards,
including the National Conference of Christian and Jews Brotherhood
award and the Sertoma Service to Mankind Award.
   ``He was a man without any pretentions of grandeur,'' Sidney H.
Closter, executive director of the B'nai B'rith, said today. ``He
dedicated himself to the community, especially the Jewish
community.''
   Blumberg was born in Forrest City, Ark., on July 6, 1911.
   He is survived by his wife, Janice; and a son, James R. Blumberg.
</TEXT>
