<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Journalist     11-02 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Journalist,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Raids Palestinian Journalist's Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian journalist who works for The New
York Times and the CBS television network said today that the army
raided his home and later tried to intimidate Arabs who work with
him.
   An army spokesman confirmed that troops raided the Gaza City
home of Taher Shriteh on Monday and seized material for a military
investigation. In addition to the American news media, Shriteh also
works for the London-based Reuters news agency.
   The spokesman, who cannot be named under military rules, said
the raid was conducted because ``prior information supports the
suspicion that ... he may be involved in incitement or support of
violent disturbances.''
   The occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip have been rocked by a
Palestinian uprising against Israeli rule for the past 22 months.
   The army closely monitors and censors Palestinian newspapers,
and has raided Palestinian press offices and the homes and offices
of several Arab journalists, including one who works for The
Associated Press.
   Shriteh said that on Monday, seven soldiers broke into his house
and searched his office and bedroom. The material they confiscated
included reports he submitted to Reuters, his telephone directory
and five videotapes.
   He said three of the videotapes were of demonstrations he filmed
for CBS, one was a movie and one was a tape of his 1987 wedding.
   Shriteh said an officer working with the military administration
in Gaza, Capt. Yaacov Sabagh, later called three people named in
Shriteh's phone directory and told them to stop supplying him with
information.
   ``They are trying to limit my work and scare people from helping
me,'' Shriteh said.
   An army spokesman refused to confirm or deny if the army called
Arabs named in Shriteh's book but said, ``We are checking that
there will be no unauthorized use of the material taken.''
   Shriteh said the book was returned Thursday along with about
half of his files.
   ``What they did is a clear violation of my rights as a
journalist,'' he said. ``If they think that reporting the news
incites riots, then all of the foreign press is guilty of
incitement.''
</TEXT>
