<HEAD>Mailing Campaign Launched to Help Find Missing Minnesota Boy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A hunter found the body of a strangled 4-year-old in Washington,
a search was called off for a boy lost in snowy Oregon woods, and a
missing-child support group promised a nationwide mailing to help
find a kidnapped Minnesota boy.
   The Kevin Collins Foundation, named after an abducted California
child, opened an office in St. Joseph, Minn., Wednesday to organize
volunteers in sending out at least 90,000 fliers starting today.
   That signaled to Jerry Wetterling that the search for his
11-year-old son, Jacob, could drag on. Jacob was kidnapped Oct. 22
on a rural road near his home in St. Joseph, a town of 3,000.
   ``I'm preparing myself for the long haul,'' the boy's father
said.
   Lee Joseph Iseli, a boy who disappeared from a Portland, Ore.,
playground on Sunday, was discovered strangled Wednesday near
Vancouver, Wash., Coroner Arch Hamilton said. A hunter found the
nude body in brush near a lake.
   Authorities said they had no suspects. Prosecuting Attorney Art
Curtis said an expert on child sexual abuse had been consulted.
   Sheriff Frank Kanekoa said nothing has been found to link the
killing to the fatal stabbings on Labor Day weekend of William
Neer, 10, and Cole Neer, 11, in a park in the city of about 45,000
people.
   In Oregon, searchers said they ran out of places to look for
Nathan Madsen, 9, of Veneta, who disappeared with his pony Oct. 22
during a family cattle roundup.
   Authorities will continue investigating, Sheriff Carl Burkhart
said, but rescuers ended a search that peaked last week with 350
people involved.
