<FIRST>r i PM-Norway-Spy     11-02 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Norway-Spy,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer: Reputed Soviet Spymaster Would Testify for Convicted Spy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet KGB general and reputed spymaster
is willing to testify on behalf of a former Norwegian diplomat
convicted of spying, the Norwegian's attorney said today.
   Gen. Gennady Titov would say that convicted spy Arne Treholt
never passed NATO secrets to the KGB, said Treholt's lawyer Arne
Haugestad. Treholt said this summer that he would request a retrial.
   Titov was declared unwelcome in Norway after Treholt was
arrested in 1984 and sentenced the following year to 20 years
imprisonment, Norway's harshest punishment. Titov was named at the
trial as Treholt's controller.
   At a meeting Wednesday with Haugestad in Moscow, Titov also
claimed that Norwegian intellegence sent him an unsigned,
handprinted letter in 1984 offering him $500,000 to defect to the
West, Haugestad told the NTB news agency.
   ``If the KGB is given the opportunity to testify in a Western
spy case it would be a historic and trailblazing event,'' Haugestad
said.
   He said Titov gave him documents and statements defending
Treholt, as well a copy of a letter Titov claimed was an offer to
defect for pay.
   Treholt, 48, was convicted of passing NATO secrets to the
Soviets during the 1970s and early 1980s. Photographs and other
evidence of Treholt's meetings with Titov were instrumental in the
case.
   ``I see the Treholt case as closed and am indifferent to this
new information,'' Jostein Erstad, of Norwegian intellegence, told
NTB. He refused to comment further.
</TEXT>
