<FIRST>r a PM-BigCockroach 1stLd-Writethru a0510 11-02 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Big Cockroach, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0510,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brooklyn Grows 'Em Biggest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout to CLARIFY that the bug was biggest this
year, record still held by 1987 roach; CORRECTS that there was no tie for
second, UPDATES with quote from spokeswoman. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bigger bug than the bug from Brooklyn there
wasn't.
   A 1.88-inch cockroach found in a Brooklyn apartment defeated
entries from Texas and Florida to be declared this year's biggest
specimen of its genus.
   The creepy crawler did not, however, topple the 2-inch-plus mark
set by a specimen from Florida in 1987.
   The roach was given the award posthumously, having been dead for
several weeks.The man who found the Periplaneta americana in his
home, Peter Roman, won $1,000 and a lifetime supply of roach killer
from Combat Roach Control System.
   ``I'm sure he'll be very happy,'' said Barry Glass, president of
Big Apple Pest Control, who accepted the award for an absent Roman.
   Michael Bohdan, Combat field director, measured the insects with
electronic digital calipers.
   Second place went to a 1.78-inch roach entered by Howard Morrill
of North Miami, Fla. The third-place winner was a 1.77-inch roach
submitted by Michael Bartolone of Plano, Texas.
   Another bug, from Mexico _ ``it dwarfed the others,'' said
spokeswoman Brenda Burrows _ was disqualified by the judges, who
ruled that it was in fact a waterbug.
   The contest was held at the Explorers Club.
</TEXT>
