<SECOND>PM-Yugoslavia-Protest, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0524,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Demonstrator Killed in Clashes With Police</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with official news agency confirming
death of demonstrator, details on protest in Pristina district; Picks up
8th graf, ``A real ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of people protesting the
trials of 15 Albanian separatists battled police in the troubled
province of Kosovo, and one protester was killed, sources and the
official Tanjug news agency said today.
   The demonstrator, identified as Bedri Sokolji, was shot dead
during a protest by about 1,000 people in the province's capital of
Pristina late Wednesday night, Tanjug said.
   Several smaller groups of demonstrators fought running battles
with police today in different Kosovo towns to protest the trial of
Azem Vlasi, a popular former provincial Communist Party chief, and
14 other ethnic Albanians, sources told The Associated Press on
condition of anonymity.
   The defendants are charged with engaging in
``counterrevolutionary activities'' and opposing constitutional
changes that limited the province's autonomy.
   Death is the maximum penalty on conviction of the charges, which
include inciting ethnic Albanians to riot and strike. Vlasi's
co-defendants are officials and workers at a zinc and lead mine
where a strike occurred in March.
   Shots were heard today in the Pristina district of Suncani Breg
where security forces used tear gas and firearms to quell a
demonstration by an unspecified number of ethnic Albanians, the
sources said.
   Four people barricaded themselves in a ``public building'' in
Suncani Breg, shooting at the police, which have surrounded the
area, Tanjug said.
   ``A real war is going on out there,'' said a source in a
telephone interview. He said the area was sealed off by heavy
police forces and armored vehicles.
   On Monday, police used tear gas and clubs to disperse a similar
demonstration of about 1,000 people. The same day, the trial was
adjourned soon after it opened as defense lawyers asked for a
change of venue. The lawyers said a fair trial is impossible in
Serbia because none of its courts could be considered impartial.
   Kosovo, with a predominantly ethnic Albanian population, is a
province in the republic of Serbia. For generations the Serbs and
ethnic Albanians have accused each other of discrimination.
   Vlasi, 42, on Monday described the proceedings as a show trial
and claimed he was the victim of a plot by archrival Slobodan
Milosevic, president of Serbia.
   Until his arrest in March, Vlasi publicly opposed Milosevic's
efforts to increase control over Kosovo, an autonomous province in
which 85 percent of the 1.9 million people are ethnic Albanians. At
least 24 people were killed in the March violence.
   Milosevic and the Serbian leadership argued the changes were
necessary because of alleged harassment of the Serbian minority in
Kosovo, the heartland of ancient Serbia.
   The trial has been denounced in the liberal Yugoslav republics
of Slovenia and in Croatia as a Serbian bid to intimidate ethnic
Albanian dissent in Kosovo.
</TEXT>
