<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Tanker     11-02 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Tanker,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arens Appeals for Help in Gaining Tanker's Release</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Moshe Arens today asked Egypt
to release an Israeli-owned tanker seized because of an oil spill
in the Gulf of Suez, and other officials complained that the crew
was poorly treated.
   The two-week detainment of the Nyuta dominated the front pages
of all major Israeli dailies and raised tensions at a time of
deadlock between Egypt and Israel over efforts to arrange
Palestinian-Israeli negotiations.
   The 103,332-ton tanker flying a Panamanian flag was carrying
50,000 tons of crude oil from an Egyptian oil terminal to the
Israeli port of Eilat when it was stopped Oct. 21.
   Reports from Egypt said the ship spilled oil covering an area of
about 60 square yards. The tanker's captain, Joseph Zvi, and
Israeli officials have denied there was damage.
   Egyptian Foreign Minister Esmat Abdel-Meguid agreed today to
raise the tanker's seizure with ``relevant'' officials following a
telephone call from Arens, an Israeli Foreign Ministry official
said. He did not disclose details of the call.
   Israeli Ambassador to Egypt Shimon Shamir on Wednesday appealed
to the Egyptian oil minister, Abdel Hadi Kandil, to intervene on
behalf of the crew of 24 Israelis and one Yugoslav.
   ``We hope and expect the problem to be solved soon,'' Shamir
told The Associated Press today.
   Israel's Energy Minister Moshe Shahal said he was willing to
offer Egypt an unlimited financial guarantees to get the Nyuta
freed.
   Israeli officials complained about the holding of the captain in
jail between his arrest Oct. 22 and his return to the ship last
Thursday.
   ``What has disturbed us is the treatment of some of the crew ..
. the fact that they didn't have water,'' added the Foreign
Ministry official, who asked not to be identified.
   A Foreign Ministry official said Israel had no plans to cancel
its annual purchase of 2 million tons of crude oil from Egypt,
stemming from the two countries' 1979 peace treaty.
</TEXT>
