<FIRST>u i PM-Jaguar-Ford 2ndLd-Writethru   11-02 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jaguar-Ford, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0526,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Makes Cash Offer For Jaguar, GM Drops Out Of Race</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with GM dropping out; picks up
6th graf `Ford and GM were...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. today made a friendly offer of $2.5
billion in cash for the struggling British luxury carmaker Jaguar
PLC, and General Motors Corp. said it would not try to outbid its
U.S. competitor.
   Jaguar, which had negotiated with General Motors to fend off
unwanted advances from Ford, recommended that its shareholders
accept Ford's offer of 850 pence, or $13.35, a share. Shareholders
must approve the deal by a 75 percent majority.
   GM spokesman Tony Spalding said in London later today that his
company would not bid for Jaguar shares.
   The world's biggest automaker, GM had U.S. regulatory approval
to buy up to 15 percent of Jaguar. But on Wednesday, GM Chairman
Roger B. Smith said he didn't expect a bidding war to erupt with
Ford.
   Ford and GM were looking at Jaguar to add prestige to their
lineups and a manufacturing plant in England, auto analysts have
said. Some also have said that a U.S.-backed Jaguar could offer
competition in the growing luxury car market to the this fall's
Toyota Lexus and Nissan Infiniti lines.
   Jaguar had been expected to become the target in a
multibillion-dollar bidding war between GM and Ford after the
British government announced Tuesday that it was prepared to waive
its ``golden share,'' which allows Jaguar to veto any takeover.
   Jaguar, which has suffered from a slump in the U.S. sales it
depends heavily upon, had been looking for a partner to give it
financial and technological support while remaining independent.
   The offer from Ford, which already controls 13.2 percent of
Jaguar, was lower than Jaguar's closing share price $13.80
Wednesday.
   ``It looks like Jaguar have settled for the best they could
get,'' said John Lawson, auto industry analyst at the Nomura
Research Institute in London. ``I don't see a higher, counter offer
emerging.''
   Said Peter Deighton, an analyst with brokerage County Natwest
Woodmac: ``To suddenly find that the management of Jaguar is
endorsing the bid from Ford and recommending it suggests that GM
have said they're not prepared to go this far.''
   Analysts had said that Jaguar could fetch $2.8 billion if Ford
and GM put competing bids on the table.
   In a joint statement, Ford and Jaguar said the deal represented
an important step toward helping Ford develop a presence in the
worldwide luxury car market.
   Under the deal, Jaguar said it would remain a ``separate legal
entity with a self-sustaining capital structure.''
   Jaguar's board would also operate independently, made up of
senior Jaguar management and directors nominated by Ford. Jaguar
would report to the chairman of Ford of Europe.
   Ford and Jaguar said they believed there was considerable
potential to increase sales by expanding Jaguar's product range in
Europe, the United States and elsewhere.
   Ford would inject funds into Jaguar to develop the company's
existing product range and boost its research and development
funding. In addition, Jaguar would be able to make use of Ford's
worldwide engineering, purchasing and manufacturing technologies.
   GM's friendly talks with Jaguar in recent weeks had been
expected to result in a deal by mid-November under which General
Motors would have acquired a stake of perhaps 30 percent.
   The pursuit for Jaguar became public on Sept. 19, when Ford
announced it would buy up to 15 percent of the carmaker.
   After obtaining U.S. regulatory approval, Ford said it was
prepared to mount a full bid for Jaguar once takeover restrictions
were dropped.
   Trade Secretary Nicholas Ridley said this week that if 75
percent of Jaguar shareholders vote to lift a 15 percent
restriction on holdings in Jaguar, the government would drop its
special share.
   The golden share and the 15 percent limit were due to expire at
the end of 1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
