<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Strikes 1stLd-Writethru a0541 11-02 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Strikes, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0541,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Miners Demand Reforms Promised During Summer Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with miners blocking coal shipments,
warning of shortages and rationing, meeting on strike call; Picks up penultimate
graf, `In Donetsk ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miners in the Arctic Circle are blocking coal
shipments to other Soviet regions to pressure the government to
keep its promise of better living and job conditions, official
press reports said today.
   Other miners in the Vorkuta region have walked off the job, and
Soviet officials warned that a drop in coal production could force
fuel rationing as the long and severe Russian winter begins.
   In the Ukraine's Donetsk Coal Basin, the country's top
coal-producing area, tens of thousands of miners walked off the job
for two hours Wednesday to press demands for higher coal prices, an
end to corruption and political reform, a strike leader said.
   Miner representatives were meeting again today to decide whether
to call a walkout. In Moscow, Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov introduced
a bill that would increase pension benefits by about 40 percent and
upgrade benefits for coal miners, Tass said.
   At the Vorgashor mine north of the Arctic Circle, a strike
continued for an eighth day, with a number of other mines in the
region holding two-hour walkouts Wednesday in support of the
Vorgashor miners, the Tass news agency said.
   Night-shift workers have walked out at three mines in Vorkuta,
and one mine is refusing to ship any coal, the Komsomolskaya Pravda
youth newspaper said.
   At the Komsomolskaya mine, miners have not stopped digging coal,
but are preventing it from being shipped outside Vorkuta, the paper
said.
   ``We do not expect any special privileges, nor are we depriving
other regions of food, goods or money,'' the miners said in a
statement quoted by Komsomolskaya Pravda. ``All we are asking is
that the government, the Coal Ministry and the union leadership
should keep their word.''
   In July, miners in the Soviet Far North and Ukraine ended a
two-week strike after the government passed a resolution promising
reforms, including improved social and economic conditions. The
miners now say the government is not fulfilling its promises.
   In a separate article, Komsomolskaya Pravda painted a stark,
sympathetic picture of a miner's lot in the Soviet Far North,
noting many do not see dayligh for months in this region where the
sun dips below the horizon in winter and miners toil below the
earth's surface.
   In Donetsk, the miners gathered in front of the House of Unions
to demand that the government set a deadline for implementing
reforms, Tass said. They called for an immediate announcement of
when improved benefits, including pensions and longer vacations,
will take place, the news agency said.
   A regional court in Vorkuta ruled that the walkout was unlawful,
but has not yet imposed any penalties on the miners. The miners
said they will appeal the court's decision in the Supreme Soviet.
</TEXT>
