<FIRST>r a PM-BoyBurned     11-02 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boy Burned,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Father Who Burned Son Nears Prison Release, Says He's Sorry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man sent to prison for setting his son on
fire in a custody dispute six years ago has been given a release
date of Dec. 11.
   Charles Rothenberg was sentenced to 13 years behind bars after
pleading guilty to arson and attempted murder of his
then-6-year-old son, David. With time off for good behavior, he was
scheduled for release from Soledad State Prison.
   Superior Court Judge James R. Frank said he gave Rothenberg the
maximum when he sentenced him in 1983.
   ``He would have died in prison if I had anything to say about
it,'' Frank said.
   David was rescued from the flames but has had to undergo dozens
of reconstructive operations to repair the damage and severe
disfigurement caused by the burns to 90 percent of his body.
   The case was dramatized last year in an ABC movie, ``David,''
starring Bernadette Peters as the boy's mother and John Glover as
the father.
   Rothenberg, a one-time cab driver and waiter, told a KABC-TV
reporter in a prison interview that he is sorry for the crime and
would never hurt his son again.
   Expressing concern about his future, Rothenberg said he has no
job or home waiting for him and is unsure about how the public will
react to his freedom.
   Rothenberg's former wife, Marie Hafdahl, said she fears for her
son's safety as well as her own and doesn't believe her ex-husband
has changed.
   David, now 13, has said repeatedly he never wants to see his
father again.
   Rothenberg fled from New York to California with David in 1983
after Ms. Hafdahl refused to extend a visit and threatened to keep
him from seeing his son again.
   After giving David a sleeping pill in a Buena Park motel room,
Rothenberg poured kerosene on the bed, set it on fire and fled. He
was arrested six days later.
</TEXT>
