<HEAD>Police Inspector Fired for Pickpocketing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior police inspector has been fired for
allegedly grabbing a man's wallet on a crowded train during rush
hour last month, police said Thursday.
   Inspector Masatoshi Yamada was dismissed two days after being
accused of taking the wallet, said Katsumi Yakushiji, head of the
Honjo Police Station in downtown Tokyo.
   On his way to work on Oct. 23, Yamada, 54, boarded a commuter
train near his home in the northern outskirts of Tokyo and
allegedly stole a man's wallet containing about $21 from his hip
pocket, Kyodo News Service quoted Yakushiji as saying.
   The man caught Yamada and took him to a station keeper, who
notified police, it said.
   Yamada has denied the charge, saying jostling in the crowded
train caused his hand to clutch the wallet.
   A night duty officer at the Honjo Police confirmed the report,
but would not provide details, including whether any charges were
filed.
