<FIRST>u i PM-SouthAfrica     11-02 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Says African National Congress Rally May Lead To Prosecution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities are weighing whether
to prosecute people who participated in a rally honoring freed
leaders of the African National Congress, President F.W. de Klerk
said today.
   De Klerk said that during Sunday's rally there were ``apparent
contraventions'' of the Internal Security Act, which makes it a
crime to promote the aims of an outlawed organization.
   He said police were preparing a dossier for the attorney general
so he can decide whether to prosecute. De Klerk did not say when
the police investigation would be completed.
   Seven African National Congress leaders were freed
unconditionally on Oct. 15, but their guerrilla movement remains
outlawed.
   Speakers at the rally, including four of the freed guerrilla
leaders, endorsed the movement's use of violence and some quoted
exiled ANC officials _ both violations of security laws.
   More than 70,000 people attended the rally at a soccer stadium
outside Johannesburg.
   De Klerk, in a speech to a military parade, said his government
would not lift the ban on the congress as long as it remained
committed to violence.
   Regarding the freed prisoners, he said: ``They must guard
against being misused by those seeking continued confrontation.
They would also be wise to steer away from imflammatory rhetoric.''
   However, de Klerk said further major political changes were
needed to resolve South Africa's racial conflict. He gave no
specifics today, but has said previously that additional steps
under consideration include lifting of the state of emergency and
release of Nelson Mandela, the best-known African National Congress
leader, who remains in prison.
   Mandela is widely expected to be freed within the next few
months. Justice Ministry spokesman Dirk de Villiers described as
``just speculation'' a report today that tentative plans were being
made for Mandela to be released in January.
</TEXT>
