<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Cat     11-02 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Cat,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cat, Exiled From Moscow For Her Crimes, Comes Home on Her Own</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOSB1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A year ago, Murka the cat was banished from her
Moscow home for eating two canaries.
   Today, she is home, happy and pregnant.
   The saga of the feline who managed to find her way home from
Voronezh, 400 miles south of Moscow, was related in the newspaper
Komsomolskaya Pravda Thursday.
   The gray and white cat caught and killed the first canary two
years ago when it was out of its cage in the apartment of her owner
Vladimir Dontsov, the paper said.
   A year later, Murka somehow unlocked the birdcage and killed the
second.
   ``Thus it happened that she found herself in Voronezh. She was
exiled there to stay with the (Dontsov) children's grandmother,''
Komsomolskaya Pravda said.
   Murka stayed at the grandmother's house for only two days before
disappearing.
   On Oct. 19, Dontsov was on his way to work in Moscow when he
spotted the cat on the fourth floor of their apartment building,
dirty and hungry and minus part of her tail.
   ``Without any information desk, she found her way to the correct
neighborhood,'' the newspaper said.
   Komsomolskaya Pravda said the case of Murka was not unique, but
that animal psychologists still cannot explain how some animals can
find their way home from hundreds of miles away.
   Murka apparently found both adventure and romance during her
yearlong journey.
   ``It resulted in the loss of the tip of her tail and an injured
ear,'' it said. And, it added: ``She is pregnant.''
</TEXT>
