<FIRST>u i PM-Palme 1stLd-Writethru   11-02 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Palme, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0513,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rules Lack of Evidence, But Police Still Investigate Suspect</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to UPDATE with police saying Pettersson still
under investigation. Pickup 2nd graf `Pettersson, 42,...'; INSERTS 2 grafs
after 7th graf ``It cannot be...'' with details. Pickup 8th graf `The verdict
said...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christer Pettersson likely was the man
seen outside a movie theater where Prime Minister Olof Palme was
slain, but it has not been proved he killed the Swedish leader, an
appeals court said today.
   Police, however, said Petterson was still under investigation.
   Pettersson, 42, was convicted by a district court in July of
killing Palme three years ago and sentenced to life in prison.
   However, the Svea Court of Appeals court threw out his
conviction on Oct. 12 and ordered him freed, saying that there was
not enough evidence to conclusively prove his guilt.
   The appeals court today released its formal written ruling of
that verdict, making clear that there was not enough evidence to
convict Pettersson but also raising doubts about his innocence.
   Palme, who was prime minister for 11 years and Scandinavia's
leading international figure, was shot Feb. 28, 1986, while walking
home from a movie in downtown Oslo with his wife, Lisbeth.
   Mrs. Palme's testimony, the key evidence against Pettersson,
left too much room for uncertainty, the appeallate court said.
   ``It cannot be considered proved that the perpetrator is
identical with Christer Pettersson. Therefore, the court leaves the
indictment unsanctioned,'' the court said.
   But Ingemar Krusell, a senior investigator, said police have
formed a special squad focusing on finding evidence against
Pettersson while two other teams pursue other possible leads.
   ``Pettersson is still a suspect with us,'' the national news
agency TT quoted him as saying.
   The verdict said Pettersson had no alibi and was most likely the
man who was seen outside the theater apparently waiting for the
prime minister to leave.
   Pettersson had said he was at a surburban train station at the
time Palme was shot in downtown Stockholm.
   But the court said the prosecutor had not erased all doubts that
he committed the murder, and that Mrs. Palme's identification of
him was insufficient evidence.
   Mrs. Palme identified Pettersson as the man she saw a few feet
away when she looked up from her dying husband.
   But the court said Mrs. Palme had seen the gunman only for an
instant in poor light when she was under great stress, and that the
widow was asked to make her identification after a gap of three
years.
   The court also said there no murder weapon was found and that
Pettersson had no apparent motive for the slaying. Also, the
shooting ``gives the impression of a certain amount of planning''
uncharacteristic of Pettersson, the court said.
</TEXT>
