<FIRST>r a PM-MissouriRiver-Navigation     11-02 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Missouri River-Navigation,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a0557 to fix typo in `Missouri.'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Missouri River States Battle Over Navigation Season</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   States upstream and downstream on the
drought-lowered Missouri River are arguing over how to control the
precious water flow.
   The concerns about dwindling water levels in the river's six
reservoirs drew about 80 people from Nebraska, Kansas, Missouri,
Colorado, Iowa, North Dakota and South Dakota at a U.S. Army Corps
of Engineers' hearing Wednesday.
   Storage in the reservoirs is at its lowest level since the
system was filled in 1967.
   Upstream officials urged that the river's navigation season be
shortened by two to three months to boost upstream flows hit hard
by three years of drought. But barge operators who operate
downstream oppose any further shortening of the season.
   ``We cannot continue to operate as if the drought doesn't
exist,'' said Tim Edman, special assistant to South Dakota Gov.
George Mickelson, in calling for a three-month delay in opening
navigation. ``We are not opposed to navigation.''
   The corps shortened the season by three weeks in 1988 and by
five weeks in 1989. The season begins and ends at different times
at different ports. This year, it opened in mid-April and ended
Oct. 25 in Omaha and Wednesday at St. Louis.
   Edman recommended during the meeting Wednesday that navigators
haul more tonnage during a shorter season. In 1987, about 2.3
million tons were shipped during a seven-month, three-week season.
   Don Huffman of Phoenix Towing in St. Louis said the lower river
levels have forced him to reduce the number of barges he can tow
and the tonnage of cargo on each barge, amounting to a 45 percent
loss of efficiency.
   ``We've been very drastically affected by this drought. This has
cost us a lot of money,'' he said. Further season cuts will raise
shipping costs and hurt the farm economy, he added.
   The one-day meeting is part of the process the corps uses to
develop its annual operating plan for the Missouri River. The plan,
due out in January, includes an overview of what happened in 1989
and how the corps will operate in 1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891102-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 1323EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-US     11-02 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-US,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Thanks U.S. For Aid, Looks Ahead to Trip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa on Thursday
thanked the United States for its first emergency shipment of
grain, although he said he'd rather be accepting combines than corn.
   ``I am not delighted with this kind of help,'' said Walesa. ``I
treat this help as a kind of necessity, so we can work out
solutions.''
   The emergency food arriving from the United States and the
European Community is intended to help Poland weather shortages and
other ill effects of economic reform without an explosion of public
unrest that could threaten the Solidarity-led government of Prime
Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki.
   About 11,500 tons of U.S.-donated sorghum arrived by ship Monday
at the Baltic port of Gydnia, about 10 miles from Gdansk, the
headquarters of the Solidarity movement.
   ``We need more the means of production than the product itself
... but I am thankful for this help because it will enable us
peaceful reforms,'' Walesa said at his weekly news conference.
   ``I urge everone to produce food here,'' he said. ``For example,
it would be better if Americans could send the equivalent in
combines and machines and then the farmers could produce in
Poland.''
   Walesa will be able to deliver his message in person next week,
when he leaves for his first trip to North America. He will visit
Canada on Nov. 11-13 and then go to the United States, where he
will address Congress on Nov. 15.
   President Bush has been under pressure from Democratic
congressional leaders to increase the aid he proposed for the first
East bloc country not led by a communist.
   But Walesa said he is going to the United States ``to gain
friends and not to divide them'' and won't let himself be drawn
into a political struggle.
   ``Right at the airport I am going to say, `I am coming here only
to thank you and ask for understanding for the Polish reforms.
Please do not use me for election purposes and political aims
because they are your own internal problems and not our problems.'''
   Walesa said the journey represents ``my most difficult trip.''
   While he intends to thank Americans for their support over the
years, he said he also ``will try to urge the United States to turn
their eyes to Poland, especially in the time of reforms, and to
take part in those reforms.''
   Walesa, who was not allowed to travel abroad for seven years
after martial law was imposed to crush his independent union, made
his first foreign trip in 1988 to France.
   Since then, he has visited several European countries and it was
reported Thursday he will go to Britain on Nov. 29 at the
invitation of the General Council of the British Trade Union
Congress.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
