<FIRST>u w PM-Congress-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0440 11-02 0628</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0440,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Votes to Condemn Ortega</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Tops 8 grafs new with House action on resolution; picks up at
pvs 3rd graf, `I can't;' trims below to shorten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House today overwhelmingly condemned
Nicaragua's cancellation of a cease-fire, saying President Daniel
Ortega's complaints of renewed rebel attacks are ``a phony
pretext'' for renewing the fighting.
   The lawmakers voted 379-29 for a non-binding resolution
denouncing Ortega's resumption of military action against the
Contra rebels and opposing any effort to cancel or delay national
elections scheduled for next Feb. 25.
   Ortega must ``cease his reckless rhetoric'' and Nicaragua's
leftist leaders must fulfill commitments to ``end their aggression
in the region, end their tyranny over their own people and permit
the establishment of democracy inside Nicaragua,'' the resolution
said.
   Any attempt to put off the elections or to impose a state of
emergency ``under the phony pretext of a major Contra-initiated
breakdown of the cease-fire'' is deplored by Congress, it said.
   The resolution was identical to one passed 95-0 by the Senate on
Tuesday. House Republicans used a parliamentary tactic to
substitute the tough-worded Senate measure for a watered-down
version that had been approved on Wednesday by the House Foreign
Affairs Committee.
   In the committee's version, the U.S.-backed Contras were also
admonished not to interfere with or disrupt the election process
and to abide by the cease-fire; the Senate language focused
entirely on the actions of the Sandinista government.
   The resolution reaffirmed U.S. intentions to continue
humanitarian aid to the Contras _ now flowing at a rate of about $4
million a month _ through February. The aid is subject to review by
Congress at the end of this month, and could be halted if key
lawmakers believe the rebels are not conforming to the peace
process.
   The action reflected widespread outrage on Capitol Hill with
Ortega's Wednesday announcement, but also the feeling that it was
important to keep the elections alive.
   ``I can't conceive of the House moving now toward providing
military assistance'' to the Contras, said House Speaker Thomas S.
Foley, D-Wash. ``That's not in the direction of the peace process.''
   Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., suggested opposition
candidate Violeta Chamorro be invited to address a formal joint
meeting of Congress when she visits Washington next week, an honor
normally reserved for foreign heads of state.
   Longtime opponents of aid to the rebels said Ortega had put
those who had supported the peace process in a delicate political
position.
   ``Ortega is a damned fool, and he's always been a damned fool,''
said Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., chairman of the House Appropriations
subcommittee with jurisdiction over the aid.
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., Obey's Senate counterpart, noted the
issue of Contra aid had seemed dead. ``Daniel Ortega is doing
everything possible to turn that around. He is doing more to stir
support for it than anyone else in this hemisphere,'' he said.
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., said the United States should
urge international groups like the United Nations and the
Organization of American States to press Ortega to reconsider.
   ``I would like to think my colleagues would exercise some
caution and not go charging over the cliff,'' he said.
   ``The key right now is to try to act so swiftly and to send such
strong signals that military aid is not necessary because the
cease-fire ... doesn't get broken,'' said Rep. Newt Gingrich,
R-Ga., the No. 2 House GOP leadership official.
   But Gingrich added: ``It's important for the Congress on a
bipartisan basis to send a signal to Ortega that we are not going
to stand by and see people slaughtered by a communist army which
ruthlessly violates the cease-fire in order to pre-empt the
election.''
</TEXT>
