<FIRST>r i AM-Laos-US     11-02 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Laos-US,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Team Discusses Expanding MIA Searches in Laos</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and Laos will conduct
another joint field effort this year to account for missing U.S.
soldiers, Laotian media said Thursday in reporting on talks between
both sides.
   The effort is to determine the fate of American soldiers listed
as missing in action from the Vietnam War, which also involved
fighting in Laos.
   The Laotian news agency said the expansion of joint efforts on
the issue was discussed in talks in Vientiane on Thursday between
teams led by David F. Lambertson, U.S. deputy assistant secretary
of state for Asian affairs, and Souban Salitthilat, Laos' deputy
foreign minister.
   ``In 1989, two joint excavations to find the remains of the
missing Americans were conducted together with a further survey,''
the report said. ``It is expected that this will also (be)
conducted late this year at a site in southern Savannakhet
province.''
   It was not clear from the report if a preliminary survey or an
actual dig would be conducted in Savannakhet, which is bordered by
Thailand and Vietnam.
   About 2,300 Americans are listed as missing in action from the
Vietnam War, about 545 of them in Laos. The war ended in 1975 with
Communist victories in Vietnam, Laos and Cambodia. The United
States has diplomatic relations only with Laos.
   In March, the U.S. Defense Department said a U.S. team found
human remains at a site in Savannakhet where a CH-34 helicopter
with seven crewmen crashed in 1968.
   Another search team visited Laos in May.
   Lambertson was on the delegation which U.S. presidential envoy
John W. Vessey Jr., led to Vietnam this week for talks on speeding
up work to resolve the fate of Americans there.
   Lambertson was accompanied to Laos by Ann Mills Griffiths, head
of the private National League of Families of American Prisoners
and Missing in Southeast Asia.
   The KPL report also said that on Sept. 30, the United States and
Laos signed a $200,000 aid agreement for rural development in the
northeastern province of Houaphan. The United States has boosted
humanitarian aid to Laos in return for its help on the missing
soldiers.
</TEXT>
