<FIRST>u w PM-US-Nicaragua 3rdLd-Writethru a0575 11-02 1085</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Nicaragua, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0575,1030</SECOND>
<HEAD>Contras Can't be Expected to Lay Down Arms, White House Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 3rd graf, `You can't,' with House vote
on resolution; deletes last 2 grafs to shorten; minor editing elsewhere</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House said today it is unrealistic
to expect Nicaragua's Contra rebels to lay down their arms when the
leftist Sandinista government is out ``to destroy them'' by
breaking the cease-fire.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the United States
still backs the regional peace accord that calls for the Contras to
voluntarily disband by Dec. 5, and return to their homeland if they
so desire. But he also indicated that this support is tied to
Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega's decision to restart the war.
   ``You can't ask people to repatriate themselves into a climate
where they're threatened with death,'' the spokesman told
reporters. ``I don't think anybody expects demobilization to
proceed as long as the Sandinistas are on the offensive attack to
try to destroy them.''
   Meanwhile today, the House adopted, 379-29, a Senate-passed
resolution that condemned Ortega for canceling the cease-fire and
opposed any effort to cancel or delay national elections scheduled
for next Feb. 25.
   Ortega must ``cease his reckless rhetoric'' and Nicaragua's
leftist leaders must fulfill commitments to ``end their aggression
in the region, end their tyranny over their own people and permit
the establishment of democracy inside Nicaragua,'' the resolution
said.
   Fitzwater replied indirectly when asked if the administration
wants the Contras to remain together as a fighting force until the
Feb. 25 elections, or disband by Dec. 5 as called for in the
regional accord signed this year in Tela, Honduras.
   ``We want the Tela accords to be complied with and we are not
willing to say what might happen and speculate on those actions,
but simply to point out the reality of the situation, which is the
Sandinistas are attacking them _ what do you expect them to do?''
Fitzwater said.
   ``If they're going to go home and be killed, it's pretty hard to
ask them to do it.''
   ``Mr. Ortega has forced the situation,'' Fitzwater said of the
Nicaraguan leader's announcement that his leftist government would
no longer honor the unilateral cease-fire.
   Although President Bush and members of Congress have harshly
criticized Ortega for canceling the cease-fire, they do not appear
ready to resume military aid to the Contras, who are reported to be
re-entering Nicaragua.
   U.S. officials said Wednesday up to 1,500 Contras have crossed
the border into Nicaragua over the past month from base camps in
Honduras, bringing the guerrillas' troop strength to about 4,000.
   Ortega cited renewed rebel attacks as the reason for suspending
the cease-fire and hinted he might cancel the national elections,
saying the actions of ``Yankee Congress and the Yankee President''
will determine whether they take place.
   Later, a Nicaraguan official said that country has no plans to
cancel the elections, and Ortega insisted in a column published in
today's New York Times that the elections will be held and that the
Sandinistas will win.
   Bush lashed out at Ortega, saying, ``The man is so out of step
with the other democratic countries in this hemisphere and so
wildly insensitive to the feelings of others that we shouldn't have
been surprised'' by his action.
   ``On the other hand, I don't think he has unleashed a full-scale
offensive at this moment,'' Bush said in a radio interview with ABC
News. ``He's hedging his bets now.''
   Ortega's announcement that he was calling off the truce, reached
in March 1988, touched off high-level meetings among administration
officials and expressions of anger on Capitol Hill.
   ``Ortega is a damned fool, and he's always been a damned fool,''
said Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., chairman of the House Appropriations
subcommittee with jurisdiction over aid to the Contras.
   House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., said, ``I can't conceive
of the House moving now toward providing military assistance.
That's not in the direction of the peace process.''
   Asked about prospects for renewing military aid for the rebels,
White House spokesman Fitzwater said Wednesday, ``We don't want to
go that route. We want to get free elections.''
   But some conservative supporters of the Contras began discussing
legislative language that could lead to renewal of military aid to
the Contras if the elections are canceled or delayed.
   The administration said Bush was consulting with leaders in
Central America to bring diplomatic pressure on Ortega to reverse
course.
   Ortega wrote in the Times, ``It is now clear that there is
little point in concentrating our peace efforts around the single
issue of a cease-fire. We do not consider it an acceptable
cease-fire when we cease and the Contras fire.''
   One major irritant to the administration was the seizure at the
Honduran border two weeks ago of a large quantity of weapons the
Sandinistas reportedly had earmarked for leftist rebels in El
Salvador.
   Officials said Secretary of State James A. Baker III confronted
Soviet Ambassador Yuri Dubinin with photographs of some of the
seized equipment, including Soviet-made AK-47 rifles.
   Under a Central American peace plan, the Contras are supposed to
be disarmed and demobilized by Dec. 5. Sources said many Contras
decided to return to Nicaragua because it would be far easier for
them to escape demobilization if they were wandering undetected
inside Nicaraguan territory.
   At the same time, the rebels have asked the U.S. Agency for
International Development, which administers the current U.S.
humanitarian aid program for the Contras, for food packaged in
smaller, more easily portable quantities and for increased amounts
of cash in Nicaraguan currency, said an official familiar with the
aid program.
   AID has refused the requests, believing that to help the
reinfiltration effort would ``be a wrong signal,'' said the
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The administration has asked the rebels to continue to observe
the cease fire, and the Contra leadership reaffirmed Wednesday from
their Honduran base camps they would do so.
   But Ortega said the rebels have been escalating attacks against
civilians recently. Alejandro Bendana, a top Nicaraguan Foreign
Ministry official, said Wednesday night 44 civilians have been
killed by Contra forces over the past 10 days.
   Assistant Secretary of State Bernard Aronson, who appeared with
Bendana on PBS' ``McNeil-Lehrer News Hour,'' said the Sandinistas
never obeyed the cease-fire, launching a major offensive against
the Contras a month after signing it. He added that 90 Contras have
been victims of summary executions by the Sandinistas.
</TEXT>
