<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 1350EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-HUD-McGann     11-02 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-McGann,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-HUD Adminstrator Reassigned Pending Outcome of Investigations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former acting administrator of the New
York regional HUD office has been reassigned to a job at
headquarters after an investigation concluded she violated the
agency's code of conduct, a spokesman says.
   HUD General Counsel Frank Keating concluded that Geraldine
McGann behaved unethically by voting on HUD-related issues as a
trustee of the village of Island Park, N.Y., according to a HUD
audit and other documents obtained under the Freedom of Information
Act. Keating pronounced the internal investigation closed.
   McGann is now working as a special assistant in HUD's Office of
Housing ``until such time as other investigations are concluded,''
HUD spokesman Jack Flynn said Wednesday. He was referring to
criminal investigations being conducted by U.S. Attorney Andrew
Maloney in New York and Nassau County District Attorney Denis
Dillon.
   ``She has no direct management role and is not involved in
funding decisions,'' Flynn said, adding that McGann continues to be
paid the same salary she made as regional administrator, $68,500 a
year.
   McGann did not immediately return a phone call Thursday seeking
comment.
   The internal investigation of McGann stemmed from her dual role
as a Department of Housing and Urban Development employee and a
trustee of the village of Island Park, Long Island. Minutes of the
Island Park board meetings show McGann voted on HUD-related
resolutions from 1982 to 1989, a violation of HUD's code of conduct.
   ``Trustees who served with Ms. McGann advised that it was her
position to abstain from voting on HUD resolutions and that the
minutes must have been drafted or recorded incorrectly,'' said an
audit completed Aug. 30 by HUD's office of inspector general.
``However, Island Park residents present at various meetings
advised that they heard Ms. McGann both vote in the affirmative and
abstain with regard to HUD-related matters.''
   She also voted to approve the village's annual budget, which
generally included HUD funds, according to the inch-thick audit. In
addition, investigators obtained a tape recording of a Nov. 17,
1988, board meeting at which McGann discussed a controversial
swimming pool that Island Park was trying to build using a $425,000
HUD grant obtained by the town's favorite son, Sen. Alfonse
D'Amato, R-N.Y.
   Island Park dropped the project after a spate of reports
ridiculing it, HUD and D'Amato for directing federal housing money
to a pool for a middle-class beachfront community.
   The latest audit reaffirms some conclusions of a January 1984
HUD audit of a federally subsidized housing program in Island Park.
That investigation found inexpensive HUD houses were being steered
to white, politically connected village residents, to the exclusion
of minorities. It also found that McGann had apparently voted on
HUD issues before the Board of Trustees, and noted that one of the
subsidized houses went to McGann's son, Daniel.
   Subsequently, Geraldine McGann told HUD investigators that the
board minutes were erroneous, and then-Village Clerk Harry Scully
sent a letter to HUD saying he had incorrectly recorded some votes.
   In 1988, McGann moved up to acting administrator of the HUD
regional office which then served New York, New Jersey and Puerto
Rico.
   But in June, The New York Times reported that Scully had
recanted the letter and was saying he had lied to protect McGann.
She was suspended as acting administrator in August. She also
resigned as trustee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
