<FIRST>u w PM-DefenseBill 1stLd-Writethru a0467 11-02 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Defense Bill, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0467,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congresional Negotiators Reach Tentative Agreement on Defense Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: TOP 11 grafs new with tentative agreement reached; comments
from Darden, Skelton, conservative groups; picks up 7th graf pvs, The bill.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional negotiators reached a tentative
agreement today on a $305 billion defense bill that cuts $1.1
billion from President Bush's Strategic Defense Initiative request.
   Although lawmakers indicated that the only remaining task was
final signatures on the package by House and Senate negotiators, a
few House members still expressed their opposition to the
conference report.
   ``The deal is done,'' said Rep. Ike Skelton, D-Mo., a member of
the House Armed Services Committee.
   ``We have an agreement but we have to sign off,'' said Rep.
George ``Buddy'' Darden, D-Ga., another member of the House panel.
   Late Wednesday, four House Democrats criticized the conference's
plan to fund both the MX and Midgetman nuclear missiles, and said
they hoped to scuttle efforts to finish the defense bill after
nearly eight weeks of wrangling.
   ``I hope it kills the conference,'' Rep. Charles Bennett,
D-Fla., chairman of a House Armed Services subcommittee, said after
he and three other lawmakers said they could not sign the
provisional conference report.
   The compromise package, based on House and Senate bills passed
in early August, includes a $1.1 billion cut in President Bush's
request for the SDI for a Pentagon total of $3.55 billion and one
less B-2 stealth bomber than the administration sought, said
lawmakers and congressional sources who requested anonymity.
   The level of funding for SDI prompted conservative groups to
call for a presidential veto of the defense bill, saying the amount
would signal the demise of the program.
   ``This is a critical time for SDI,'' John Kwapisz, executive
director fo the Center for Peace and Freedom, told reporters.
``Where's George? He has not spoken out in support of SDI.''
   Pro-SDI groups such as Americans for the High Frontier, the
American Conservative Union and Coalitions for America said if the
president accepts an SDI level less than $3.85 billion he must
``share some of the blame with Congress for the eventual demise of
the program.''
   The defense bill includes about $1.2 billion for the MX
multiple-warhead, rail-based missile and the Midgetman
single-warhead, truck-based missile, which is equivalent to the
$1.1 billion Bush proposed for the MX and $100 million for the
Midgetman.
   The bill requires Defense Secretary Dick Cheney to cut $100
million from the $1.2 billion and gives him discretion on how to
spend the remaining amount. Cheney favored funding only the MX
missile, but Bush opted for both land-based nuclear missiles.
   That provision drew complaints from the four House members,
including three chairmen of Armed Services subcommittees.
   ``We feel that the proposed deal on the B-2, Strategic Defense
Initiative and mobile ICBM's is inadequate and we cannot sign the
conference report in its present form,'' the four said in a letter
to Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the Armed Services panel.
   ``A real opportunity to assert leadership would be lost unless
we eliminate funding for one of the two mobile ICBM's. This could
be achieved by eliminating the Midgetman,'' the lawmakers said.
   Signing the letter were Bennett, chairman of the House Armed
Services subcommittee on seapower and strategic and critical
materials; Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo., chairman of the
subcommittee on military installations and facilities; Ronald
Dellums, D-Calif., chairman of the subcommittee on research and
development; and Lane Evans, D-Ill., a member of the full panel.
   Questioned about the letter, Bennett said supporters of the
Midgetman tout it as a key bargaining chip in U.S.-Soviet
negotiations to reduce strategic weapons. But the Florida Democrat
scoffed at the idea of ``spending millions of dollars on a
bargaining chip.''
</TEXT>
