<FIRST>u a PM-DC-10Crash-Hearing 1stLd-Writethru a0497 11-02 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-10 Crash-Hearing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0497,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Electric Official Acknowledges Double Fan Serial Numbers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with double serial number controversy;
EDITS to tighten and conform. Pick up 5th graf: `Such testing ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEERY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIOUX CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pilots association representative said
today he has questions about the significance of a serial number
mixup in a flawed engine fan disk installed in a DC-10 that
crashed, killing 112 people.
   ``I don't think the records exist properly to answer that
question right now,'' D.B. Robinson, an accident investigator for
the pilots union, said during a break in a National Transportation
Safety Board hearing on the accident.
   A rear engine fan disk that split apart in midair is being
blamed for the crash of United Flight 232 as it made an emergency
landing at Sioux City's airport July 19.
   A more detailed test than one conducted before the crash would
have detected the faulty part, an engineer told federal
investigators.
   A crack in the disk probably existed when the disk was last
inspected in February 1988, said Chris Glynn, a design engineer for
General Electric Co., which manufactured the engine.
   James Tucker, general manager of product operations for GE's
airplane engine plant in Evendale, Ohio, acknowledged Wednesday the
company unwittingly listed two new engine fan disks under the same
serial number in 1971. One of the disks was to be destroyed because
tests showed it might be faulty; the second was to be sent on for
installation in a DC-10.
   Company officials were unaware of the double bookkeeping entry
when they pulled records on engine fan disk 00385, the serial
number of the disk that split in midair.
   But Tucker said company officials are certain the faulty disk
with the same serial number was destroyed in 1972 and did not wind
up in the rear engine of United Flight 232.
   ``There's no way that this ... could have been assembled in that
engine,'' he told NTSB officials at the four-day hearing that
concludes Friday.
   Robinson, however, said he wasn't convinced.
   ``I'm not satisfied, but I'm not dissatisfied either,'' he said.
``The board will discover what's going on. It will be resolved.''
   Ultrasonic testing in February 1988 probably would have led to
the engine's recall, Glynn told the NTSB at the hearing Wednesday.
   United spokesman Robert Doughty said that since the crash, the
Federal Aviation Administration has ordered more detailed
inspections involving ultrasonic examination of all disks similar
to the titanium disk that split apart near the tail of the plane.
   Such testing can detect cracks and other flaws beneath the
surface in a block of material. Before the crash, surface testing
of disks was deemed adequate.
   ``If the ultrasonic testing had been required, it (the crack)
would have been discovered,'' Doughty said during a break in
testimony.
   The crash occurred as the crippled plane was brought in for an
emergency landing at the Sioux City airport after its rear engine
exploded in over northwest Iowa. The explosion severed the plane's
three hydraulic lines, rendering the aircraft virtually
unmanageable.
   The rear engine's huge fan disk was found in two sections in
northwest Iowa farm fields. Initial testing has found a crack
measuring one-half inch deep and more than an inch long in the
larger section of the disk, according to an NTSB report.
</TEXT>
