<FIRST>r w AM-US-Refugees     11-02 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Refugees,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>New US Policy to Be Set on East European Refugees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bush administration officials told Congress
Thursday the proportion of refugees coming to the United States
from East European countries other than Poland and Hungary likely
will rise under an expected new policy based on the danger of
persecution.
   Princeton N. Lyman, director of the State Department's Bureau
for Refugee Programs, testified that the administration policy is
undergoing a review that should be completed in a few weeks.
   He spoke before the House Judiciary Committee's Immigration
Subcommittee at a hearing on the question of refugees from Eastern
Europe _ but not including the Soviet Union.
   Administration witnesses testified that the governments of
Poland and Hungary are becoming more liberal, so that the danger of
persecution there is receding, while that is not the case in
Czechoslovakia and Romania.
   Of 25,000 East Europeans waiting in West European camps in the
hope of coming to the United States, about 80 percent come from
Poland and Hungary. But more refugees from Romania are now
appearing in Western Europe, and also in Hungary.
   One possibility being considered is help for some of those Poles
and Hungarians to return home, said Lyman.
   ``We have to be fair to the 25,000 who have been waiting, some
of them for a long time,'' he said. ``We have to look at
repatriation.''
   Rep. Marcy Kaptur, D-Ohio, suggested that the United States work
with France and West Germany to help such Poles and Hungarians. She
said they would not be accepted easily back home.
   Rep. Bruce A. Morrison, D-Conn, who chaired the hearing, said
that these are just the kind of people Americans would like to see
back in their own countries, working for more democracy.
   ``A little international help would go a long way,'' he said.
   Lyman also pointed out that few East Germans seek to come to the
United States; the overwhelming majority leaving their country go
to West Germany.
   He predicted a rise in the proportion of refugees from countries
where there is a real fear of persecution.
   ``One dilemma we face is the danger that the very existence of a
continuing U.S. refugee admissions program for Poles and Hungarians
will act as a magnet, drawing more people into Austria and other
Western European countries,'' he said.
   For the year that began Oct. 1, the United States will accept
50,000 refugees from the Soviet Union and 6,500 from other
countries in Eastern Europe.
   Nancy R. Kingsbury of the congressional General Accounting
Office testified that only 1,500 places out of the 6,500 will are
still available. The other 5,000 have already been assigned to
people approved last year for admittance to the United States.
   Rep. William O. Lipinski, D-Ill., urged that the number for the
whole area, including the Soviet Union, be raised to 100,000 a year
for 10 years.
   ``Given their qualifications. as well as a forthcoming American
labor shortage, the United States would benefit tremendously from
increased immigration,'' he said.
</TEXT>
