<HEAD>Witnesses Say Silver Cloud of Glasnost Has a Dark Lining</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Witnesses told Congress Thursday that
political repression and human rights abuses remain facts of
political life in the Soviet Union despite Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
new policies.
   All of the witnesses before a House Foreign Affairs subcommittee
acknowleged that there have been significant and unanticipated
human rights advances under the leadership of the Soviet president.
   But all said that the new freedoms of glasnost have been
incomplete and halting.
   ``It's a case of two steps forward, one step back, and every
day's newspaper is evidence of that,'' said Holly Burkhalter,
Washington director of Helsinki Watch, the observer group that
monitors human rights developments in the Soviet Union.
   Rep. Wayne Owens, D-Utah and the subcommittee's chairman,
outlined the moe positive developments in the Soviet Union,
including the expansion of legitimate private enterprise, broadened
religious rights, a more independent press, greater freedom of
expression, a less oppressive KGB, psychiatric reforms and a
dramatic increase in emigration.
   But Owens and the witnesses said the silver cloud has a dark
lining.
   ``Paradoxically, glasnost has sometimes led to increased human
rights abuses, as the authorities have countered with new types of
repres several protestors taking part in a weekend
Moscow demonstrattion held to call attention to past KGB killings
of political prisoners were ``clubbed and dragged to waiting
buses'' when they moves from the sanctioned protest site several
blocks to demonstrate near the headquarters of the secret police
agency.
