<FIRST>r w AM-PostalScandal     11-02 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Postal Scandal,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Argues Post Office Procurement Case Should Be Dismissed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Criminal charges in a post office procurement
case should be dismissed, defense lawyers argued Thursday,
contending prosecutors unfairly manipulated grand jury witnesses to
obtain an indictment against a Texas company.
   Midway through a criminal trial, attorneys for Recognition
Equipment Inc. and two of its top executives moved for the case to
be thrown out because the government showed its star witness
previous grand jury testimony.
   Government investigators were ``threatening'' executive
recruiter William Spartin ``and then poisoning his recollections
through unlawful exposure to the Grand Jury testimony of others,''
defense attorneys said in a 69-page court filing.
   Dallas-based REI and executives William Moore and Robert Reedy
are accused of conspiring to corrupt the federal procurement
process in 1985 in an attempt to win a $250 million contract to
build mail-sorting equipment.
   At the urging of Peter Voss, then vice chairman of the postal
board of governors, REI hired a consulting firm owned by John Gnau
and of which Spartin was president. Gnau then made illegal payoffs
to Voss in a scheme to which both men have pleaded guilty and have
been sent to prison. Spartin has been granted immunity from
prosecution.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Joseph Valder showed Spartin summary
statements of previous grand jury witnesses, making it impossible
for Spartin to distinguish between what he knew and what he had
read, the defense attorneys said.
   The grand jury that indicted REI was never told that the five
main witnesses in the case were unable to implicate the company in
payoffs to Voss, according to defense attorneys.
   Spartin says that as far as he knew, REI was never told that
Gnau was paying Voss, but he never was permitted to tell that to
the grand jury, according to testimony at the trial.
   Instead, Spartin was asked by prosecutors in front of the grand
jury whether he had concluded that REI must have known about the
illegal payoffs.
   Spartin, who had been shown statements from other grand jury
witnesses, said his opinion was that REI must have been aware of
them.
   After Spartin told investigators he wasn't aware that REI had
ever been told of the payoffs, Valder tore up Spartin's immunity
agreement, according to testimony at the trial, which began Sept.
28. Investigators threatened to seek charges against Spartin's son
for obstruction of justice in the scandal.
   ``Everybody is beating me up on this issue,'' Spartin complained
in 1986 during one of his two polygraph examinations on the
question of whether he knew if REI had been told of the payoffs to
Voss.
   ``The (Postal) Inspector, the U.S. Attorney ... what they tried
to tell me was, `look Spartin, you're in deep trouble,''' Spartin
said to the polygraph examiner, who at the end of the exam
identified himself as a postal inspector.
   Spartin told the polygraph examiner that investigators were
telling him, ``You've lied to us. We (are) going to subpoena your
son. We are going to charge him with obstruction of justice.''
Spartin's son wasn't charged.
   When the polygraph examiner asked Spartin whether he would tell
if he ``knew something on REI,'' Spartin replied:
   ``Boy would I tell you, I got nothing to lose ... but I can't
make up a story.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
