<SECOND>AM-East Germany-Poland,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>New German Leader Says He Can Learn From Polish Experience</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Germany-Refugees, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WAR50</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germany's Egon Krenz said after
meeting Thursday with Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki that it was
a ``good experience'' and the two new leaders could learn from each
other.
   Krenz, a Communist Party hard-liner, emerged smiling from the
talks with Mazowiecki, a longtime Solidarity activist and former
political prisoner.
   ``We had a very good talk. We touched all subjects that concern
the German Democratic Republic and the Peoples' Republic of Poland.
It was naturally a new experience for me to speak with the prime
minister,'' Krenz said after the nearly one-hour meeting with
Mazowiecki.
   ``We spoke openly with each other and those who speak openly
with each other quickly find a way to solve all complicated and
uncomplicated problems,'' he added.
   Krenz said they discussed economic cooperation, the political
relationship between the two countries and international issues.
   Mazowiecki said there was a good atmosphere during the meeting.
``I think our conversation was open, clear and made a tour of our
problems.''
   Krenz, in power only two weeks and facing popular pressure at
home for Solidarity-style reforms, also met with President Wojciech
Jaruzelski and with Communist Party First Secretary Mieczyslaw F.
Rakowski.
   Asked what Polish experiences he could use in East Germany,
Krenz replied: ``I have only been here a few hours so I can't say
concretely yet. But, nevertheless, I said we learn from each
other.''
   But he denied taking any advice from Mazowiecki, who became
prime minister in August. ``The prime minister is such a pleasant
man that he didn't make any recommendations,'' Krenz said.
   ``He told me how one should judge things, but we did not give
each other recommendations.
   ``I hope we will have not only good, neighborly relations, but
friendship as well,'' Krenz said. ``We have had good traditions and
I think we can continue those.''
   Krenz said earlier at the airport that it was a ``great
pleasure'' for him to meet Mazowiecki, the East bloc's first
non-communist head of government.
   ``It is a new experience for me, but I think something good can
come out of this experience for East Germany,'' he said.
</TEXT>
