<FIRST>r i AM-India-Violence     11-02 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Violence,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Bodies of Riot Victims Found</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police found 25 bodies in the remote
eastern town of Bhagalpur on Thursday, the scene of sectarian
violence between Hindus and Moslems last week, news reports said.
   Press Trust of India said the discovieries raised the death toll
in the fighting to 190. There have been no reports of violence for
the past two days, the news agency said, quoting government
officials in Patna, the capital of Bihar state.
   Bhagalpur is 110 miles east of Patna and 635 miles southeast of
New Delhi. The army has been called out to maintain peace in the
town and surrounding areas and a curfew is in force.
   Mob violence broke out in Bhagalpur and four nearby village on
Oct. 24 after Hindu fundamentalists organized processions
celebrating the building of a temple at a spot in neighboring Uttar
Pradesh state, which both religious groups claim as sacred.
   Indian news media rarely identify the perpetrators or the
victims of sectarian violence.
   Press Trust said decomposed bodies could be seen on the street
of at least one of the villages and that occasional gunshots were
heard. Many residents were living in camps because their houses
were burned in the violence and the streets were deserted even when
curfew was lifted for two hours, it said.
   Moslems form 12 percent of the country's 880 million people.
Hindus make up 80 percent.
</TEXT>
