<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 1648EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Greece-Smog     11-02 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-Smog,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Smog Closes Schools, Injures 15</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air pollution soared to dangerous levels
in Athens on Thursday, prompting the government to shut down
schools, ban cars from downtown and order industries to cut in half
their use of fuel.
   The National First Aid Center reported that by noon Thursday, 15
people had been hospitalized due to the air conditions _ nine
people with heart problems exacerbated by the smog and six with
respiratory problems.
   The Education Ministry ordered all schools in the Athens area to
close Thursday and Friday in an unprecedented move to protect
students and reduce traffic.
   The Environment Ministry banned all private motor vehicles from
the city center between 7 p.m. Thursday and 5 p.m. Friday. In the
area outside the commercial center, only those with license plates
ending in even numbers were allowed.
   Thousands of office workers had to abandon their cars in the
city, and only half of Athens' 14,000 taxi cabs were permitted to
enter downtown.
   Industries in the Athens area were ordered to halve fuel
consumption as part of the emergency action, and smelting works and
furnaces were shut down.
   The weather bureau predicted that the unusually warm and
windless autumn weather would continue until Sunday, threatening to
raise pollution levels even higher.
   The Attica coastal basin, in which Athens is situated, is home
to more than one-third of Greece's 10 million inhabitants and has a
population density of more than 14,000 people per square mile,
according to the last census in 1981.
   Air pollution has become a serious problem, reaching emergency
levels whenever high temperatures and still weather trap smog
within the mountains that circle the city.
   In September 1982, the government banned half of the capital's
estimated 800,000 private automobiles from central Athens during
office hours. Vehicles are allowed into the restricted zone on
alternate days, depending on the last number of their license
plates.
</TEXT>
