<FIRST>r w AM-JudgeNixon     11-02 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Judge Nixon,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Closes Doors to Debate Impeachment Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate closed its doors Thursday to debate
the case of Judge Walter L. Nixon of Mississippi in the second
impeachment trial to come to the floor in the last two weeks.
   Lawmakers were expected to vote Friday on whether to remove the
61-year-old U.S. District Court judge.
   Nixon was convicted in 1986 of lying to a federal grand jury
investigating reports that he intervened with a local prosecutor on
behalf of a defendant in a marijuana smuggling case. He was
incarcerated at Eglin Air Force Base in Florida last year and
recently moved to a New Orleans halfway house.
   Nixon says witnesses lied at his trial and biased prosecutors
held him to an unfair standard of accuracy in his testimony with no
leeway for error.
   If convicted, Nixon would be the seventh official ever removed
through impeachment and the third judge ousted from the federal
bench in three years.
   Alcee L. Hastings of Florida was removed as a District judge two
weeks ago for conspiracy to obtain a $150,000 payoff in return for
reducing the sentences of two defendants to probation and then
lying about it under oath.
   Reporters and spectators were shooed out of the galleries as
lawmakers prepared to debate the impeachment charges against Nixon.
   The closed-door debate came after final arguments Wednesday from
Nixon, defense attorney David Stewart and House members who play
the role of prosecutors in impeachment trials.
   The House approved three articles of impeachment by a vote of
417-0. They charge that Nixon lied to the grand jury and also in an
interview with the FBI and another representative of the Justice
Department
   Conviction on any of the charges by two-thirds of the senators
present and voting would automatically remove Nixon and halt the
$89,500 salary he has continued to collect. Otherwise, he says, he
would like to return to the bench and preside over trials again.
</TEXT>
