<FIRST>r a AM-CountyLiquor     11-02 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-County Liquor,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Maryland County Becomes First in Nation To Sell Own Liquor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCKVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Montgomery County, a Washington suburb,
became the first county in the nation to have its own brand of
booze when it introduced its County Crest line in liquor stores.
   Gin, rum, bourbon, vodka and scotch have been sold since last
month under the label, which features a knight's helmet and shield
that the county director of liquor control described as a
``knockoff'' of the county crest.
   The County Crest line was described by County Executive Sidney
Kramer as a marketing move to better serve county consumers and to
make Montgomery's county-run liquor stores competitive with
neighboring jurisdictions.
   However, Virginia Bright, head of the county chapter of Mothers
Against Drunk Driving, called the action improper and in poor taste.
   ``What kind of example are we setting for our young people by
having the county's name, the county's crest on alcohol?'' she
asked.
   ``What's the big deal?'' said County Director of Liquor Control
Jerome I. Baylin, noting that it is common for a large liquor store
to sell alcohol under a private label. ``We don't get them to
drink. They have already made the decision.''
   Montgomery County is the only local government in the nation
that controls the wholesale distribution of alcoholic beverages. It
provides beer and wine to retailers in the county and it has a
monopoly on the sale of hard liquor. Four other counties in
Maryland have a less strict form of liquor control, and 18 states
have liquor control.
   ``We walk a fine line,'' Baylin said. ``Basically, we are here
to foster moderation, temperance and respect of the law. But on the
other side of it, we are a revenue-driven agency, here to offer a
product to people who drink.''
   The County Crest spirits, produced by a Baltimore distillery,
have been available for about a month, and several managers of the
stores said it is too soon to say how popular they will be.
   ``They haven't had time to really establish themselves,'' said
Bob Stover, manager of a Rockville store.
   Baylin said the products will appeal to bargain-hunters. For
instance, the 1.75-liter bottle of County Crest vodka costs $10.95,
compared with $11.39 for Gordon's, $13.69 for Smirnoff and $22.99
for Absolut.
   The County Crest spirits are supplied by Majestic Distilling Co.
of Baltimore.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
