<DOCNO> AP891102-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 1641EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SleepingOnions     11-02 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sleeping Onions,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nitrogen Storage Means Vidalia Onions at Thanksgiving</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vidalia onions will be available at
Thanksgiving for the first time this year, thanks to a new storage
technique that puts Georgia's famous edible bulbs to sleep for up
to six months in a controlled atmosphere.
   The only problem is Vidalia lovers will need to be in north
Florida to put their hands on the sweet things.
   But the new storage technique is expected to become more
widespread by next growing season, and the one farmer now using the
procedure estimates that within three to five years he will have
enough competition to make the onions available nationwide at least
four months of the year.
   Grower W.J. Grimes has been using his $100,000 nitrogen storage
warehouse since June, but on Thursday held an opening ceremony.
   The sweet hybrid, which under state law can be grown only in
specified areas near Vidalia with low-sulfur content soil, normally
cannot be stored for long periods.
   Grimes placed about 350,000 pounds of his Vidalias in the
special warehouse in June and has kept them stored at 34 degrees in
an atmosphere of 5 percent carbon dioxide, 3 percent oxygen and 92
percent nitrogen.
   The controlled atmosphere puts the onions to sleep.
   The low temperature and the humidity keep them from rotting,
sprouting or rooting, while the low oxygen keeps them sweet and the
high carbon dioxide keeps the onions from getting pungent, said
Doyle Smittle, the scientist who developed the process.
   Nitrogen storage could generate an additional $100 million a
year for growers, he said.
   ``We have the potential to have onions year around,'' said
Smittle, a horticulturist at the University of Georgia's Coastal
Plain Experiment Station in Tifton. ``We need to fine-tune the
system. We know we can store them for six to seven months. We just
don't know about 12 months.''
   Besides generating extra profits for Georgia's 260 registered
growers and packers, he said, it also should improve the overall
quality of the $30-million-a-year crop because some growers now
harvest immature Vidalias to get a jump on the season.
   Last season, Vidalias fetched for their growers $20 to $25 a
50-pound bag early in the six-week season, but within three to four
weeks the price had dropped to $10 to $12 a bag.
   Smittle said he believes nitrogen storage will stabilize prices
and give the industry more control over the supply.
   ``I personally think it's going to increase the total
consumption of onions,'' he said. ``I'm sure there are people out
there like me who, when they can't get a good Vidalia onion, quit
eating onions.''
   The consumer should benefit from the more controlled marketing
season of Vidalias, Grimes said, because it will cut down wild
price swings. He said a consumer who pays 89 cents a pound for the
onions, then sees them a week later for 39 cents a pound ``feels
cheated.''
   Grimes sold all his onions to a major grocery chain in Florida.
   ``You'll have to go to north Florida if you want one,'' Smittle
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
