<DOCNO> AP891102-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 1551EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-EastGermany 1stLd-Writethru a0622 11-02 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East Germany, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0622,0734</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honecker's Wife Resigns From Cabinet; Krenz Promises New Travel Law</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with tens of thousands of pro-democracy
protesters marching in three cities; Picks up 8th graf, `Two regional ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos WAR50, BER8,12</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Germany-Refugees, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of ousted East German Communist Party
leader Erich Honecker lost her cabinet post in a series of
top-level resignations Thursday, and tens of thousands of marchers
in three cities demanded democratic reforms.
   New party leader Egon Krenz said his government wanted closer
ties with the European Economic Community and called for a quick
trade agreement. He also discussed reforms with Poland's new prime
minister.
   Krenz promised to announce on Monday a new law allowing freedom
of travel to the West, according to Martin Bangemann, an EEC
commissioner from West Germany who spoke with the East German
leader.
   Thousands of East Germans weren't waiting, however, and poured
into neighboring Czechoslovakia after Krenz lifted a monthold
travel ban. The East Germans hoped to follow countrymen who have
fled West.
   Tens of thousands of those who stayed behind carried candles and
banners as they marched in the East German cities of Erfurt, Halle
and Wilhelm Pieck Stadt. Some shouted over loudspeakers for more
democracy and an end to Community Party privileges, the state-run
news agency ADN reported.
   An opposition leader challenged the Communists to abandon their
40-year monopoly on power.
   Several longtime party officials surrendered their positions as
the pressure for reform intensified.
   Margot Honecker's resignation was announced by ADN following a
cabinet meeting. Mrs. Honecker, 62, had held the post since 1963.
   Two regional Communist Party bosses were replaced, the chief of
the Communist-controlled trade union federation stepped down and
the leaders of two Communist-allied political parties resigned, ADN
said.
   Among those who resigned were Heinrich Homann, the 78-year-old
leader of the National Democratic Party, and Gerald Goetting, the
66-year-old chief of the Christian Democrats.
   Both men also were among the nation's four vice presidents.
   All recognized political parties in East Germany are allied with
the Communists and have closely followed the dominant party's
doctrine. But in recent weeks some of the non-communist parties
have begun to assert their independence.
   Homann and Goetting were believed to have resigned under
pressure from party members. The two parties have a combined
membership of slightly more than 200,000.
   Annelis Kimmel, 55, became the first woman to head the nation's
8.6 million-member, state-run trade union federation when she was
elected to replace Harry Tisch, a protege of Honecker, himself
ousted on Oct. 18.
   Tisch, 62, who headed the organization for 14 years, also is a
member of the Communist Party's policy-making Politburo. It was not
immediately known if he would lose that post as well, or whether
Mrs. Kimmel would gain that seat if he did.
   Young unionists had complained that Tisch ran the federation
only with the party's interests in mind. Mrs. Kimmel promised to
work for more independence for the Communist-controlled trade
unions, according to ADN.
   In an interview with West Germany's Saarland radio, an
opposition leader challenged the Communist Party's leading role in
the society, saying no democratization was possible unless the
party gave up this self-assigned role.
   ``If the party does not give up this claim, there will be no
democratization, no revival of the economy, no solution to the many
problems,'' said Ehrhard Neubert, a leader of the opposition group
Democratic Awakening.
   The Communists could not win a free election, Neubert said.
   Michael Goebel, a member of the largest opposition group, New
Forum, said in an interview with a state-run East German newspaper
that for his group ``the removal of the Communist Party was not
part of the debate.''
   The group says it is pushing for reforms within the socialist
system.
   Krenz met Thursday in Warsaw with Poland's Prime Minister
Tadeusz Mazowiecki, the East bloc's first non-communist leader.
Krenz called it a ``good experience'' and said they could learn
from each other.
   ``He told me how one should judge things, but we did not give
each other recommendations,'' Krenz said.
   ``We spoke openly with each other and those who speak openly
with each other quickly find a way to solve all complicated and
uncomplicated problems,'' he said.
</TEXT>
