<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 1811EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-US     11-02 0688</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-US,0711</SECOND>
<HEAD>Harassment Continues Outside U.S. Embassy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the fourth time in a week, U.S. officials
protested the large Chinese police presence outside the U.S.
Embassy and the harassment by guards of staff and visitors, an
embassy source said Thursday.
   Also Thursday, China said former President Richard Nixon's visit
will help restore badly strained relations with the United States,
but it insisted again that the blame lies with Washington.
   In the U.S. capital, State Department spokesman Richard Boucher
said incidents of harassment are ``unacceptably intrusive security
activity, and we have protested this and previous actions to
Chinese authorities both in Washington and in Beijing.''
   The embassy source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
latest verbal protest came Wednesday, hours before another night of
provocations outside Ambassador James Lilley's residence.
   On Wednesday night, about two dozen uniformed police and at
least 10 plainclothes police congregated outside the gate to the
residence, shining a spotlight and forcing visitors to go through a
gauntlet of armed guards.
   Twenty other policemen were posted on nearby streetcorners and
along the street in front of the compound, turning some cars away
and forcing those going to the embassy to park hundreds of yards
away even though there were many empty spaces near the gate.
   When visitors tried to park closer to the embassy, police banged
on their cars and yelled at them to leave.
   Police cursed at a CBS crew that tried to photograph them, and
they shined another spotlight into the crew's camera.
   A similar massing of police occurred Tuesday evening, only then
they were armed with automatic rifles and did not carry spotlights.
   In an apparent gesture to Nixon, the People's Armed Police
around the three U.S. Embassy compounds did not carry rifles
Wednesday for the first time in four months.
   Nixon aides said the former president told Premier Li Peng he
did not like guns and did not want to see rifle-toting guards when
he visited the embassy.
   On Thursday, guards continued to wear pistols, and eight black
or gray Mercedes sedans, some without license plates and with what
apparently were plainclothes police inside, again were parked along
the street outside the ambassador's residence.
   The embassy also has complained of three cases of embassy staff
findig their car tires slashed and security forces tailing embassy
employees as they left the compounds.
   Twice in the past week, armed police outside the embassy pointed
their automatic rifles at children of U.S. diplomats and pulled the
trigger, an embassy source said. The guns were not loaded.
   During a Halloween party at the embassy on Saturday, the arrival
of people wearing costumes apparently rattled the Chinese. At least
80 police were called in, seemingly to block Chinese fugitives from
sneaking into embassy grounds. Police became particularly upset
when partygoers arrived carrying a fake coffin.
   One man who came to the party dressed in a gorilla suit was told
to park his car elsewhere.
   Premier Li reportedly told Nixon that the heavy guard _ most
embassies have only one or two Chinese police posted outside _ was
necessary to prevent the escape of dissidents Fang Lizhi and his
wife Li Shuxian, who took refuge in the embassy after the June 4
military crackdown on the pro-democracy movement.
   Fang and Li, wanted by Chinese police as counterrevolutionary
agitators, remain in one of the embassy compounds.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Li Zhaoxing, asked about the police
harassment at a weekly briefing Thursday, said China ``always
attached importance to the safety of the foreign embassies in
China.''
   Li said Nixon's five-day visit, which ended several before the
briefing, ``will undoubtedly be conducive to the restoration and
development of the normal relations.''
   But he said ``it is imperative for the United States, and
actually the United States only, to take the initiative'' in
improving ties.
   Washington cut off high-level contacts with Beijing after the
crackdown, when Chinese troops killed hundreds of unarmed
civilians. It has urged China to end repression against those who
advocate democratic reform.
   Nixon aides said he will present an account of his visit to
President Bush.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
