<FIRST>u i AM-Yugoslavia     11-02 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Albanians Killed in Riots in Kosovo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SLOBODAN LEKIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least five ethnic Albanians were
killed during riots in Kosovo over the trial of the former
provincial Communist Party chief, said reports Thursday from the
troubled southern province.
   Sources said four were killed Thursday in Pristina, the capital,
when police dislodged armed men who barricaded themselves inside an
apartment house.
   Police said a man identified as Bedri Skolji was shot dead
Wednesday night when about 1,000 people protested in Pristina.
   About 500 ethnic Albanians tried to mount a protest in the
provincial capital's main thoroughfare Thursday evening, but police
dispersed them with tear gas and clubs.
   Some protesters ran into the city's largest department store,
but police dragged them out, a witness reported. The witness said
20 to 30 people were arrested.
   The trouble stems from the trial of Azem Vlasi, the former party
chief, and and 14 other members of the overwhelming ethnic Albanian
majority in Kosovo, an impoverished southern province bordering
Albania. Of Kosovo's 1.9 million people, 85 percent are ethnic
Albanians.
   Their trial opened Monday, but was postponed immediately for at
least 10 days so appeals courts can rule on demands by Vlasi's
lawyers that the presiding judge and prosecutor be removed on
grounds of bias.
   On Wednesday, about 1,000 policemen sealed off Pristina's
Suncani Breg district, where armed men barricaded themselves in the
apartment building and held security forces at bay with automatic
weapons fire, a source told The Associated Press.
   Shooting was ``fierce'' and began after a midday street protest,
he said by telephone.
   No figures were available on the number of people wounded, the
source reported. He said a special team of paramilitary national
police cleared everyone from the building, one of several in a
modern housing complex.
   Running battles between police and demonstrators were reported
in other Kosovo towns. Television news said one officer was
seriously injured Podujevo, 20 miles north of Pristina, by a man
who struck him with an ax.
   The deaths were the first in the violence that began Monday,
whent the trial began of the 15 men charged with
``counterrevolutionary activity.''
   Vlasi also is accused of inciting riots in February and March in
which at least 25 people, including two policemen, were killed.
   Those riots followed passage of constitutional amendments by the
Serbian republic, in which Kosovo is an autonomous republic, giving
Serbia control of the police and judiciary.
   Serbia said the action was necessary to prevent harassment of
the Slavic minority by the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, a heartland
of ancient Serbia.
</TEXT>
