<FIRST>u w AM-SantaMail     11-02 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Santa Mail,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ho, Ho, Ho and ZIP-Plus-Four</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What to give Santa Claus, the man who truly
has everything, for Christmas? Why not his own ZIP code?
   So the U.S. Postal Service has done it, giving Santa the ZIP
code of 30351-1989. That's the number boys and girls can use when
they address their letters to the jolly old elf.
   Children always have been able to write to Santa without even
that much of an address, and they still can. The Postal Service has
ways of getting those letters to him, or some of his volunteers
scattered around the country. Somehow, most letters get answered _
often with toys if the child appears needy.
   Now, however, the Coca-Cola Co. is trying to give a boost to the
tradition of writing to Santa and got the postal people to
cooperate with 30351, which happens to be in the Atlanta area where
Coke is and not the North Pole where Santa is.
   To make things easier, the company is putting form letters on
the sides of some of its cartons.
   The soft-drink maker, said Postal Service spokesman Ray Jacobs,
is donating 5 cents for each of the first 2 million letters it
receives to the Marine Corps Reserve's Toys-for-Tots program.
   ``We don't want people to think they have to buy cartons of Coke
to send letters to Santa,'' Jacobs said.
</TEXT>
