<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 1604EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-CongressionalMail     11-02 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congressional Mail,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Rejects Attempt to Force House to Disclosing Mailing Costs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senators made clear Thursday they want House
members to join them in disclosing mass mailing costs, but refused
to force the issue in order to avoid scuttling a deal to cut the
taxpayer-financed mailings in half.
   Senators voted 64-35 to table _ in effect to reject _ an
amendment by Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H. that would have required
the House disclosure.
   Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev., warned that the House would reject a
conference agreement to cut mass mailings from six to three
annually per member if senators attempted to change House rules.
   Reid, the chief Senate negotiator of the mail reduction
agreement, said that while he and other senators fought earlier for
Humphrey's plan for quarterly disclosure, they were unwilling to
jeopardize the compromise now.
   `We have gotten from the House all we're going to get,'' said
Reid. ``The conference we had with the House was brutal. The House
had the feeling we should clean up our house before we tell them
what to do.''
   Humphrey, however, argued, ``We have to say we're not going to
be blackmailed. I suggest we have the guts to stand up to the
blackmail of the House.''
   The vote was the latest development in the continuing debate
over changing one of lawmakers' favorite perks: mailings, usually
newsletters, addressed to ``postal patrons'' throughout their
states or districts. The mailings always rise in an election year
because they are considered a great advantage to incumbents.
   Members of each house, however, have used the mail debate to
threaten changes in the way the other chamber does its business.
Senators don't like the idea that only their rules require
disclosure of mailing costs by each member. The House objects to
senators' use of money from honoraria, political action committees
and party campaign committees for office expenses.
   While the House has approved the conference agreement with the
mass mail reductions, the Senate debate is continuing. It was
unclear when the Senate would decide to either accept the agreement
or buck the issue back to the House.
   In addition to the mass mail reductions, the conference
agreement would: establish for the first time separate House and
Senate mail accounts; limit the size of newsletters to two sheets
of paper; establish a voluntary procedure for keeping mail costs
within their budget and strictly enforce a prohibition against
postal patron mailings 60 days before an election.
   The compromise would budget $100.2 million for mailings,
including $44.5 million for the House, $23.9 million for the Senate
and the remainder to pay the Postal Service for mailings that
exceeded the fiscal 1989 mail budget.
</TEXT>
