<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica     11-02 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Says Prosecution Likely Over ANC Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security laws apparently were
broken at a rally honoring freed leaders of the African National
Congress, and prosecution could result, President F.W. de Klerk
said Thursday.
   De Klerk also said the ANC ``remains committed to violence and
terrorism'' and will not be legalized until it drops its commitment
to an anti-government guerrilla campaign.
   The president, addressing a military parade, said that at the
huge pro-ANC rally Sunday ``there occurred what appeared to be
contraventions of existing laws,'' but he did not elaborate.
   Speakers at the rally, including four of the freed guerrilla
leaders, endorsed their movement's use of violence and some quoted
exiled ANC officials _both violations of security laws.
   De Klerk said police were preparing a dossier for the attorney
general so he can decide whether to prosecute, an added: ``Law and
order will be maintained.''
   The seven freed African National Congress leaders were released
unconditionally on Oct. 15 but their guerrilla movement remains
outlawed.
   De Klerk said the free prisoners ``must guard against being
misused by those seeking continued confrontation. They would also
be wise to steer away from imflammatory rhetoric.''
   De Klerk said further major political changes were needed to
resolve South Africa's racial conflict. He gave no specifics
Thursday but has said previously that additional steps under
consideration include lifting of the state of emergency and release
of Nelson Mandela, the best-known ANC leader, who remains in prison.
   Mandela is widely expected to be freed within the next few
months. Justice Ministry spokesman Dirk de Villiers described as
``just speculation'' a report Thursday that tentative plans were
being made for Mandela to be released in January.
   Constitutional Development Minister Gerrit Viljoen, assigned by
de Klerk to draw black leaders into negotiations, said in a
television interview that the rally Sunday had ``exposed the ANC
for what it is _ an organization that openly flaunts its
association with the Communist Party.''
   The flag of the outlawed South African Communist Party was
draped behind the podium at a soccer stadium near Johannesburg,
where more than 70,000 people gathered.
</TEXT>
