<FIRST>r a AM-LandlordSentenced     11-02 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Landlord Sentenced,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Landlord Gets One-Year Prison Term in Fire Deaths</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A landlord was sentenced Thursday to
one year in prison in the deaths of two men trapped inside a
burning apartment house by a locked corridor door.
   Frank Thomas, who installed the lock that violated safety codes
at the request of tenants, appeared shaken by the sentence,
although he could have received up to eight years in prison.
   ``I wished it didn't happen,'' he told state Supreme Court
Justice Nicholas Colabella. ``I tried to help them (the tenants)
and make them comfortable. ... I'm sorry this thing happened.''
   Thomas, 68, of New Rochelle, was convicted Sept. 18 on two
counts of criminally negligent homicide.
   Eight people were killed in the Jan. 15 fire at the Yonkers
apartment building where Thomas was landlord. State Supreme Court
Justice Nicholas Colabella convicted Thomas in only two deaths
because the charred bodies of the men were found behind the door,
which locked from both the inside and the outside.
   Thomas said he installed the lock because tenants wanted to keep
non-residents out of the building.
   The fire, started by the careless smoking of a resident in a
basement apartment, spread rapidly because there was no fire door
between the basement and first floor, another code violation,
authorities said.
   Relatives of the fire victims have sued Thomas.
   Colabella said Thomas was ``not the typical slumlord. You were
attempting to keep the building, in your own way, habitable, even
though it resulted in the building not being safe.''
   Colabella said the city of Yonkers was ``a party to the
tragedy'' since Thomas was not cited for various code violations
and the building had not been inspected regularly.
   Thomas will remain free on $5,000 bond, pending appeal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
