<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-KGB     11-02 0724</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-KGB,0744</SECOND>
<HEAD>Calling the KGB: Phil &amp; Oprah, Eat Your Hearts Out</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five KGB officers sat under the harsh lights
Thursday for a questioning that touched on some of the Soviet
Union's most sensitive secrets.
   The five were not accused traitors, nor were they among the
feared secret service's counterintelligence officers trying to
wring out a confession.
   They were answering questions from the Soviet public in a
first-of-its-kind nationwide call-in program at a Soviet TV studio.
   If the spokesmen for the five KGB departments didn't reveal how
many agents are working abroad as diplomats or trade
representatives, how many have been killed or defected in recent
years, nor the size of the KGB budget, they at least showed off the
KGB's new atmosphere of openness.
   ``Today the KGB is not asking the questions,'' national TV
commentator Vladimir Tsvetov said opening the 75-minute program
that preceded the evening TV news. ``Today they are being asked
questions.''
   Questions from around the country, taken by a group of telephone
operators seated behind the panel, were written out and read by
Tsvetov. That eliminated the possibility of direct exchanges
between the officers and their questioners.
   Questions touched the personal lives, salaries and living
conditions of KGB officers, details of the secret service's foreign
activities as well as charges of its activity inside the Soviet
Union.
   _ Svetlana Matviyenko, a vocational school student from
Leningrad, asked about the romantic tough-guy image of the spy as
portrayed in the James Bond movies.
   ``We wouldn't like our agents to have even the smallest part of
these qualities. That's why it's just ridiculous to speak about the
likeness between a Soviet secret agent and James Bond,'' said Maj.
Gen. Anatoly Bondarev of the KGB personnel department.
   Responding to another question, Bondarev acknowledged that a few
Soviet spies have defected in recent years, causing ``serious
political and moral damage.''
   ``They deserve the most severe punishment,'' he added. ``But we
are principally opposed to passing a verdict in abstentia and
principally opposed to summary punishment.''
   _ Asked if any KGB officers were punished personnally for
hounding Nobel Peace Prize winner Andrei D. Sakharov or exiled
Nobel literature laureates Alexander Solzhenitsyn or Josef Brodsky
during the 1960s and 1970s, Col. Alexander Karbainov, spokesman for
constitutional security department, said:
   ``Those actions were determined by the law that was in force and
the political situation in the country. It doesn't make sense to
talk about personal responsibility, but concerning the KGB as an
organization we share the responsibility for those actions.''
   _ Asked by lawyer Alexander Yegorov of Moscow whether the time
will come when Soviets will be able to see their KGB file, Maj.
Gen. Gennady Kislikh of the investigations department denied that
the KGB has any personal files on Soviet citizens.
   In response to a question about the number of KGB agents working
abroad, and how many have been killed in the line of duty, Vasily
Dozhdalev said all secret services keep such information secret and
that ``I don't want to make their work easier.''
   The TV program comes at a time when KGB chief Vladimir Kryuchkov
is trying to remold his organization's fearful image.
   In the era of President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of
glasnost, or greater openness, the KGB and its predecessors have
been subjected to unaccustomed open criticism for repressing Soviet
citizens.
   On Monday, a group of protesters held lighted candles in front
of KGB headquarters on Moscow's Dzerzhinsky Square in memorial to
the victims of the organization's excesses. Following that protest,
which was peaceful, a group of demonstrators tried to march to
Pushkin Square and many were badly beaten by riot police in the
most savage attack on demonstrators in Moscow in the past 18 months.
   Kryuchkov has spoken out for cooperation against terrorism and
drug trafficking among the world's secret services, has granted
several interviews with foreign journalists and permitted the
government news agency Novosti to make a film about the KGB.
   In keeping with the effort to remodel the image of KGB officers,
Bondarev told Tsvetov that many officers are multitalented people
who write music or poetry, or paint landscapes.
   As a memento of the program, Tsvetov handed out to the five
buttons sold by private producers that are popular now in Moscow.
The buttons read: ``KGB Agent.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
