<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Sake     11-02 0147</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Sake,0150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Brewer to Make Sake in Colorado</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major Japanese rice wine brewer plans to set up a
factory in Colorado that will use ``pure Rocky Mountain water'' to
make traditional Japanese sake, the company said Thursday.
   Tatsuuma-Honke Brewing Co., a sake brewer based in western
Japan, will build its $7 million factory in Golden, Colo., on land
bought from Adolph Coors Co., a major U.S. brewer, said Tetsuya
Ogura, Tatsuuma-Honke spokesman.
   Dry air, cool weather and abundant, pure water from the Rocky
Mountains, as well as cheap rice, are factors that led the company
to set up a brewery in Colorado, Ogura said.
   Constrution of the factory is to start next April. It is
expected to produce 200,000 bottles of rice wine a year beginning
in March 1991, with output increasing to 500,000 bottles in the
third year of production.
</TEXT>
