<DOCNO> AP891102-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 2047EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     11-02 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghan Rebels Reject Ruling Communists in Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan guerrillas on Thursday
rejected peace talks with the Kabul government as suggested in a
resolution adopted by the U.N. General Assembly.
   ``We see the resolution as the same as last year,'' said
Najibullah Lefrey, minister of information of the Afghan
government-in-exile in neighboring Pakistan, where many of the
guerrillas are based.
   The U.N. document, adopted by consensus Wednesday, calls for an
``intra-Afghan dialogue for the establishment of a broad-based
government to ensure ... immediate participation of all segments of
the Afghan people.''
   The insurgents, armed mainly by the United States and Pakistan,
have been fighting the Soviet-backed Kabul government for 11 years.
   ``We don't believe it means the puppet regime should have any
involvement in the talks,'' said Lefrey, referring to the ruling
People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan which seized power in a
bloody 1978 military coup that sparked the insurgency.
   ``The PDPA has no support, so how can it be included in a
broad-based government?'' he said.
   An official of the Pakistan Foreign Ministry, which drafted the
U.N. resolution in consultation with Moscow, acknowledged the call
for intra-Afghan dialogue was not new. But he said this one differs
from last year's document by calling for a cease-fire and for a
solution to the conflict that recognizes the ``Islamic character of
Afghanistan.''
   The guerrillas, known as the mujahedeen or Islamic ``holy
warriors,'' aim to make Afghanistan an Islamic republic.
   ``Intra-Afghan dialogue is quite vague,'' said the Pakistani
official on condition he not be identified by name. ``The Soviet
side may interpret it as comprising all sides, including Afghan
President Najib and the People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan.''
   But the guerrillas have refused to accept either Najib or his
party in a post-war government.
   The resolution's call for a ``cessation of hostilities'' also is
open to interpretation, the official said.
   Kabul and Moscow have said they want a cease-fire first,
followed by efforts to find a political solution. Mujahedeen have
refused to lay down their arms until Najib and his party are out.
   ``There have been compromises on both sides to reach a consensus
resolution,'' said the Pakistani official. ``How else do you
achieve a consensus?''
   The United Nations in 1988 brokered an agreement that provided
for the withdrawal of some 103,000 Soviet combat troops from
Afghanistan, completed in February of this year. The Red Army
intervened in 1979 to fight the mujahedeen and to replace one
communist government with another.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
