<DOCNO> AP891102-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 2051EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-OilSpills     11-02 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spills,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Debates Liability For Oil Spills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House opened debate on comprehensive oil
spill legislation Thursday with members skirmishing over regulatory
powers for states and liability limits for industry.
   Debated for more than a decade but given momentum by the Exxon
Valdez disaster, the proposed legislation would establish a federal
liability and compensation system for damages caused by oil spills
in navigable U.S. waters.
   The bill has broad support, but debate has focused on a
provision that would bar state governments from setting tougher
liability standards than those in the federal legislation.
   Also contested is a provision that would make those responsible
for spills fully liable for damages if grossly negligent.
Environmentalists are pushing an amendment to establish liability
for simple negligence, a lesser standard.
   ``It simply makes no sense, especially now with Prince William
Sound still contamined by oil, to pre-empt the right of state
governments and state legislatures to protect their own people ...
in the way they feel is best,'' said Rep. Gerry Studds, D-Mass.
   But Rep. Norman Shumway, R-Calif., said the federal standards
would be tough enough on oil spillers and that pre-emption of state
laws would ensure a single, comprehensive system.
   ``Without pre-emption, we are going to have a patchwork of
confusing, duplicative and sometimes competing laws that cause
delays and in fact do further damage to the environment because of
the confusion,'' Shumway said.
   Studds has said he will offer an amendment to delete pre-emption
from the bill. Votes on pending amendments and the bill itself were
postponed until next week.
   Rep. George Miller, D-Calif., is expected to offer an amendment
to change the bill's liability threshold from gross negligence to
simple negligence.
   Shumway said he would fight the amendment, describing the bill's
gross negligence standard as a tradeoff with the oil and gas
industry, which under the bill would pay for a $1 billion cleanup
fund.
   The Bush administration supports the bill and says it will
oppose the Studds and Miller amendments.
   If enacted, the bill would establish a fund for spill cleanup
financed through a tax on domestic crude oil and imported petroleum
products. The fund would cover damages to natural resources, injury
to real and personal property, profits and earning capacity.
   A 1986 law provided for a 1.3 cents-per-barrel oil spill tax,
but the House voted this year to boost it to 3 cents.
   The bill would toughen penalties for oil spills and require the
president quickly to mobilize federal resources in the event of a
major spill. Seven regional strike teams would be established to
provide fast cleanup assistance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
