<FIRST>r a AM-RacialFountains     11-02 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Racial Fountains,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plaques Installed Over Fountains Labeled `Colored' and `White'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ELLISVILLE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Metal plaques have been placed over the
engraved words ``colored'' and ``white'' on two courthouse
fountains, ending months of public controversy that generated
national interest in the issue.
   The plaques, which read simply ``Jones County Courthouse 1908,''
were bolted to the two fountains on the lawn by order of the Board
of Supervisors.
   ``As long as the wording is not visible, we're going to back
off,'' said Manuel Jones, president of the local chapter of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People. ``If
the wording is invisible, we don't have to explain to our kids what
`colored' means.''
   Local and national NAACP leaders had been fighting since January
to have the words covered or the non-working fountains removed.
When the County Board of Supervisors began exploring the issue it
was deluged with calls from constituents saying that the fountains
were a part of the town's history and they didn't want them removed.
   County workers plastered over the words in early April only to
have the plaster washed away by month's end by heavy rains.
   ``Something should have been done way before now,'' Jones said
Wednesday, a day after the plaques were attached. ``It just brought
a whole lot of publicity Jones County didn't need and that the
state of Mississippi didn't need.''
   Before deciding on the plaques, the Board of Supervisors
considered uprooting the fountains from the lawn and sending them
to the state Department of Archives and History in Jackson for
museum display. However, constituents' requests to leave the
fountains there prevailed.
   The plaques meet the criteria of historians for careful
preservation, said Elbert Hilliard, director of the archives
department.
</TEXT>
