<HEAD>House Sergeant-at-Arms Admonished for Party Prank</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of a House subcommittee formally have
admonished Jack Russ, the House sergeant-at-arms, for using ``poor
judgment,'' and for violating procedure when he ordered Capitol
police to arrest his assistant in a bachelor party prank.
   Reps. Mary Rose Oakar, D-Ohio, and Pat Roberts, R-Kan., sent a
letter to Russ chastising him for his conduct and ordering him not
to do it again.
   Oakar and Roberts, the head and ranking member respectively of
the Committee on House Administration's subcommittee on personnel
and police, on Thursday released the contents of a letter they sent
to Russ.
   ``The decision to play a praticial joke under color of your
office was poor judgment,'' the letter said.
   ``In view of this incident we are constrained to admonish you to
examine your decisions and your conduct before, during and
subsequent to the incident, and to make those changes necessary to
ensure that there will be no repetition,'' the letter said.
   House Speaker Tom Foley, D-Wash., said earlier he considered
Russ' conduct a ``lapse of judgment,'' but that the letter had
closed the case. Russ did not return three telephone calls.
   The subcommittee investigated the Sept. 13 incident in which
Russ said he arranged for off-duty Capitol police officers to go to
the bachelor party for Assistant Sergeant-at-Arms Robert Fischer at
a restaurant.
   The Washington Post reported that Fischer was taken, kicking and
screaming, in a police cruiser, to Capitol police headquarters
where he incarcerated briefly.
   ``This incident involving both on and off duty officers,
government equipment and government facilities was improper by all
of these tests,'' according to the letter sent to Russ.
   ``Under no circumstances should government-provided equipment or
resources be used for other than official business nor should the
power of your office be exercised for anything other than official
business,'' it said.
