<FIRST>r i AM-TripoliCrash     11-02 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tripoli Crash,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilot's Error Blamed For KAL Plane's Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pilot error was to blame for the July
crash of a South Korean jetliner in fog near Libya's Tripoli
Airport that killed 80 people, officials said Thursday .
   The Transportation Ministry said flight records of the Korean
Air DC-10 with Libyan aviation experts indicated the pilot had been
told of deteriorating weather but still tried to land.
   ``A careful study of the plane's black box and flight records
showed that the pilot attempted to land in conditions which were
beyond his power,'' said Yoo Han-kyu, chief of the Seoul District
Aviation Control Office.
   The flight, which originated in Seoul and carried 119 people,
crashed into an orchard July 27 after hitting the top of a building
near the Tripoli airport. Eighty people were killed, including six
Libyans on the ground.
   About 25 minutes before the crash, Yoo said, the airport's
control tower advised the pilot to divert to another airport
because visibility had dropped to to 800 yards.
   The plane was kept informed of deteriorating conditions as it
approached the aiport, he said. Visibity was 250 yards 10 minutes
before the crash and 50 yards five minutes before the plane went
down, he said.
   The pilot also was told Tripoli's instrument-landing system had
been out of order for several months, Yoo said.
</TEXT>
