<FIRST>r a AM-BoxRestraint     11-02 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Box Restraint,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parents of Boy With Down's Syndrome File Lawsuit Over Box Confinement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parents of a boy with Down's
syndrome said in a lawlawsuit filed Thursday that he suffered pain
and humiliation when school employees placed him in a wooden box
several times for up to one hour.
   The lawsuit filed by Demar and Dixie Elam said their 7-year-old
son, John, was put in the 2-foot-by-2-foot box in September at a
technical center while he waited for a school bus home.
   The lawsuit said the boy couldn't move anything but his head in
the box and suffered physical pain and humiliation, embarrassment
and mental anguish because other children made fun of him.
   Elam said he ``would not treat an animal'' the way his son was
treated.
   The box, which has an adjustable top that was placed at chin
level for John, is used at Madison County Technical Center during
physical therapy with students in performing such tasks as standing
up.
   The lawsuit names as defendants Rollin Gates and Jan Williams,
two workers at the center, charging them with neglect and-or wanton
supervision, false imprisonment and outrageous conduct.
   Jenny Van Dyke, special education coordinator for Madison County
schools, said the box was not intended as punishment but to keep
John from getting hurt or from running into traffic.
   ``We've tried to say we're sorry, what can we do? We've tried to
correct it,'' she said.
   Mrs. Van Dyke said she has told teachers that such restraints
are not to be used without notifying parents.
   The lawsuit, seeking unspecified damages, said the two workers
placed the boy in the box several times for 40 minutes to one hour
each time. Mrs. Van Dyke said the boy was placed in the box for
only 20 to 25 minutes four or five days.
   Elam said he found his son in the box Sept. 7 and took
photographs, which he presented to school officials. The couple
began driving John to and from school after that.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
