<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Hungary     11-02 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Hungary,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pozsgay Reports on Meeting With President Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungarian reform leader Imre Pozsgay said
Thursday that President Bush views the upcoming Mediterranean
superpower summit as advancing cooperation in Central Europe and
around the world.
   Pozsgay, speaking with reporters after a 30-minute Oval Office
meeting with the president, also said Bush promised to review trade
restrictions that currently keep high-tech products from being
shipped from the West into Hungary and other Soviet-bloc nations.
   Bush already has announced a major relaxation of trade barriers
with Hungary, including extension of most-favored-nation trading
status, to reward recent political reforms there.
   Hungary declared itself a democracy two weeks ago and Pozsgay is
a presidential candidate in elections to be held there later this
month.
   Pozsgay, who holds the title of minister of state, said Bush
``briefed me on what were his motivations regarding the summit.''
   ``He assured us that the whole region and European cooperation
and global cooperation could benefit from that, and naturally it
would be very benefical and advantageous to Hungary,'' Pozsgay said.
   ``All Central European nations can only profit'' from the
strengthening of East-West relations that the December summit
signifies, Pozsgay said through a translator.
   Pozsgay sidestepped a question on whether he would try to take
Hungary out of the Warsaw Pact if he is elected president.
   ``My view is that this is a global European problem that could
be resolved the best way by the elimination of both blocs,'' the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization of western countries and the
Warsaw Pact.
   Asked whether Bush had done enough for Hungary, he said: ``I
believe he has done what he could.''
   The White House issued a statement saying that during the
meeting, Bush ``restated his commitment to the success of Hungary's
democratic reforms, stressing that our support is for the process
of change rather than for any particular party or candidate.''
</TEXT>
