<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 1755EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Polish 1stLd-Writethru a0682 11-02 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Polish, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0682,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polish Official Says Aid Delay Threatens Solidarity Movement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Pozsgay in 8th graf, In a</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The speaker of the Polish parliament said
Thursday he told senior Bush administration and congressional
officials that further delays in economic aid to Poland could help
topple the Solidarity government.
   ``The situation is rather dramatic,'' said Mikolaj Kozakiewicz,
a leader of the Peasants Party and marshal of the lower house of
the Polish Sejm or parliament. Kozakiewicz said he urged U.S.
officials to move more quickly.
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa is expected to convey much the
same message during his scheduled visit to Washington this month.
   The Peasants Party last summer split from the Communist Party
coalition in parliament, opening the way for Solidarity activist
Tadeusz Mazowiecki to form the first non-communist government in
Eastern Europe since World War II.
   Kozakiewicz's party remains in the Solidarity coalition,
although there are differences over some policies.
   Congress has appropriated $100 million for food that is en route
to Poland. But further aid is stalled over Republican efforts to
attach to the Polish assistance bill an unrelated amendment to cut
the U.S. capital gains tax.
   Democrats have proposed sending Poland and Hungary $989 million
in aid over three years, while the Republicans have proposed a $585
million package.
   In a related development Thursday, President Bush met with
Hungarian reform leader Minister of State Imre Pozsgay. Bush
``restated his commitment to the success of Hungary's democratic
reforms,'' the White House said.
   Kozakiewicz met Wednesday with Deputy Secretary of State
Lawrence Eagleburger and on Capitol Hill with two sponsors of the
Polish aid package, Senate Majority Whip Alan Cranston, D-Calif.,
and Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill.
   Cranston and Simon, appearing at a luncheon for Kozakiewicz on
Wednesday, said they were continuing efforts to pass the aid
package.
   After the meeting with Eagleburger, the State Department said
the two men ``discussed the current political and economic
situation in Poland as well as the role of foreign assistance from
the West in helping Poles implement their economic programs.''
   Kozakiewicz, speaking with reporters Thursday at the Polish
Embassy, avoided commenting on wrangling between the administration
and Congress.
   But he repeatedly criticized Western governments for not moving
fast enough to get aid to Poland in the pipeline.
   ``All the major countries are all the time elaborating their
programs, but not sending aid,'' he said. West Germany has also
pledged a major aid package, but details may not be clear until
Chancellor Helmut Kohl visits Warsaw next week, he said.
   The delays ``mean that we will be sitting in the middle of
winter with the situation getting harder and harder.''
   The delays dishearten those Poles ``who traditionally trust the
West,'' and prompt ``malicious joy among those who do not trust the
West,'' he said.
   Most Poles still wish success for the first non-Communist
government in Poland since World War II, but they are running out
of food, heating coal, medical supplies and other necessities,
Kozakiewicz said.
   In addition to sending aid to Poland, the administration has
authorized the U.S. Overseas Private Investment Corporation (OPIC)
to insure American businessmen seeking to invest in Poland. The
insurance would protect Americans against the risk the Polish
government would change and expropriate their investment, said OPIC
spokesman James V. Hall.
   Fred M. Zeder, president of OPIC, will lead a delegation to
Poland on Monday to review 250 projects there that need private
investment, said Hall. About 25 companies are expected to send
representatives with Zeder.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
