<FIRST>r w AM-Pentagon-Pakistan     11-02 0152</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon-Pakistan,150</SECOND>
<TEXT>
   Pentagon Tells Congress of Arms Sale to Pakistan
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon informed Congress on Thursday
that Pakistan intends to buy four Phalanx weapons systems, a type
of Gatling gun used as a last-ditch defense against anti-ship
missiles.
   The estimated cost of the five-inch gun systems, which also
include ammunition, logistical support and training, amounts to $29
million, the Pentagon said in a statement.
   The weapons will provide a surface-to-air defensive capability
for frigates in the Pakistani Navy and will be in addition to the
earlier versions of the weapons systems that have been delivered to
their forces, the Pentagon said.
   The Pentagon also said that Pakistan intends to buy 13
Firefinder counter-mortar radar sets, 26 AN@VRC-46 radios and
logistical support at a cost of $65 million.
   The sale of both types of equipment will not affect the basic
military balance in the region, the Pentagon statement said.
