<FIRST>r a AM-Boy-Shooting     11-02 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boy-Shooting,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Young Boy Shoots Uncle; Father Remembers Similar Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PINE BLUFF, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ricky Jenkins was 7 when he removed a
pistol from his mother's purse and shot himself in the throat. This
week, his 5-year-old son took a pistol from a kitchen table and
killed his uncle.
   ``I just want parents to know that children don't know; they
don't know that a loaded gun can kill,'' Jenkins, 28, said. ``I
just want parents to know the danger they put their family in by
leaving loaded guns around.
   ``Those things happen, and all you can say is you're sorry, when
you could have been more responsible,'' he said.
   The shooting Sunday morning killed Jenkins' brother, John Evans,
33. Ricky Jenkins and his son were staying at Evans' apartment and
the 5-year-old was the first one awake Sunday morning. Police said
they did not know why the brothers had different last names.
   Evans had left the gun and some papers on the kitchen table
after cleaning out cabinets Saturday, and the shiny pistol
apparently sparked the child's curiosity, Jenkins said.
   Evans, who was asleep on the living room floor at the time, was
shot once in the upper torso with a .25-caliber semiautomatic
pistol. He got up, staggered out of the apartment and collapsed.
   Evans was pronounced dead less than an hour later.
   ``He picked it up, started playing with it and fired the gun
once,'' Sgt. Tommy Kelly of the Pine Bluff Police Department said.
``Guns are real interesting to small kids, and even if they have
been instructed not to mess with the weapons, a kid is going to
play with guns because they fascinate them.''
   Ricky Jenkins said that when he was 7, ``I was playing with a
gun and I shot myself. And I still have the bullet in me.''
</TEXT>
