<FIRST>r i AM-Kenya-Sudan     11-02 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kenya-Sudan,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Relief Flights to Sudan Resume after Town Bombed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Nations resumed relief flights
from Kenya to southern Sudan Thursday after a 24-hour suspension
following the bombing of a rebel-held town.
   Four people were killed in Tuesday's bombing of Yirol in Sudan's
southern Bahr el Ghazal province, 625 miles southwest of the
capital Khartoum, a U.N. source said.
   The Sudan People's Liberation Army clandestine radio said the
government bombed the town and swore revenge on the nation's
military strongman, Lt. Gen. Omar Hassan el-Bashir.
   ``The SPLA assures ... el-Bashir that his indiscriminate and
barbaric bombing of Yirol will not go long unpunished,'' the radio
said. ``Every war-mongering madness of el-Bashir will be quickly
met by a swift, iron-fisted retaliation that will cost the regime
another garrison town.''
   It said four civilians were killed and six civilians wounded.
   The U.N. source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
flights from Lokichoggio in northern Kenya _ suspended Wednesday _
resumed after safeguards were implemented involving radio contact
with relief personnel in southern Sudan and assurances the planes
would be met on arrival.
   The planes are part of a U.N.-coordinated operation that has
moved 107,000 tons of food and supplies into southern Sudan since
April in an effort to avert a repeat of last year's tragedy when an
estimated 250,000 people died of starvation.
   Until last week, government forces and rebels had observed a de
facto cease-fire in their nearly 7-year-old war in southern Sudan
to facilitate movement of relief supplies.
   However, hostilities appear to be on the rise. The Yirol bombing
came four days after rebels seized a town on Ethiopia's border
following days of fighting.
</TEXT>
