<FIRST>r w AM-Pentagon-Saudi     11-02 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon-Saudi,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Tells Congress of Arab Arms Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon said on Thursday that it informed
Congress of a $3.1 billion arms purchase by Saudi Arabia, touching
off a 30-day period in which Capitol Hill can reject the deal.
   The sale, which was reported in the media several weeks ago, has
touched off little opposition among lawmakers.
   In the past, Congress has rejected several U.S. arms sales to
Arab countries out of concern for Israel's security.
   But political maneuvering in recent weeks managed to diffuse the
concerns that customarily touch off strong opposition to U.S. deals
with Arab countries technically at war with Israel.
   ``The sale of this equipment and support will not affect the
basic military balance in the region,'' the Pentagon said in a
statement.
   It includes 315 M1A2 tanks, but two-thirds of the price tag _
which is equivalent to a year's U.S. aid to Israel _ is the cost of
equipment and ammunition, including huge trucks to transport any
tanks that break down.
   The sale also includes the design and construction of
maintenance facilities for the vehicles, the Pentagon said.
   The statement did not say where the tanks would be based.
   Several House members have written Secretary of State James A.
Baker III asking further consultations and raising some questions
about the sale, and Baker promised to provide assurances the arms
were necessary for the Saudi defense.
   With the formal notification, Congress has 30 days either to
kill the deal by majority votes in the Senate and House or let it
go through.
   The Saudis are to receive the tanks beginning in the middle of
the next decade, about the same time the U.S. Army would field
them. Israel has a comparable tank, the Merkava.
   To smooth congressional approval, the Bush administration agreed
not to equip the Saudi tanks with plates of uranium armor, a much
denser metal than steel.
   If some are deployed at the Tabuk military base the tanks would
be only 120 miles from Israel. Others may be based near Kuwait, and
still others at an armored training school near Mecca.
</TEXT>
