<FIRST>u w AM-Nicaragua-Rights     11-02 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Rights,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Release at 6:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<HEAD>Report Says Sandinista Forces Killed 74 Suspects</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Nicaragua, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaraguan forces were responsible for the
deaths of 74 Contra supporters in the northern part of the country
between 1987 and early 1989, a human rights group said in a report
released Thursday.
   Americas Watch, a private group based in New York, also said
Sandinista authorities were to blame for the disappearance of 14
others thought to support the rebels.
   On the other hand, Americas Watch said in a separate report that
the claim by State Department and Nicaraguan opposition groups that
5,000 to 7,000 Nicaraguans are being detained for political
offenses is ``patently false.''
   The report said the total of such prisoners is not significantly
greater than the 1,306 estimated by the International Committee for
the Red Cross last August.
   Americas Watch, which often has been critical of abuses by the
Nicaraguan Contras in previous reports, said the Sandinista record
in investigating the alleged killings is mixed.
   Some cases have resulted in convictions and punishment but
others have not, the report said.
   According to the report, Americas Watch researchers discovered
20 other possible killings in addition to the 74 but it said the
information on these cases was incomplete.
   It said the vast majority of the killings took place in the
remote mountains of northern Nicaragua.
   ``The concentration of so many cases in a particular geographic
area in this period led us to conclude that these killings
constituted a pattern, and could not be dismissed as isolated or
sporadic,'' it said.
   The pattern indicates that regional military or security forces
engaged in selective kidnappings and assassinations of persons
suspected of being Contra collaborators or couriers, it said.
   ``In most cases, bodies were found within hours or days, and in
many cases those corpses showed signs of brutal torture,'' the
report added.
</TEXT>
