<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 1837EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-SchoolBusSafety     11-02 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School Bus Safety,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parents of Boy Run Over by Bus Urge Better Mirrors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parents of a boy run over and killed by
the school bus he had been riding moments before appealed to
Congress Thursday to prevent the deaths of other children who stray
into ``blind spots'' not covered by the driver's mirrors.
   ``As sure as I'm standing here, there will be another child run
over by his school bus _ because he couldn't be seen _ before this
year is ended,'' Thomas Peterson of Howell, Mich., told a House
subcommittee.
   ``We cannot believe that any school system would risk the lives
of children for the sake of the extra dollars that adequate mirrors
would cost,'' said Peterson, whose 6-year-old son, Matthew, died in
1984 after he walked in front of his school bus and was struck as
it pulled away.
   Peterson and his wife, Kathy, appeared before the House Energy
and Commerce subcommittee on transportation and hazardous materials
to urge passage of a bill sponsored by Rep. Dennis Eckart, D-Ohio,
giving the federal government a deadline for toughening standards
for school bus mirrors.
   Those standards now require only one mirror reflecting one foot
in front of the bus; most states require two mirrors.
   Even with two mirrors, however, there's a large ``blind spot''
where a driver is unable to see a child directly in front of the
bus and on either side of it if he is within a foot of the vehicle.
   Eckart's bill would require special mirrors that eliminate
``blind spots.'' The mirrors, he and manufacturers estimate, would
cost about $100 per bus.
   Jeffrey Miller, acting administrator of the National Highway
Traffic Safety Administration, said the legislation is unnecessary
because the agency has already begun revising the rules to improve
a driver's visibility and require swing-out ``stop'' sign
attachments, now mandatory in 28 states.
   New standards could be in place in 14 months, Miller told the
hearing.
   But the chairman of the panel, Rep. Thomas Luken, D-Ohio, said
that's not good enough and the federal agency hasn't acted fast
enough.
   NHTSA is ``inherently, inately lethargic,'' he told Miller. ``I
think your comments here are that you're going to continue to be
lethargic.''
   A member of the National PTA board told the panel her meetings
with the NHTSA left her convinced the agency didn't consider the
issue a top priority. ``NHTSA's attitude was one of a `big yawn' _
insensitive and apathetic,'' said Millie Waterman of Mentor, Ohio.
   ``Today we're going to wake NHTSA up,'' promised Luken.
   On average, 26 children are killed and 470 children are injured
each year in the moments after getting off a school bus, according
to a report issued in May by a research arm of the National Academy
of Sciences. In each case, the children walked, ran or chased a
dropped object near the bus but outside the driver's field of
vision.
   Mrs. Waterman's husband, Harry, told Luken's subcommittee that
when he was in charge of transportation for Mentor's public schools
he installed state-of-the-art mirrors for about $100 a bus that
erased driver blind spots.
   The mirrors make the area in front of the bus and underneath the
front bumper visible to the drivers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
