<FIRST>r i AM-Haiti     11-02 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haiti,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leftist Opposition Leaders Arrested</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Three leftist leaders were arrested
after signing a statement calling on Haitians to rally against the
government of Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril, a private radio station said
Thursday.
   Radio Antilles said Jean-Auguste Mesyeux, Evans Paul and Etienne
Marino were arrested Wednesday night in suburban Carrefour by
police trailing their car. Mesyeux is co-leader of Haiti's biggest
union, the Autonomous Central of Haitian Workers.
   On Tuesday, more than 20 organizations that make up the
opposition coalition called National Assembly co-signed a statement
calling for a monthlong ``general mobilization'' against the
government, including marches and distribution of leaflets. The
three men were among the signers.
   The National Assembly includes the Haitian Communist Party and
the parties of major conservatives such as Louis Dejoie, Hubert De
Ronceray, and Sylvio Claude. It has denounced austerity measures
and alleged human rights abuses by the regime.
   ``The government is out of its mind. Instead of realizing how
unpopular its policies are, it is cracking down on popular
organizations,'' Dejoie told The Associated Press Thursday.
   Paul is leader of the Confederation of Democratic Unity party
and Marino heads the Sept. 17 Popular Organization, a group
inspired by the September 1988 soldiers' revolt that ousted
dictator Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy and brought Avril to power.
   Joseph Maxi, president of the Haitian Human Rights League, said
three presidential guardsmen entered his Carrefour home Wednesday
night searching for former guardsman Frantz Patrick Beauchard, a
member of Marino's group.
   Maxi said Beauchard asked him for legal help ``because he felt
his security was threatened.'' Beauchard was jailed for two months
and expelled from the army in December 1988 for allegedly plotting
to overthrow the government.
</TEXT>
