<HEAD>Panama Protest Naming of New U.S. Charge Without Accreditation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf after 3rd pvs, `The protest...' to ADD background
on Bushnell. Picks up 4th pvs, `He replaced ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega's government on
Thursday protested the appointment of a new chief of mission at the
U.S. Embassy, saying the diplomat was not accredited.
   The Foreign Ministry statement also said several American
diplomats are on an ``irregular'' status in Panama.
   The protest followed the announcement that John Bushnell, former
deputy chief of mission at the U.S. Embassy in Argentina, has been
named charge d'affaires at the U.S. Embassy.
   Bushnell, 59, a former staff member of the National Security
Council and former deputy assistant secretary for inter-American
affairs, also served in Colombia, the Dominican Republic and
Switzerland.
   He replaced John Maisto, who has been named the alternate U.S.
representative to the Organization of American States.
   The statement mentioned Bushnell by name and said his status and
those of other American diplomats ``is irregular, since their
function is to represent a government with which Panama does not
maintain normal relations.''
   The United States has refused to recognize the government since
February 1988, when federal grand juries in Florida indicted
Noriega on drug trafficking and money laundering charges and issued
warrants for his arrest.
   The United States imposed economic sanctions and has exerted
diplomatic pressure to remove Noriega from power.
   Soon after the indictments, President Eric Arturo Delvalle fired
Noriega as Defense Forces chief, but the Noriega-controlled
national legislature dismissed Delvalle instead. The Bush
administration has maintained that Delvalle is Panama's legitimate
head of state.
   Maisto was accredited three years ago, so the issue did not come
up until his replacement by Bushnell earlier this week.
   The United States withdrew Ambassador Arthur Davis to protest
Noriega's cancellation of the May 7 national election, in which
international observers said opposition candidate Guillermo Endara
defeated the government candidate by a landslide.
   On Sept. 1, Noriega named Francisco Rodriguez, a close friend,
as provisional president.
   Opposition groups insist that Endara won and should become the
next president.
</TEXT>
