<SECOND>AM-Bush-Helicopter,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Orders Copter to Leave so Medivac Copter Could Land</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush ordered his helicopter, Marine
One, to take off from Walter Reed Army Medical Center without him
Thursday so that a Coast Guard emergency medical copter could land.
   Bush had flown to the hospital from the White House to visit
ailing former Salvadoran President Jose Napoleon Duarte.
   The president was talking with reporters outside Walter Reed
when the Coast Guard helicopter began circling, unable to land
because Bush's craft was still parked there.
   ``Excuse me, got an emergency coming in on the chopper,'' Bush
said, abruptly ending the session with reporters.
   He climbed into in his limosene and ordered Marine One to take
off empty, according to presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater.
   The Coast Guard copter was rushing Coast Guard Petty Officer
Daniel Willis to Walter Reed from Cape May, N.J., to treat an acute
case of kidney stones, Fitzwater said.
   The medivac copter deposited its passenger and then left. Marine
One landed and picked up Bush.
