<FIRST>r w AM-InformationServices     11-02 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Information Services,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>For release 8:30 p.m. EST; time set by source</HEAD>
<HEAD>FCC Chairman Urges Newspapers To Join Phone Companies In Electronic
Publishing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newspapers should join, not fight, telephone
companies in the electronic publishing field, a top federal
regulator told a newspaper publishers meeting Thursday.
   Alfred Sikes, chairman of the Federal Communications Commission,
said newspapers could use their publishing experience to boost the
nation's telecommunications infrastructure and help assure that
Americans derive the same ``information age'' benefits that other
nations are beginning to enjoy.
   ``I think there's a good opportunity today for publishing
companies to capitalize on their experience and move into
electronic delivery of their product,'' Sikes told a meeting of the
American Newpaper Publishers Association.
   ``Obviously, the American newspaper industry understands that
videotext services will ultimately have a significant impact on
your industry,'' Sikes said, noting newspaper opposition to
telephone companies providing such service. ``I would like to
suggest, however, that as lines of demarcation blur, partnerships
can often work better than rear guard actions.''
   Electronic publishing includes computer-based data and voice
messaging services and advertising programs such as electronic
Yellow Pages.
   The seven regional Bell operating companies were barred in the
1984 breakup of the American Telephone and Telegraph Co. from
entering the so-called information services industry out of fear
they would use their huge resources to kill competition.
   But U.S. District Court Judge Harold Greene, who oversaw the
AT&amp;T divestiture, later said the Bell companies may provide
voice-messaging services and also act as ``gateways'' by providing
single phone numbers that will reach multiple information service
providers. The Bells still cannot offer the information services
themselves.
   The ANPA opposes the Bell companies' entry into electronic
publishing as long as the Bells have monopoly control of the local
telephone networks. The ANPA believes many of the Bell companies
have resisted fully developing the gateways in hopes of dismantling
the line-of-business prohibitions in the 1984 AT&amp;T consent decree.
   Congress and the White House are considering whether to lift
some of those restrictions on the Bell companies, and Sikes, during
his confirmation hearings earlier this year, told Congress he
supported lifting the line-of-business prohibitions.
   Major U.S. electronic publishers already include Knight-Ridder,
Dow Jones and Reuters, and Sikes, in his address Thursday, said
newspaper-telephone company partnerships ``make sense, since each
would bring complementary talents to the bargain.''
   ``The underlying rationale of the many mergers in today's
communications market is that there are real synergies available
from product line to product line and by viewing software, hardware
and distribution assets as complementary,'' he said.
   Sikes said European publishers such as France's Hachette
organization have been working with France Telecom to develop its
Minitel videotext system. He noted these companies already have
entered the North American market in Montreal and Dallas, where
``they should have something of a competitive edge'' already.
   ``We want to make sure that America's leading firms have some
degree of competitive parity,'' Sikes said.
   ``It seems to me you might want to concentrate increasingly on
helping assure a fair and rational regulatory framework within
which this country's full resources can be utilized,'' Sikes said.
``There are logical options reasonably available here, including
efforts to blend the complementary talents of the publishing and
telephone industries.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
