<FIRST>r i AM-Austria-Hungary     11-02 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Austria-Hungary,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>Austria to Ask Compensation from Hungary in Dam Project</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Austria said Thursday it will ask $300
million in damages from Hungary, which decided this week to stop
work on a Danube River hydroelectric project.
   Economics Minister Wolfgang Schuessel said the halt was
considered a breach of contract by the state-owned Austrian
contractor Donaukraftwerke, which was doing 70 percent of the work
on the Hungarian part of the $3 billion joint project with
Czechoslovakia.
   He said the government would ask 4 billion schillings in
compensation.
   Austrian state companies contracted to build much of the
Hungarian power complex at Nagymaros in return for future power
supplies.
   Tuesday's vote in the Hungarian parliament to stop work, which
is near completion on the Czechoslovak side, came five months after
Hungary declared a moratorium because of mounting costs and fear of
environmental damage.
   Czechoslovakia, a conservative Warsaw Pact ally displeased by
Hungary's turn toward democracy, also demands compensation. Its
Communist Party daily, Rude Pravo, said Thursday the decision to
abandon the project ``is motivated not by ecological, but mainly
political reasons.''
