<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-02 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow Closes Schools in Parts of Michigan, Wisconsin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy snow shut down schools and businesses in parts of Michigan
and northern Wisconsin on Thursday, while rain plagued the
Southeast.
   Michigan's western Upper Peninsula was covered in up to 36
inches of snow that had fallen since Tuesday. Snow-plowing crews
were forced off the streets Thursday by too much snow and ice.
   The snow snarled traffic, but no serious accidents or injuries
were reported.
   Scattered electrical outages were reported in Ironwood, Mich.
Four public school districts shut down, along with Gogebic County
buses and some businesses in Ironwood, sheriff's Deputy Jay Kangas
said.
   Far northern Wisconsin got two feet of snow since Wednesday.
   ``They (residents) don't like it, but they're used to it,'' said
Larry Baldovin, sheriff in Iron County, Wis.
   Geri Zaelski, a bookkeeper for Hurley, Wis., Public Schools,
struggled through hip-deep drifts to get to work even though
schools were closed.
   ``I live only two blocks from work and I had too much work to do
to miss a whole day,'' she said.
   The snow was attributed to low pressure over Lake Huron.
   Light snow was scattered across the upper Mississippi Valley,
eastern portions of the Dakotas and the Minneapolis area of
Minnesota.
   Rainshowers ahead of a cold front in the Southeast were
scattered from the central Gulf Coast to Georgia and South Carolina.
   Cloudy skies prevailed from the Mississippi Valley to the
Atlantic Coast and from the Dakotas to Washington, with sunny skies
across much of the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures dipped below freezing in the Great Plains region,
with single-digit readings as far south as southeast Colorado.
   Highs in Florida were in the 70s and 80s, with temperatuers in
the 60s in the Gulf Coast.
   A new record low for the date _ 22 degrees _ was set in Midland,
Texas. The old record, set in 1966, was 27 degrees.
   The morning cold spots in the Lower 48 states were Grand Forks,
N.D., and Yellowstone National Park, Wyo. Both had lows of 4
degrees.
</TEXT>
