<FIRST>u a AM-DakotasBirthdays 1stLd-Writethru a0661 11-02 0714</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dakotas Birthdays, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0661,0728</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dakotas Celebrate Birthdays With Bells, Song</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, `Star-covered...', with three grafs to UPDATE
with festivities at civic center. Picks up 10th graf, `It is...'. SUBS
grafs 15-16, `State officials...', with three grafs to UPDATE with South
Dakota events and quote from first governor's descendant.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEG COUGHLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bells, sirens and thousands of children's
voices rang out across two states Thursday as both Dakotas marked
their 100th birthdays. Each was admitted to the union on Nov. 2,
1889 _ though residents continue to argue good-naturedly about
which really was first.
   Pony Express riders carrying messages between the two states
``ran flat out'' trying to emulate the riding of their
predecessors, and the events of 1889 and other pioneer milestones
were re-enacted.
   North Dakota Gov. George Sinner kidded his South Dakota
counterpart, Gov. George Mickelson, after Mickelson arrived a few
minutes late for a morning radio show in which the governors wished
each other's states a Happy Birthday.
   ``I thought it was appropriate that you got in a minute or two
late,'' Sinner told Mickelson. ``We did some research, and it turns
out that North Dakota was actually the first of these states to
become states, and so that minute or two was just exactly right.''
   Officials said not even President Benjamin Harrison, who signed
the Nov. 2 proclamation that created both states, knew which one
came first even though North Dakota was admitted as the 39th state
and South Dakota as the 40th.
   ``President Harrison really did kind of a wonderful thing when
he shuffled those papers and didn't let anybody know who was
first,'' said Jim Sawyer, assistant director of the South Dakota
Centennial Commission.
   ``The president covered the papers up and then he said `They
were born together, they are one, and I shall make them twins.'
Then he shuffled them again and signed them. Even he doesn't know
which one came first.''
   North Dakota invited to the state capital more than 6,000
second-graders _ scheduled to graduate from high school in the year
2000 _ to join in song during festivities at the Bismarck Civic
Center.
   The pupils helped in the official countdown to 3:40 p.m._ the
exact moment when North Dakota became a state 100 years ago. Then
balloons fell from the ceiling and the arena erupted into a
boisterous round of ``Happy Birthday.''
   ``Just think if everybody would have brought a present,'' said
David Schaefer, from New Rockford, gazing at a wall festooned with
hundreds of birthday cards made by students around the state.
   An arch fashioned of red, white and blue balloons stretched over
the stage, which was flanked by the North Dakota state seal and
centennial logo.
   ``It is a sense that we are bringing back a little history,''
said one of the Pony Express riders, Ken Tischmak of Shields.
Tischmak's horse, Firewater, is a Spanish mustang, a descendant of
the breed used in the original Pony Express, he said.
   ``We went all out,'' he said. ``We tried to do it as close as we
could to the way they did it originally. And when they ran it
originally, they ran flat out.''
   Erma Bohrer of Napoleon arranged stacks of napkins as she
prepared to serve cake and cupcakes to celebrants. About 6,500
cupcakes were made, plus eight large cakes decorated with North
Dakota's centennial logo.
   ``I'm getting excited, getting ready for a rush,'' she said.
   In South Dakota, Watertown was declared ``Capital for a Day.''
It was the home of the state's first governor, Arthur C. Mellette.
   State officials were on hand for a re-enactment of Mellette's
swearing-in ceremony, abbreviated by subfreezing temperatures and a
stiff wind. The ceremony followed a parade from the restored
Mellette House.
   ``This is wonderful, terrific,'' said Mellette's
great-granddaughter, Mimi Ide Suverkrup, of Cedar Pines Park,
Calif. ``Although I never met him, Arthur was always sort of a
grand figure to me, somewhat of a reserved but benevolent person.''
   The weather was slightly chillier than in 1889, with light snow
and highs in the 20s over both states. Weather records show both
states had highs in the 40s and 50s on Nov. 2, 1889, said Bill
Abeling, meteorologist at the National Weather Service in Bismarck.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
