<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua 2ndLd-Writethru a0704 11-02 0842</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0704,0864</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sandinista Troops Launch Attacks in Central, Northern Mountains</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 3rd graf, President Daniel ... to UPDATE
with Bush hints renewed aid. Picks up 4th graf, The Contras ... with minor
editing to trim. Four grafs SUB for final 5 grafs, 23-27, U.S. officials
... UPDATING with human rights report</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MGA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sandinista troops launched attacks in
Nicaragua's central and northern mountains Thursday to try to wipe
out outnumbered Contra forces that have infiltrated from Honduras,
according to reports.
   Lt. Col. Rosa Pasos, a military spokeswoman, said most of the
action was concentrated on rebels sneaking into Nicaragua, but she
would confirm only one attack near Quilali, in the border province
of Nueva Segovia.
   President Daniel Ortega ended a 19-month cease-fire on
Wednesday, saying the Contras had been stepping up attacks inside
Nicaragua. He also blamed the United States for the renewed attacks
and accused President Bush of promoting ``terrorism.''
   Bush on Thursday appeared to reopen the possibility he may seek
a renewal of U.S. military aid for the Contras, saying ``we will
leave our options open'' now that the Sandinistas resumed military
attacks.
   The Contras announced Thursday they had accepted in principle a
Sandinista offer to meet Monday and Tuesday at the United Nations
to discuss demobilization. Roman Catholic Cardinal Miguel Obando y
Bravo said he had also accepted an invitation.
   In a communique, the Contras said they were still awaiting an
official invitation from a U.N.-Organization of American States
commission set up to verify Central American peace accords.
   The Sandinista party newspaper Barricada said Thursday that
combat units in 14 towns in northern Nicaragua began operations
overnight, but neither the newspaper nor Ms. Pasos gave details.
   The Contra communique, distributed by the Nicaraguan Resistance
in Tegucigalpa, Honduras, said the Sandinistas mounted attacks
Wednesday with tanks, helicopter gunships and heavy artillery.
   Ms. Pasos refused to comment and said she had no immediate
reports on casualties or details of the fighting.
   In Tegucigalpa, Contra commander Enrique Bermudez said the
Contras would continue observing the cease-fire because they have
not had the resources to launch attacks since U.S. non-lethal aid
was cut off in February 1988.
   ``These troops will only carry out evasive actions,'' said
Bermudez.
   Contra field commanders began moving their troops back into
Nicaragua from Honduras after Central American peace accords were
signed Aug. 7, but said they would await the outcome of national
elections set for Feb. 25 before deciding whether to launch
offensive operations.
   The accords called for voluntary Contra demobilization in
exchange for democratic reforms in Nicaragua, but the Contras were
not a party to the agreement and said they would not disband.
   In Washington, the House of Representatives voted 379-29 for a
non-binding resolution denouncing Ortega's resumption of military
action against the rebels.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Thursday it was
unrealistic to expect the Contras to lay down their arms when the
leftist Sandinista government is out ``to destroy them.''
   State Department deputy spokesman Richard Boucher said the
administration believes the Contra reports that the Sandinistas
have commenced major military operations in at least two regions in
Nicaragua.
   Honduran President Jose Azcona Hoyo urged Ortega to reconsider
his decision on the cease-fire. ``Ortega's decision is deplorable.
Nevertheless, I hope he meditates ... and rectifies it,'' he said
in Tegucigalpa.
   The Hondurans also accused the Sandinistas of attacking a
Honduran army post Monday in the border town of Las Manos. Col.
Manuel Suarez Benavides said there were no casualties.
   A duty officer at the Nicaraguan Defense Ministry said he wasn't
familiar with the alleged incident and could not comment
immediately.
   Ms. Pasos said most of the operations, which started near the
Honduran border, were in north and south-central Nicaragua.
   Ms. Pasos put the number of Contra fighters inside Nicaragua at
2,500; U.S. estimates put it at 4,000 and Bermudez said there were
more than 6,000. They face the 70,000-member Sandinista armed
forces.
   Ms. Pasos accused the Contras of using the cease-fire to bolster
their positions and prepare for further attacks inside his country.
   U.S. officials earlier ruled out immediate resumption of
military aid to the Contras and the Bush administration said it was
consulting with Central American leaders to bring diplomatic
pressure on Ortega.
   Nicaraguan government and Contra representatives signed a
temporary truce in March 1988, but when peace talks broke down
three months later, the Sandinistas continued extending the
cease-fire every month.
   In a report Thursday, Americas Watch, a private human rights
group based in New York, held the Sandinistas responsible for the
deaths of 74 Contra supporters in northern Nicaragua from 1987 to
early 1989 and for the disappearance of 14 others thought to
support the rebels.
   But in a separate report it called ``patently false'' a claim by
State Department and Nicaraguan opposition groups that 5,000 to
7,000 Nicaraguans are being detained for political offenses. It
said the 1,306 estimated by the International Committee for the Red
Cross last August was nearer the mark.
</TEXT>
