<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 2042EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DC-10CrashHearing     11-02 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DC-10 Crash Hearing,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>GE Official Acknowledges Inadequate Records On Fan Serial Numbers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEERY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIOUX CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A General Electric official acknowledged
Thursday that no records exist to prove a serial number mixup
wasn't responsible for a faulty engine part placed in the United
Airlines DC-10 that crashed July 19.
   But James Tucker, general manager of the GE airplane engine
plant in Evendale, Ohio, testified before federal safety
investigators that company officials are certain that two fan disks
numbered 00385 were not mixed up.
   One of the disks was intended for the scrap heap, while the
other was approved for installation in a DC-10.
   A fan disk with that serial number broke apart in flight and is
being blamed for the crash of United Flight 232 as it made an
emergency landing at Sioux City's airport. The crash killed 112
people.
   The fan disk was made in 1971. A National Transportation Safety
Board report found a tiny crack that experts say probably existed
before the crash. When GE pulled manufacturing records on the disk
after the crash, it discovered that two disks had mistakenly been
given the same serial number in 1971.
   One of those disks was deemed faulty after testing that year and
was slated to be scrapped. The other disk was sent on through the
manufacturing process.
   Tucker said the two disks would have been stored in different
areas of the Ohio plant and were tested three months apart. Records
show the part that failed GE's testing was sent to another company
for further testing and the flaw was confirmed, Tucker said.
   But he acknowledged that no records exist to prove the company's
claim that the two disks with the same serial number were not
confused. Tucker said he too believes the two disks were not mixed
up.
   ``I made an analogy of a person being hit over the head and his
wallet being stolen,'' Tucker testified Thursday at the NTSB
hearing into the crash.
   ``And so somebody comes up to him and said, `Show me what your
name is and give us proof of who you are.' He can't do it. But then
they take him down to fingerprint him and then they find out who he
is.''
   Tucker said the second test that found a flaw in the same spot
as the earlier test on the faulty disk ``is the fingerprint of that
particular disk.''
   D.B. Robinson, an accident investigator for the Air Line Pilots
Association, said Thursday during a break on the hearing's fourth
day that questions about any serial mixup remain without adequate
proof.
   ``I don't think the records exist properly to answer that
question right now,'' he said.
   ``I'm not satisfied, but I'm not dissatisfied, either,''
Robinson said. ``The (safety) board will discover what's going on.
It will be resolved.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891102-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 2145EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-People-Goode 1stLd-Writethru a0633 11-02 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Goode, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0633,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Philly Mayor Back In Hospital for Tests</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with cardiologist's comments; ADDS mayor's
age.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor W. Wilson Goode entered a hospital
Thursday for the second time in two weeks after experiencing an
irregular heartbeat.
   Doctors said the mayor's condition was not life threatening and
he felt fine. The 51-year-old mayor will remain hospitalized until
Saturday for tests.
   ``We believe it is an innocent type of heart irregularity which
can be seen in individuals with normal hearts,'' said his
cardiologist, Dr. Edward S. Cooper.
   From early Wednesday to early Thursday, Goode experienced three
bouts of rapid heartbeats lasting from 30 seconds to several
minutes, doctors said.
   The latest occcured at 5 a.m. Thursday while the mayor was being
monitored in the Hospital of the University of Pennsylvania.
   ``I have no idea yet what is triggering these rapid but normal
heartbeats. Whether it is overwork or something, I can't say right
now,'' Cooper said.
   Goode first went to the hospital Oct. 20 after complaining of
head and neck pain. After tests, another physician said Goode had a
normal heart and attributed his symptoms to sinus problems.
   Cooper said more tests will be taken before Goode is discharged.
   ``If we come up with nothing, we have to assume it has something
to do with his 16-hour work days, and maybe he should slow down,''
Cooper said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
