<FIRST>r a AM-People-Burns     11-02 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Burns,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>George Burns at 93: I `Can't Afford To Die'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Burns at 93 says he knows he's old enough
for his body to quit on him but he has so many projects in the
works that he ``can't afford to die.''
   One of them is a two-week appearance at the London Palladium in
January 1996, when the comedian will celebrate his 100th birthday.
   ``You can't do anything about dying,'' he told USA Weekend in
its Nov. 3-5 issue. ``I don't think I'm going to die for a long
time because I'm busy.''
   These days he's pushing his newly released show-biz memoir,
``All My Best Friends;'' a new comedy video, ``George Burns: His
Wit and Wisdom;'' and hopes to begin filming ``Oh, God! Book IV''
as soon as he finds a script he likes.
   ``I think the most important thing is to fall in love with what
you do for a living. It's nice to get out of bed and do something
that day that you're going to love,'' he said.
   His day-to-day chores are made more difficult by arthritis,
astigmatism and hearing loss and he had a bypass operation at age
79, but Burns says he is looking toward the future.
   ``I'm not interested in things I've done. I'm interested in what
I'm doing right now and what I'm doing tomorrow,'' he said.
</TEXT>
