<SECOND>AM-Peru, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0574,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Patrols Lima After Guerrilla Attack</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE with police arresting 13 people
from reputed rebel newspaper, U.S. advisory on travel. Picks up 12th pvs,
`Official reports...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW SCOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers took control of highways leading into
the capital and armored units patrolled the city Thursday, the day
after a bold attack by leftist guerrillas on police guarding a
religious procession.
   Police arrested 13 employees of the newspaper El Diario,
considered the public voice of the Maoist Shining Path rebels,
officials said.
   Officials said two guerrillas were killed and at least 15 people
wounded in the battle at an All Saints' Day observance in a
working-class district.
   El Peruano, the government newspaper, said the decree placing
Lima and its port of Callao under military control was a response
to the call by the Shining Path for a general strike in Lima Friday.
   Shining Path has designated it an ``armed strike,'' implying
violence against anyone who does not cooperate.
   Major political parties and candidates for municipal office in
Lima scheduled a ``March for Peace'' on Friday to counter the
strike. Candidates for the April presidential election said they
would join the march.
   The guerrillas are trying to disrupt nationwide municipal
elections set for Nov. 12. Shining Path has killed at least 120
mayors, candidates and local officials this year, which caused
hundreds more to quit in fear.
   In Washington, the State Department on Thursday advised U.S.
citizens against traveling to Peru until after the elections.
   Lima and Callao have been under a state of emergency that
suspends civil rights and gives authorities broad powers in
fighting the insurgents, but national police had been in charge
until Thursday.
   Other areas affected by the emergency _ about one-third of the
country and half the 21 million people _ have been under military
jurisdiction.
   Government spokesman Mario Betayeluz said the condition was
short of martial law despite the military involvement.
   Radio reports Thursday said the military was exerting strict
control along the main routes into Lima: the coastal Pan-American
Highway, which runs through the city, and the Central Highway
leading east to the Andes.
   Other reports said guerrillas were stopping buses on rural
highways and confiscating electoral identification cards from the
passengers.
   El Diario is widely known as a voice of the Shining Path, and
has been used by the group to claim responsibility for attacks and
to urge people to support the group's calls for strikes.
   El Diario's director Janet Talavera was arrested earlier this
year and is still in detention on charges of supporting terrorism,
while editor Luis Arce Borja is in self-imposed exile in Europe.
   Official reports and witnesses to Wednesday's battle said 100 to
150 Shining Path guerrillas and supporters began marching in the
working class district of La Victoria. The area was filled with
people for a religious procession on All Saints' Day.
   Interior Minister Agustin Mantilla said two rebels were killed
and 15 people wounded. He said about 150 people were arrested.
   President Alan Garcia said on TV Thursday night at least some of
the wounded and 100 or more of those arrested were known to have
connections with Shining Path, which began its insurgency in 1980
near the Andean city of Ayacucho, 235 miles southeast of Lima.
   The government says more than 15,000 people have been killed in
the insurgency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
