<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 2212EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-Election     11-02 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Election,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>Late Entrant in Presidential Race Holds Surprise Lead in Poll</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEN SILVERSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A TV entertainer and millionaire
businessman who declared his candidacy for president just two days
ago holds a wide lead among voters questioned about the race,
according to a poll released Thursday.
   Last-minute entrant Silvio Santos, a conservative running on the
ticket of the small Brazilian Municipalist Party, was the choice of
29 percent of the voters queried by the Gallup Institute.
   The poll, published in the newspaper O Estado de Sao Paulo,
comes less than two weeks before the scheduled Nov. 15 election.
Santos, a former street vendor who has strong support among the
poor, declared his candidacy Tuesday but still faces legal
challenges.
   The newspaper said the support for center-right candidate
Fernando Collor de Mello, who had led the polls for six months,
plunged from 29.3 percent to 18.6 percent among those questioned.
   The nationwide poll was conducted between Oct. 26 and Wednesday,
with people interviewed at random in the street and their homes.
The margin of error was 3 percent.
   Santos' candidacy still faces legal challenges before it can be
registered with the Supreme Electoral Court.
   Accusations have been made that Santos, a TV entertainer who
owns more than 30 businesses, paid off former Municipalist Party
candidate Armando Correa to resign.
   The court must also decide if Santos violated a law that
requires corporate directors to step down from their positions
three months before declaring their candidacy.
   Santos, who runs the SBT television network, the nation's second
largest, says he is a shareholder and not a director in the
company, and thus exempt from the law.
   A ruling on Santos' bid may not come until Nov. 13, two days
before the vote.
   Collor de Mello, whose base of support is with the rural poor,
was hardest hit by Santos' candidacy but other major candidates saw
their support fall as well, according to the poll.
   Rep. Luis Inacio Lula da Silva, of the socialist Workers' Party
came in third with the support of 10.6 percent of those questioned,
down from 12.4 percent in the last poll.
   Left-wing populist Leonel Brizola, a former governor, was
fourth, receiving 9.9 percent, a drop of 2.8 percent.
   Mario Covas, of the Brazilian Social Democratic Party, was fifth
with 8 percent support, down slightly from 8.2 percent in last
week's poll.
   Eight percent of those questioned were unsure who they would
vote for, and 5.6 percent said they would cast blank ballots.
   Gallup conducted a simultaneous poll that excluded Santos from
the presidential contenders.
   Without Santos in the race, 27.5 percent of those questioned
favored Collor de Mello, followed by da Silva at 13.8 percent,
Brizola with 12.7 percent and Covas at 10.6 percent.
   On Nov. 15, 82 million Brazilians are to choose a successor to
President Jose Sarney for a five-year term, the first popular vote
for president since 1960. Sarney was selected by an Electoral
College influenced by the military regime that ruled the country
from 1964 to 1985.
   If no candidate wins a majority Nov. 15, the two top
vote-getters will face each other in a runoff in December.
   Santos' entrance into the race was criticized by left- and
right-wing candidates, who agreed Sarney was behind the maneuver.
The president has been harshly attacked by the campaign's leading
contenders, who blame him for 1,300 percent inflation and
corruption.
   Sarney by law cannot run for re-election.
</TEXT>
