<FIRST>r i AM-Australia-Dinosaur     11-02 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Australia-Dinosaur,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Species Of Dinosaur Believed Found in Australian Outback</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists said Thursday they believe a
previously unknown species of dinosaur has been found in the
Australian Outback by a rancher who stumbled on a
100-million-year-old skeleton while herding cattle.
   Queensland Museum officials said the son of a property owner
discovered the fossilized skull of a 16-foot pliosaur, or
short-necked reptile, sticking out of a creekbed after heavy rains
three weeks ago.
   Mary Wade, the museum's curator of palaentology, called the find
significant and said it was one of the best preserved ever found
here.
   ``It has been preserved even down to the tiny bones in its
flipper,'' she said. ``It is not recognizable as anything we have
seen in Australia to date. We are checking the literature but we
think it might be a new species.''
   She said the complete skeleton was removed from a property near
Richmond in northwest Queensland, Australia's northern subtropical
state, and that the family did not want publicity.
   The creature was a carnivore that lived in the inland sea that
covered most of western Queensland about 100 million years ago.
Along with the remains were those of prehistoric fish and turtles
believed to have been the animal's prey.
   To remove the fossils, the team removed soil and rock from
around them before wrapping them in plaster bandages. The fossils
were then removed in blocks to ensure they were kept in order.
   The museum said the find eventually would be displayed.
</TEXT>
