<FIRST>r i AM-Finland-Soviet     11-02 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Finland-Soviet,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Objections Scrap Finnish-Soviet Visa Deal, Newspaper Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Objections by Finnish security police
scuttled a draft agreement between Finland and the Soviet Union to
waive visa requirements, newspapers reported Thursday.
   The agreement was to have been signed here last week during
Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev's state visit.
   A report originating in the Uusi Suomi daily said negotiations
broke down due to opposition from Finnish police, who feared
security problems from an upsurge of Soviet vistors and potential
defectors.
   Instead, the two countries last week signed a ``memorandum of
intent'' to ease visa bureaucracy, together with 30 other joint
agreements, it added.
   The Finnish consulate in the Estonian capital of Tallinn granted
more than 32,000 visas by Oct. 31, more than 10 times the 3,000
granted in 1988.
   Police declined to comment on the report.
   Foreign Ministry official Marita Eerikainen said only that the
question could still be reviewed.
   ``The Soviet Union has not waived visa requirements with any
Western country, but as perestroika continues there seems to be a
real desire (in the Soviet Union) for a change in this policy,''
Eerikainen said.
   Eerikainen said a system of multiple entry visas already was in
use for some categories of visitors, such as business people and
students.
</TEXT>
