<FIRST>u a AM-IowaExplosion     11-02 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iowa Explosion,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Family Says Battleship Victim Told of Earlier Turret Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT NEWS, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sailor killed in the gun turret
explosion aboard the battleship USS Iowa had told his family of
previous firing problems and said ``goof-offs'' were ``going to get
us killed,'' a newspaper reported Thursday.
   Members of Jack E. Thompson Jr.'s family said the gunner's mate
told them of a February incident in which the No. 2 turret _ where
the fatal explosion occurred last April _ was ordered to fire with
its right 16-inch gun too close to a forward turret, the Daily
Press of Newport News reported.
   The blast blew off the rubber protective bellows of the forward
turret's guns.
   According to an aunt, Mary T. Wahler, Thompson also told
relatives of an earlier accidental firing and a fire inside the
turret.
   The Daily Press reported that Thompson, 22, of Greeneville,
Tenn., complained to his wife, Leasa, that ``there were a bunch of
goof-offs in the turret.''
   ``He said they were `going to get us killed someday,''' Mrs.
Thompson said.
   Rear Adm. Brent Baker, the Navy's chief of information at the
Pentagon, said, ``There was no accident back in February. It's not
true.''
   But two sailors confirmed to the newspaper that the incident
happened. One, former gunner's mate Roy Frazier, was assigned to
the No. 1 turret at the time the incident was said to have
occurred. The other sailor was not identified by the newspaper.
   None of the incidents were mentioned in the Navy's investigation
of the explosion. That report found the explosion ``most likely''
was caused by sabotage by a disgruntled gunner's mate, Clayton
Hartwig, who died in the blast.
   In Thompson's last letter to his wife, written eight days before
the explosion, he expressed uneasiness about the upcoming gunnery
exercise.
   ``We've got a dangerous shoot coming up. It's always scary,'' he
wrote.
   Mrs. Thompson said her husband never explained why the exercise
was any more dangerous than others.
</TEXT>
