<FIRST>r a AM-Thornburgh-ADL     11-02 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thornburgh-ADL,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thornburgh Vows To Help All Soviet Jews Wanting To Immigrate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Attorney General Dick Thornburgh said
Thursday he was determined to open the United States to any Jew
wanting to leave the Soviet Union.
   Thornburgh, speaking to the national Civil Rights Committee of
the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith, said immigration quotas
limit the number of Soviets to 50,000 annually, but the Bush
administration has proposed an increase of 30,000.
   ``We must see that the window of emigration that is now open is
left open,'' he said. ``The United States has been a beacon for
those who aspire to breath the fresh air of freedom, and we don't
want to slam a door in the face of anyone who seeks to come here.''
   Thornurgh spoke about his recent trip to the Soviet Union, where
he met with activists, and said everyone agreed the new openness
instigated by Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev had truly brought
change.
   ``In 1976, when I was last in the Soviet Union, only 787 Jews
were allowed to emigrate to the United States,'' the attorney
general said. ``In 1990, there will be more than 100,000
applications.''
   Soviet Jewish emigration has increased dramatically under
Gorbachev, from 8,000 in 1987 to 19,000 last year and a projected
35,000 in 1989. Non-Jewish emigration this year is expected to
reach 15,000.
   But new U.S. immigration rules have aroused some fears that
Soviet Jews could forced to go elsewhere. Under rules effective
Oct. 1, Soviet Jews no longer can leave that country with visas for
Israel, then apply in Vienna or Rome for refugee status in the
United States. Instead, the refugees' paperwork is being processed
at the U.S. Embassy in Moscow, the same as any other would-be
immigrant's.
</TEXT>
