<FIRST>r a AM-MeaslesEpidemic     11-02 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Measles Epidemic,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Measles Epidemic Claims 17 Lives This Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A measles epidemic has killed 17 people and
hospitalized hundreds in Southern California this year, racing
through vulnerable ethnic communities and college campuses, public
health officials said.
   While outbreaks of measles have been reported this year in
Chicago and Houston, the epidemic in five Southern California
counties is the nation's biggest and has sputtered and flared for
more than two years.
   ``It's very hard to keep control in a large urban area where you
have a large influx of people from other countries,'' Dr. Gary
Euler of the San Bernardino County Public Health Department said
Thursday.
   State health officials also have been forced to contend with a
shortage of vaccine, said Dr. Loring Dales, chief of immunization
for the California Department of Health Services. And vaccine
prices jumped sharply in 1988 as the demand for inoculations soared
30 percent, Dales said.
   Dales blames the epidemic on the lack of immunization among
children.
   In recent weeks, at least eight University of California at Los
Angeles students have contracted measles, threatening another
flare-up.
   At least 1,629 cases have been reported in Los Angeles County
alone since the stubborn outbreak began in August 1987, said Chuck
Alexander, director of immunization for the Los Angeles County
Health Department. That includes 12 deaths so far this year and two
reported in 1988.
   Another 1,259 cases have been counted in 1989 in San Bernardino,
Riverside, Orange and San Diego counties, including five deaths in
San Bernardino.
   Typical measles symptoms include fever, headache, sore eyes,
heavy coughing and a rash blossoming in the fourth or fifth day,
Dales said.
</TEXT>
