<FIRST>r a AM-NunDisappears     11-02 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nun Disappears,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nun Who Received Threatening Letters in Guatemala Disappears</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nun who received threatening letters
while working as a religious educator in Guatemala disappeared
Thursday from a retreat house there, members of her order said.
   Sister Diana Ortiz, 31, had been praying alone in a courtyard at
the Belene Sisters Retreat House in Antigua between 8 and 9 a.m.
when she disappeared, said Sister Mary Elizabeth Dallard, of the
Mount St. Joseph Ursuline Sisters of Maple Mount, Ky.
   Members of the Roman Catholic order fear Ortiz has been
kidnapped, but no group has claimed responsibility for the
disappearance, The Courier-Journal of Louisville reported in
Friday's editions.
   Ortiz, a native of Grants had received at least seven
threatening letters since January, all warning her to leave the
country, Dallard said.
   Dallard said Ortiz would not have wandered off. When others at
the retreat center finished breakfast, Dallard said, Ortiz was gone
and her shawl was found on the ground.
   Ortiz and two other Ursuline sisters were in the Central
American country to work as religious educators in the village of
San Miguel Acatan.
   Some of the letters said ``The military know you're here,''
``Don't ever go around alone,'' and ``There's people here that want
to hurt you,'' Dallard said, adding that Ortiz had asked her to
keep the letters for evidence in case something happened.
   ``There's no logical reason why anybody would have anything
against her,'' Dallard said. ``She did a lot of work with little
kids. There's no way anybody could find anything subversive in what
she was doing.''
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Dave Denny said the
U.S. embassy in Guatemala City has a report on Ortiz, and the
Guatemalan police also have been given a missing person report.
   The police wait 24 hours before doing anything to see if a
missing person turns up, he said.
</TEXT>
