<FIRST>r a AM-DigestBriefs 1stAdd a9910 11-02 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Digest Briefs, 1st Add, a9910,0439</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush appeared to reopen on Thursday
the possibility he may seek a renewal of military aid for the
Nicaraguan Contras, saying ``we will leave our options open'' now
that the Sandinista government has resumed military attacks.
   Speaking to reporters after visiting El Salvador's ailing former
president, Jose Napoleon Duarte, Bush accused Nicaraguan President
Daniel Ortega of waging a ``military and intimidation campaign'' by
calling off a 19-month old truce.
   The administration has sent out mixed signals over the past two
days about the possibility of asking Congress to restore lethal aid
to the Contras.
   Bush left open that option on Tuesday but his spokesman, Marlin
Fitzwater, suggested on Wednesday that possibility was not being
serious considered.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush and Senate Republicans offered
Thursday to end their attempts to attach a capital gains tax cut to
crucial debt legislation, all but conceding defeat for the year on
what has been Bush's top legislative priority.
   ``We have tried to work constructively and cooperatively with
the Congress in a true spirit of bipartisanship,'' said a statement
from the president. ``Now the stalemate must be broken.''
   With an increase in the national debt limit needed next week to
stave off a default by the Treasury, Senate Minority Leader Bob
Dole, R-Kan., told Democrats that Republicans would agree to limit
amendments to the debt-ceiling legislation to those repealing a
Medicare tax to finance catastrophic illness coverage and a tax
provision opposed by business.
   ``No capital gains amendment will be offered,'' he said on the
Senate floor minutes after a meeting with top White House officials
including Chief of Staff John Sununu, Treasury Secretary Nicholas
Brady and budget director Richard Darman.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rear Adm. Richard Milligan said Thursday he
has ``no fear'' of investigations by skeptical members of Congress
into his report on the battleship Iowa explosion.
   ``I think the ultimate conclusion is going to be that they are
going to support my investigation'' and conclusion that gunner's
mate Clayton Hartwig most likely caused the April 19 blast that
claimed 47 lives, Milligan said in an interview.
   Since Milligan, a 30-year Navy veteran who oversaw the Navy's
technical and criminal study, issued his report on Sept. 7, it has
been questioned and criticized by members of Congress, Hartwig's
family and the sailor's former shipmates.
   At the time it was issued, Navy officials acknowledged that
their evidence was circumstantial, given the fact that all the
witnesses, including Hartwig, died in the explosion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891102-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 1441EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv03   11-02 0649</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv03,0671</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Friday, Nov. 3</HEAD>
<HEAD>Stock Market: An Imbalance of Questions and Answers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The controversy over computer-programmed trading
of stocks is compelling investors to review basic assumptions about
the very definition of a marketplace.
   In some ways, the search for that definition is clouded by
details and the fury of the fighting, by vested interests defending
their views and attacking their opponents, and by the enormous sums
of money involved.
   Away from the immediate fray, however, random discussions with
investors and others suggest there still is some agreement on what
services should be provided by a functional market.
   Among them: it must bring buyer and seller together for the
transaction of business, it must handle trades quickly, fairly and
efficiently, and it must establish a reasonable sense of values.
   In specific regard to a stock market, there seems to be
agreement that it must raise capital for industry, allow investors
equal access to buying and selling and facilitate their
participation in corporate ownership while establishing relative
values, providing liquidity and avoiding volatility.
   How well America's financial markets are handling such
obligations is therefore at the heart of the argument over program
trading, which has been accused of causing or exacerbating
explosive price movements on heavy volume.
   In essence, the most common form of such trading is so-called
index arbitrage, or short-term, computer-triggered buying or
selling to exploit brief pricing inconsistencies between spot and
futures markets.
   Individuals aren't likely to be involved, because it takes
millions of dollars to even qualify. But for certain brokers and
pension fund managers, millions of dollars are no obstacle to
playing this game.
   Among the arguments against it are these: it tends to cause or
exacerbate big price swings, it undermines valuations, it serves
little economic purpose, it threatens price collapses, and it
drives individuals from the market.
   At the extreme, some investors view today's marketplace as a
gathering ground for reckless game-playing by privileged traders
and program trading as a device letting large investors skim
profits without risk or responsibility.
   In short, they view recent events as a numbers game played by
intelligent computers, rather than individuals investing in values
_ something of a chess game in which computers instantly process
myriad possibilities.
   But shouldn't a free market be able to accommodate anything
tossed at it? It might be true in concept, but rarely in practice.
Markets of all sorts, even those in relatively simple bartering,
have rules, regulations and limitations.
   Random, informal samplings of opinion suggest that individual
investors aren't totally against program trading. Most likely,
ordinary people do not automatically fear big dollars or great
speed, as in computer trading.
   They recognize that computers are changing life, and that to
resist change might also be to resist opportunity. They know life
evolves in unanticipated ways and ways not easily understood, and
that they must remain current.
   Among questions now puzzling people, however, is instability.
For years the nation's stock exchanges boasted of their ability to
maintain generally smooth trading patterns with relatively minor
price changes between transactions.
   Now investors are told to expect greater volatility in the
future than they were accustomed to in the past, and they wonder if
this isn't an admission of market failure, or at least of an
unhealthy situation.
   What has happened, they ask, to the ability to quickly match
buyer and seller?
   Why can't the damage be contained without requiring the
reassurance of government?
   Why can't the same technology that made program trading possible
be employed to accommodate, or at least reduce the negative impact,
of program trading?
   Everyone is asking questions, and very few people are providing
answers.
   Just as an imbalance of buyers and sellers creates marketplace
volatility, it seems that an imbalance of information creates
questions to be answered.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Friday, Nov. 3.</NOTE>
</DOC>
