<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 0947EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-TVExtra-GaryCooper Adv03   11-02 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-TV Extra-Gary Cooper, Adv 03,0685</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday PMs, Nov. 3</HEAD>
<HEAD>Special on Gary Cooper Airs on TNT</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``His name was Gary Cooper. In a time now fast
receding, he was the greatest of all movie stars.''
   That's how ``Gary Cooper: American Life, American Legend,''
begins, as written by Richard Schickel and narrated by Clint
Eastwood. The one-hour TNT special's first showing is Sunday at 8
p.m. EST.
   Maria Cooper Janis, painter and only child of Gary Cooper,
agrees with the statement.
   The idea for the special was hers. She wanted, through film
clips and home movies, to show her late father as a man and an
actor to viewers born since his death at 60 in 1961. ``There was
diversity in roles he was able to portray. It wasn't just the
stereotyped Westerner.''
   And she wanted to show his values. ``He liked to play roles that
pointed up a sense of valor and quality in human behavior. Playing
Sergeant York and Lou Gehrig gave him his pleasure in life. He
liked the ones that pointed up the best that we can be rather than
the lowest that we can fall to.''
   Mrs. Janis adds, ``Heroes are not uncomplicated. They're not
goody goody. Human conflict and struggle goes on.''
   Her father, she said, ``hated stupid dialogue and unreal
situations.''
   Cooper was famous in movies for brevity of speech. Comics used
to get laughs indicating that all he said was ``Yup.''
   In his private life, his daughter says, ``He wasn't a lecturer
or a pontificator. But he chatted about ordinary things. He had a
wry sense of humor.''
   Her father's fame, she says, did not cause her to have a
troubled childhood, Mrs. Janis says. ``All the trappings, the phony
part that can come into that Hollywood way of life, didn't for them
(her parents) and therefore I had a very solid kind of base.''
   Cooper left his family for five or six years after he met
actress Patricia Neal, which is mentioned in the special. ``Facts
are the facts,'' Mrs. Janis says. ``People live their lives and
things happen and they go through difficult periods.''
   When doctors found that Cooper had lung, colon and bone cancer,
his daughter, who had never wanted to act, recalls, ``I thought
maybe I should try _carry on the family name.'' She took three
lessons. It helped her master a stutter but she realized acting
wasn't for her and returned to painting.
   She chose Schickel, film critic for Time, to write the TV
special because of the foreword he wrote for the book ``Legends.''
``I thought it was the only thing I've ever read about my father
that captured him.''
   Her pianist husband, Byron Janis, is battling arthritis in his
hands and increasingly is turning from performing to lecturing
about Chopin, working for the Global Forum on Human Survival and
composing.
   She asked him to write music for the special. One day, he played
two themes for her. She says, ``I cried at both of them. It was
really like my father had walked into the room.'' He wove them into
``Song for a Hero'' which is part of the soundtrack.
   Sometimes Mrs. Janis gives lectures about growing up in
Hollywood. ``I was in Cincinnati and I said that something which
moved Papa tremendously during the war was going to the South
Pacific to visit the troops. He was nervous and said, `I don't sing
or tell jokes. What can I give the guys?' The captain said, `Coop,
all they want you to do is say the Lou Gehrig speech.' He didn't
know if he remembered it. He said it. Everybody was in silence and
tears.
   ``After my talk a woman came up to me. She said, `I was a nurse
and heard your father do it. You cannot imagine what that meant to
those boys.'''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri PMs, Nov. 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891102-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 1300EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-KlanMovie Adv03-1stLd-Writethru b0291 11-02 0727</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Klan Movie, Adv 03 - 1st Ld-Writethru, b0291,0740</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Friday PMs, Nov. 3, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>NBC Klan Movie Earnest, Script Awful</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS `Elsewhere in television' section to UPDATE with `Nightline'
to have live interview with former President Jimmy Carter.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY SHARBUTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On Sunday night and again on Monday, NBC will
air ``Cross of Fire,'' a two-part tale of a particularly evil Ku
Klux Klan leader in Indiana. It's earnest. Badly written, too.
   Let us put it another way. If you heard a character in a work of
serious TV drama say ``there's lawlessness and loose morals right
here in Indiana,'' would you stay tuned?
   NBC's work of serious TV drama tells of the rise in the 1920s of
a young, handsome, rich Indianapolis Klansman who denies he is
bigoted, likewise the Klan. He insists that each only wants
morality, Prohibition and patrotism.
   A gifted recruiter, he swells Klan membership rolls with such
talk. He also is, in his stiff way, crazed with love for a
beautiful state education worker who only wants to help the
children of black migrant workers learn to read.
   With John Heard as the Klansman and Mel Harris as the educator,
the film also is, in theory, a drama about how the Klan, masking
hatred of blacks, Jews and Catholics, once became a strong
political force in America.
   Based on what NBC calls the true story of Klan leader and
political boss D.C. Stephenson and occasionally using old newsreel
clips of Klan parades and seemingly benign deeds, this could have
been a good two-hour movie.
   But that would have required a decision to either concentrate on
the Klan's rise or on Stephenson _ whom this film eventually shows
as a sham, a drunk and a sadist, one who kidnaps the woman he
professes to love and so viciously abuses her after the kidnapping
that she takes poison.
   Instead, NBC's epic, written by Robert Crais, tries on both
fronts. The result is four long hours of cliches, with a plodding
first part that turns vicious near its end, and a concluding
chapter of courtroom melodrama that features Lloyd Bridges as the
crafty old defense lawyer.
   Complete with a crusading Indianapolis newspaper editor (George
Dzundza) who helps an inexperienced young prosecutor (David Morse)
bring Stephenson (Heard) to justice, this ``Cross'' is almost too
much to bear.
   Heard and Harris each are fine actors. But save for moments when
Heard gets to erupt in drunken rages, their characters are so
wooden they could be a termite paradise. One keeps wondering why
they're so attracted to each other.
   Harris' Madge Oberholtzer also seems naive beyond repair. True,
when he tells her the Klan is going to crown him Grand Dragon and
asks if she knows what that means, she playfully inquires: ``You
turn green and grow scales?''
   But when he blabbers his love for her, all she can say is,
``It's all so confusing, Steve.''
   Well, any woman would be confused by a swain who likes to wear a
purple hood and robe, and start a Klan rally by welcoming the
``Imperial Wizard, Grand Goblins, Exalted Cyclops ... and all
citizens of the Invisible Empire.''
   This would be fine comedy were it not for the brutality he
wreaks on her later on. But even those shocking moments are
followed by passages that continue to exhibit author Crais' ear for
memorable dialogue.
   A good example, uttered in Monday's chapter by a young reporter
after reports of violence against the Klan, is this: ``Sounds to me
like the seeds of a full-blown rebellion against the Klan.''
   Sounds to me like you can miss all this.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   HOSTAGES REMEMBERED _ Saturday is the 10th anniversary of the
seizure of the U.S. Embassy in Tehran by Iranian militants.
Tonight's major network news programs will note this, with ``NBC
Nightly News'' concluding its two-part report on the seizure and
its aftermath.
   ABC's ``Nightline,'' which grew out of ABC's late-night coverage
of the Iran hostage crisis, also plans a one-hour then-and-now
edition that includes a live interview with former President Jimmy
Carter, a spokeswoman says.
   ``Nightline,'' anchored by Ted Koppel, began on Nov. 8, 1979, as
``The Iran Crisis: America Held Hostage,'' anchored by the late
Frank Reynolds.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri PMs, Nov. 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
