<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 2023EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-CatholicBishops Adv05   11-02 1189</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Catholic Bishops, Adv 05,1220</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Nov. 5, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Catholic Bishops Celebrating Turbulent History in U.S.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``For it is incredible how hateful to non-Catholics in all parts
of America is the very name of bishop ...''
   _ The Rev. Ferdinand Farmer, American missionary (1773)
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRIGGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Wearing the bishop's mitre in the Roman Catholic Church in the
United States has never been easy.
   From the day in 1789 when Pope Pius VI established the Diocese
of Baltimore and named John Carroll the first U.S. Catholic bishop,
the church here has had to defend the American way of life before
the Holy See and to calm the fears of non-Catholics that it was
controlled by a foreign power.
   As its bishops meet in Baltimore this week to celebrate the
bicentennial of the Catholic hierarchy in the United States, with a
conservative pope seeking greater central authority and the
abortion battle fueling critics' claims that the church wants to
set moral standards for the nation, the church is still trying to
find its place in the American experiment in democracy.
   ``I think the current leadership of the U.S. Catholic Conference
needs to continue to articulate to the Holy See the unique
characteristics of the United States,'' said Bishop James Malone of
Youngstown, Ohio, past president of the National Conference of
Catholic Bishops. ``The task of Carroll vis-a-vis the Holy See and
the task of the current church leadership vis-a-vis the Holy See is
basically the same.''
   But this time around, the American church is no longer the new
kid on the block.
   The 53 million-member Catholic Church in the United States has
grown from a persecuted minority in an isolated outpost to the
nation's largest religious group and one of the most influential
voices of Catholicism in the world.
   If a pope today tried to correct the errors of ``Americanism''
with a scolding papal encyclical, as Pope Leo XIII did in 1899,
``it just won't be paid attention to,'' said Jay Dolan, a historian
at Notre Dame.
   The United States' revolutionary experiment in democracy made
its mark on the Catholic hierarchy from the start.
   Heeding pleas from 18th century Jesuit missionaries such as
Ferdinand Farmer that appointing a bishop would only antagonize
Americans suspicious of the church's independence from Europe's
Catholic nations, the pope did not appoint Carroll as the first
American bishop until 1789, a century and a half after the church
was established in Maryland.
   One of the first issues the new bishop had to face was
trusteeism. Following the example of Protestant churches around
them, many Catholic churches were run by lay trustees, who even
took upon themselves the role of selecting priests. Carroll trod
lightly on that issue, leaving to his successors the battles to
reestablish the hierarchy's right to appoint priests.
   As American Catholicism grew with waves of immigrants in the
19th century, groups such as the Know-Nothing party and the
American Protestant Association forced the still young and
struggling church to defend itself against charges it was aiming
for ecclesiastical control of the new nation.
   Catholics also experienced more basic persecution. In 1834,
rumors that nuns were murdering illegitimate children in convent
basements prompted rioters to burn the Ursuline Convent in
Charlestown, Mass. Ten years later in Philadelphia, 13 people died
in the torchings of two Catholic churches.
   The challenges confronting the church already had brought its
leaders together in unprecedented fashion as early as 1810.
American bishops gathered, again a highly unusual thing to do in
the church at that time, in Baltimore in 1852, 1866 and 1884.
   At one meeting, the bishops took their first significant social
stand, deciding to defend the Knights of Labor, the first national
union and with a majority Catholic membership, against charges it
was communistic. Cardinal James Gibbons of Baltimore appeared
before the Holy See in 1887 and averted a papal condemnation of the
Knights.
   In the late 1800s, Rome became concerned about the influence on
other nations of such American ideals as religious liberty and
church-state separation, and the ``Americanist'' controversy
erupted.
   Pope Leo XIII's encyclical decrying the idea that the church
should adapt its doctrine to the modern age and that the American
church could be different put a stop to doctrinal ferment for
decades, but U.S. church leaders continued to organize.
   In 1919, the National Catholic Welfare Conference was founded.
The Bishops' Program of Social Reconstruction, which opposed child
labor and urged minimum wage laws and other social reforms, was
published that year. Catholics in other nations didn't begin this
sort of activism until the 1950s.
   ``The church in the United States was very conscious of the way
the U.S. was organized politically,'' said Monsignor Joesph
Gremillion, a scholar-in-residence at Notre Dame. ``The church
(leadership) in the United States felt the need of comparing notes,
consulting with one another, taking positions.''
   The Catholic conference in this country became a model for
national and regional church groups elsewhere. After the 1961-65
Second Vatican Council gave official recognition to national
conferences, the National Conference of Catholic Bishops was formed
in 1966.
   The Vatican, however, may not have been ready for the influence
wielded by the U.S. bishops.
   The papacy, which had assumed that stands on international
issues were its prerogative, ``was somewhat startled'' by the
American bishops' pastoral letters this decade on nuclear war and
the economy, said Gremillion, a former Vatican official.
   The bishops' place in the universal church is still debated
between members of the American hierarchy and the Vatican.
   When John Paul II met with the U.S. bishops in Los Angeles in
1987, he called on them to lift up unpopular Catholic teachings,
saying it is ``a grave error'' to consider dissent from the Holy
See ``totally compatible with being a good Catholic.''
   He was told in turn by Archbishop Rembert G. Weakland of
Milwaukee that ``an authoritarian style is counterproductive, and
such authority for the most part then becomes ignored.'' Archbishop
John R. Quinn of San Francisco said, ``We cannot fulfill our task
simply by an uncritical application of solutions designed in past
ages for problems which have qualitatively changed or which did not
exist in the past.''
   Still, the overall trend is conservative, according to some
church observers. ``We are now in a period of reaction to that
earlier period of the Second Vatican Council,'' said the Rev.
Thomas Reese of the Woodstock Theological Center at Georgetown
University.
   But in the United States, an educated Catholic laity that has
stepped from the pews into the inner sanctum in roles ranging from
parish administrators to eucharistic ministers is not turning back,
some church leaders say.
   ``It amazes me how much people want to do in the church,'' said
Archbishop Daniel E. Pilarczyk of Cincinnati, vice president of the
bishops' conference. ``I think that's wonderful and I could see how
that could be scary. ...
   ``If that gets off the track, it could be a mess. I don't think
it's off the track. American Catholics don't want it to get off the
track.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Nov. 5</NOTE>
</DOC>
