<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 1133EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--GoldenEggs Adv06   11-02 0752</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Golden Eggs, Adv 06,0768</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv06</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, Nov. 6, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sunny Side Up for Girl's Egg Experiment</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL ARABAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHERMAN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   She's been called the ``Chicken Feed
Queen'' by schoolmates and doubted by scientists, but Alice Havens
remains undeterred in her quest to help millions of egg-loving
Americans.
   Every day around 5 a.m., the 17-year-old high school student
slips out of bed and into a pair of boots by the kitchen door, then
heads for her backyard, where she feeds 25 hens a special formula
to cut the cholesterol in eggs.
   Cholesterol-lowering research also is going on in laboratories
where researchers with advanced degrees and heavy funding measure
results with fancy instruments. Havens' experiment started out as a
project for the science fair.
   Sitting at the kitchen table, she opens a notebook to the typed
pages that detail her research. She says the charts show that the
special feed has dropped the cholesterol count 22 to 27 percent,
and that it's going down even further.
   Some scientists are skeptical, questioning her testing methods
and results. Dr. Edward Naber, who's been doing egg experiments for
30 years at Ohio State University, doesn't think her numbers are
significant.
   Havens, who has applied for a patent, is pushing on. Her words
get stronger, her pace quicker, when asked to respond to skeptics:
``Well, that's your opinion and I've got mine, and just because of
what you said isn't going to make me stop.''
   The Havens family lives in a big wooden house tucked deep in the
woods in Sherman, with two horses, a collie, two cats and Alice's
25 chickens.
   Science has occupied her since seventh grade, when the
papier-mache volcanoes she made with her best friend, Hannah
Roberts, won a prize at the Science Horizons fair in Danbury. ``We
built all these volcanoes, and we had a backdrop and everything,
with moss and paint, and it was a huge mess.''
   Inspired by her teacher, John Halloran, she kept entering the
fair, studying vision in horses one year, chicken feed in another.
In early tests, she gave her hens different diets, like sunflower
seeds and oyster shells; she started testing for cholesterol when
she entered New Milford High School.
   ``What I did was I tested different things on the hens, things
farmers sometimes fed, to see if the cholesterol level would change
in any way.''
   She hit pay dirt with the third diet, an ingredient she decided
to try _ and won't disclose _ because a friend of her sister had a
lot. Before, the hens laid jumbo eggs with 388 milligrams of
cholesterol; after, it was 340.
   Havens says the level has dropped even more, but she won't
release the figures until the next phase of the experiment is over.
She's also trying to pinpoint exactly what in the feed is working.
   Many researchers have tried to cut eggs' cholesterol but failed
to find a safe, cheap diet, said Naber, a food science professor.
He questioned Havens' figures, and said a large Connecticut egg has
202 milligrams of cholesterol and the national average is 213.
   Havens sticks by her guns, saying she started out with bigger
eggs and hasn't relied on U.S. Department of Agriculture standards
as a benchmark. She's also egged on, so to speak, by the accolades
she's won in the last two years.
   At the kitchen table, she flips through a scrapbook to
certificates and letters from the American Heart Association and
the Nutmeg Institute of Food Technologists, and mementos like an
luggage tag from her trip to Knoxville, Tenn., for the
International Science Fair. Her booty includes an encyclopedia set,
five shares of stock from United Technologies Corp., a leather
briefcase, five trophies on her bedroom dresser, four framed
certificates on the wall above her bed, and enough cash to pay for
the experiment.
   Last summer, Havens went to London for a science symposium with
800 students from around the world. She presented her research,
made friends, toured castles _ and intiated a walkout at one
session when a boy from Ireland made disparaging remarks about Vice
President Dan Quayle. She was reprimanded for taking 400 students
with her when she left in disgust.
   She's also learned to handle the kidding she gets from some
schoolmates. ``When I first started my sophomore year, I got a lot
of ribbing for it,'' but now that she's onto something big, ``it
doesn't bother me anymore.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Nov. 6</NOTE>
</DOC>
