<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 1138EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--Briefs Adv06   11-02 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Briefs, Adv 06,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv06</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, Nov. 6, and thereafter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tiny detectors using off-the-shelf
parts and cheap 9-volt batteries can do a better job of spotting
intruders at military bases than the Vietnam War-era sensors that
weigh 140 pounds use $170 batteries.
   The miniaturized system, using eight seismic detectors the size
of cigarette packs, a portable monitor, two infrared detectors and
a beacon, is already being used by the Army, Air Force and Marine
Corps, said Dori Miller, supervisor of the sensor systems division
at Sandia National Laboratories.
   ``They're not the whole answer, but they do give you a first
alert _ where to look and when to look...,'' Miller said. ``A
Marine gets tired, gets hungry, may have to go to the men's room,
and sensors don't do that.''
   The seismic detectors are buried around a perimeter with only
their antennas above ground and transmit codes to the hand-held
monitor. The infrared detectors can signal a break in an infrared
beam, and the beacon sends a status report on the whole system
every 10 minutes. The system is remote-controlled.
   Depending on the setting, the seismic units can pick out
``anything from personnel to tanks,'' Miller said. The system costs
less than $3,000, compared with the $12,000 to $15,000 for the
older detectors that were used.
   Sandia researchers also are working on a magnetic detector and
one that would be able to detect a warm body, she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOGAN, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tang's fine, but astronauts may want
something to put on their cereal so researchers are trying to find
a way to store milk in space.
   ``NASA has decided that dairy products are necessary for
long-term space habitation,'' but needed a product that could be
stored without refrigeration, said Paul Savello, an assistant
professor of nutrition and food sciences.
   When the space agency approached Utah State University, its
Center for Dairy Food Technology had an answer:
ultrahigh-temperature sterilization, which shoots steam through
milk or passes milk over a hot plate to kill bacteria.
   UHT milk products can be stored warm on shelves for years,
although they taste better if they're cooled before serving,
Savello said. Researchers also are working on yogurt, custard,
cheesecake and citrus-flavored milk drinks.
   If NASA comes up with a pouch that can withstand the needed
heat, a pouch of milk will be on a December shuttle flight, he said.
   The steam method works instantaneously by shooting steam into
the milk at about 285 degrees, holding it at that temperature for
four seconds, then using vacuum to withdraw the excess moisture
from the steam. Using large, hot metal plates takes longer but
doesn't require the extra step of removing steam.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Nov. 6</NOTE>
</DOC>
