<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House has voted overwhelmingly to raise
the hourly minimum wage from $3.35 to $4.25 by April 1991 and
create a new, lower wage for teen-agers with less than six months
of work experience.
   The 382-37 vote Wednesday on a compromise struck between
President Bush and congressional Democrats sends the measure to the
Senate, where leaders have promised to pass it before Thanksgiving.
   Bush's signature then would trigger the first increase in the
minimum wage since January 1981. The compromise provides a 45-cent
increase to $3.80 next April 1 and another 45-cent jump a year
later.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has accused USX Corp. of more
than 2,000 repeated and deliberate violations of worker-safety
standards at two Pennsylvania steel plants and proposed fining the
company a record $7.3 million.
   The Labor Department's Occupational Safety and Health
Administration said Wednesday the company had ignored many of the
alleged violations despite an agreement to eliminate them two years
ago. Many problems were similar to those blamed for deaths at the
two plants in question, the agency said.
</TEXT>
