<TEXT>
   Orders to U.S. factories for manufactured
goods remained flat in September, but would have fallen if not for
the second-largest increase in defense orders ever, the government
reported.
   The Commerce Department said Wednesday that orders for both
durable and non-durable manufactured goods totaled a seasonally
adjusted $236.7 billion in September. That included a 59.6 percent
gain in defense orders, to $12.7 billion, the largest advance in
that category since a record 68.3 percent increase in June 1988.
</TEXT>
