   The Los Angeles Herald Examiner, once the
nation's largest afternoon newspaper, said it would publish its
last edition today.
   The announcement was made Wednesday at a tearful meeting called
in the newsrooom by Robert Danzig, Hearst Corp.'s vice president
and general manager of Hearst Newspapers. The closure was
attributed to heavy losses and a lack of suitable buyers since the
paper was formally placed for sale during the summer.
