<FIRST>r f PM-ConsumerConfidence     11-02 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Consumer Confidence,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumer Confidence Stable In October, Survey Indicates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer confidence remained stable in October
despite sharp gyrations in the stock market, the Conference Board
reports.
   A monthly survey conducted for the business-financed research
group indicated consumers were positive in their assessments of
business conditions during October and in their expectations for
coming months.
   The Conference Board's Consumer Confidence index registered
116.4 in October, compared with 116.3 in the previous month and
with a 1985 base of 100, the group said Wednesday.
   Among those responding to the survey of 5,000 households, 28.2
percent said business conditions were ``good,'' compared with 27.1
percent in September, while those characterizing business
conditions as ``bad'' was flat at 16.9 percent.
   Some 30.4 percent said jobs were plentiful, unchanged from in
September, while 20.2 percent said jobs were hard to get, compared
with 20.7 percent the month before.
   Expectations about the next six months also were largely
unchanged, the Conference Board said, with 20 percent believing
business conditions would improve compared with 8 percent believing
they would deteriorate.
   Fabian Linden, executive director of the Conference Board's
Consumer Research Center, said the stock market's late October
decline, and the 190-point drop in the Dow Jones industrial average
on Oct. 13, apparently had little effect on confidence.
   ``Survey returns received after the drop in the Dow Jones
average were about the same as the views expressed prior to that
event,'' he said.
   Buying plans were mixed. Some 6.7 percent of respondents
indicated they planned to buy automobiles in the next six months,
compared with 8.1 percent in September, while 3.3 percent said they
would buy a home during that time, compared with 3.1 percent in
September.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
