<FIRST>r f PM-TreasuryFinancing     11-02 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Treasury Financing,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Treasury To Sell $40 Billion In New Bonds, Notes In Quarterly Auction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Treasury Department said it plans to
borrow $40 billion from the public in the next two weeks in a
series of debt auctions being held to replenish the government's
depleted coffers.
   But officials said Wednesday the auctions are contingent on
passage by Congress of a bill to raise the federal debt limit. The
government's borrowing authority dropped Tuesday midnight to $2.80
trillion from $2.87 trillion.
   The House has voted to raise the debt ceiling to $3.1 trillion
for the current fiscal year, but Senate legislation has been
blocked by a squabble over whether to cut the capital gains tax.
   Michal Basham, deputy assistant Treasury secretary for finance,
told reporters Wednesday they auctions probably would have to be
postponed if the legislation is not approved early next week.
   According to Wednesday's announcement, the auctions for next
week would including:
   _$10 billion in three-year notes in minimum denominations of
$5,000 to be auctioned on Tuesday.
   _$10 billion in 10-year notes in minimum denominations of $1,000
to be auctioned next Wednesday.
   _$10 billion in 30-year bonds in minimum denominations of $1,000
to be auctioned next Thursday.
   These notes and bonds are regularly sold during the large debt
auctions which are held four times a year.
   In addition, for this series of debt auctions the government
said it would sell $10 billion in 36-day cash management bills
which would mature on Dec. 21. These bills will be sold in minimum
denominations of $1 million.
</TEXT>
