<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 0101EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Bush-AndeanTrade     11-02 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Andean Trade,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Announces Tariff Reductions for Andean Nations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has unveiled a package of trade
initiatives to help create ``economic alternatives to drug
trafficking'' for the Andean nations of South America.
   The initiative grew out of a promise Bush made to Colombian
President Virgilio Barco at a Sept. 28 meeting to expand economic
trade as part of the war on drugs.
   The White House said Wednesday the initiatives will include
expanding the list of agricultural and industrial products from the
Andean nations allowed into the United States duty-free. It gave no
specifics.
   The White House said Bush was proposing bilateral and regional
initiatives to bolster trade with Colombia, Bolivia, Peru, Ecuador
and Venezuela.
   ``I believe that through increased trade we can make a
contribution to the creation of economic alternatives to drug
trafficking,'' Bush said in a statement. ``Healthy economies are
the only lasting solution for eliminating the drug trade and
substituting legitimate trade.''
   Bush said, ``We are prepared to do all that we can to enhance
the benefits the countries of the region enjoy under our
Generalized System of Preferences,'' including an immediate review
``to consider the addition of new products, both agricultural and
industrial, to the program.''
   Those preferences provide breaks on tariffs for developing
nations.
   Bush said the United States was also prepared to ``explore
possibilities for expanding textiles trade,'' and giving technical
trade assistance to the Andean nations.
   He said the United States is committed to ``build on the
political consensus to negotiate a new International Coffee
Agreement that corrects the fundamental problems with the previous
agreement.''
   Coffee prices have plunged, much to the distress of Colombia and
other major coffee-producers, since the United States quit the last
agreement in July.
   The United States was upset with restrictions on sales of
certain types of coffee favored by American consumers and with
lower prices on coffee charged East bloc nations outside the
agreement.
   He also said the United States will seek to accelerate tariff
negotiations with participants in international trade
liberalization talks now underway in Geneva, and to support
multilateral development banks' efforts ``to promote meaningful
trade policy reforms in the Andean nations.''
   Bush said he also planned to consult with the major U.S. trading
partners, including Canada, Japan and the European Community, on
ways to help the Andean nations.
   ``Our goal must be to help create an environment where
entrepreneurship can flourish and comparative advantages can be
successfully pursued in competitive world markets,'' the president
said.
</TEXT>
