<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 0104EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-EconomicOutlook     11-02 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Economic Outlook,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fed Survey: Economic Growth Varies from Slow to Moderate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's economic growth continued to vary
from slow to moderate early this fall, the Federal Reserve said in
a survey that did not mention any inflationary problems.
   ``Consumer spending is mixed, with a number of districts
describing retail sales as steady to growing slowly,'' the survey
summary said Wednesday. ``Manufacturing activity is also mixed,
with some districts reporting weakenss in orders and shipments.
   ``Weakness of construction in some markets contrasts with
evidence of some improvement elsewhere. Resource industries,
including the energy sector, appear to be improving, as is
agriculture generally,'' it continued.
   The survey by the 12 district banks is compiled by the Fed every
six weeks to prepare for meetings of the Federal Open Market
Committee, the Fed's monetary policy-setting arm. The next meeting
is Nov. 14.
   Recent economic indicators show sluggish economic growth
following Fed moves to ease inflationary pressures by tightening
credit. As inflation appeared to abate this summer, the central
bank has eased its grip.
   The latest survey was prepared at the Fed's Kansas City bank
based on information obtained before Oct. 10.
   Seven of the 12 districts mentioned prices. They were
``generally stable'' in Boston, while ``moving up but at a
slackening pace'' in Philadelphia.
   Cleveland expects ``very little moderation in inflation''
through the end of the year, while Richmond reports a slower rise
in input prices. Respondents in the Atlanta district ``reported
only modest wage or price pressures.''
   In the Kansas City district, ``retail prices and prices of
manufacturers' inputs have changed little in recent months,'' while
``wage and price increases remain modest'' in the San Francisco
district.
   In the retail area, the srvey found that ``sales of apparel,
basic housewares and other nondurables are described as relatively
strong. Sales are weaker for discretionary, big-ticket items such
as furniture, home appliances and consumer electronics; auto sales
have also been weakening recently.''
   Manufacturing activity was described as slowing in the
Philadelphia, Chicago and Cleveland districts; varied in Richmond
and St. Louis, and improving in Boston, Dallas and San Francisco.
   Signs of weakness in residential construction appeared in St.
Louis, Kansas City and Atlanta. Dallas reported little change,
while Chicago reported receiving mixed reports. Richmond reported
stronger demand for mortgage loans.
   Nonresidential construction was reported to be weak in Atlanta
and St. Louis, holding up well in Chicago and improving in Dallas,
New York and San Francisco.
   The San Francisco district reported that most businesses in its
area ``have resumed operations since the earthquake, but road
closures and property damage are delaying a complete return to
busienss as usual.''
   The Richmond district said many of the usual South Carolina
participants in its survey did not respond because of Hurricane
Hugo. But it said the hurricane had little effect on the industrial
base of either of the Carolinas.
   Hugo, however, ``severely affected the agriculture sectors of
North and South Carolina, bringing extensive damage to crops and
structures as well as considerable destruction of livestock and
poultry. Total damage to the farm sector in both states has been
estimated at nearly $1.2 billion.''
</TEXT>
