<FIRST>r f PM-Bush-FoodSafety     11-02 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Food Safety,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumer Groups Oppose Bush Food Pesticide Proposal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Marlyn is cq in penultimate graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumers have more protection under existing
food pesticide laws than they would under changes proposed last
week by President Bush, a consumer lawyer told a Senate panel.
   ``We're better off with current law if we're going to have to
sacrifice the basic health nature of the statute,'' Janet S.
Hathaway of the Natural Resources Defense Council said Wednesday at
Labor and Human Resources Committee hearing.
   She called the Bush plan a ``cynical effort'' that
``fundamentally erodes the basic health-protective standard in the
food safety law'' by letting the government weigh the benefits of a
hazardous pesticide when deciding whether to cancel or suspend it.
   Her organization was joined by Public Citizen and Consumer's
Union in criticizing the Bush proposal to raise the acceptable
cancer risk level to one in 100,000. Critics say a risk level of
one in 1 million, the standard used last year by the Environmental
Protection Agency, should be applied.
   Although the proposals would result in swifter cancellation and
more suspension of especially dangerous pesticides, critics
questioned whether the EPA would have the political courage to
enforce a law that allows a risk-benefit calculation.
   Further, they said the plan fails to address ``aggregate risks''
_ the total risk when the entire diet of a person is considered,
not just a single pesticide in one food. Also, safety legislation
needs to consider the risk to special populations, such as children
and pregnant woment, they said.
   Legislation by Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., chairman of the
committee, would address those issues.
   Representatives of the agricultural chemical industry and farm
groups criticized both the Bush and Kennedy proposals, although
they backed Bush's risk-benefit formula.
   They said the standard in the Kennedy bill would amount to a
``zero risk'' because of its numerical formula of one in 1 million,
but they said the Bush definition of an ``imminent hazard'' would
be subject to inconsistent applications.
   ``Not only do pesticides help ensure the availability and
affordability of agricultural products, but they are often
necessary to ensure the safety and nutritional value of many
commodities,'' said Marlyn Jorgensen, president of the American
Soybean Association.
   ``The health benefits offered by pesticides to the American
consumer cannot be overlooked,'' he said.
</TEXT>
