<FIRST>r f PM-Bush-Hungary     11-02 0152</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Hungary,0158</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Lifts Import Duties On Hungarian Goods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has added Hungary to a list of
nations whose imports can receive duty-free treatment in a further
effort to boost that nation's emerging open-market economy.
   The action Wednesday came a few days after Bush lifted 15 years
of trade sanctions against the Soviet-bloc nation by restoring
most-favored-nation status.
   Hungary recently declared itself a democracy, and Bush praised
it for riding the crest of the way of political reform sweeping
eastern Europe.
   Wednesday's action adds Hungary to countries that are part of
the General System of Preferences. Usually extended to developing
or poorer nations, this system allows a wide array of products to
be imported into the United States duty-free.
   The exact products are to be determined later. In general terms,
imports given such privileged treatment only lose it if they become
direct threats to identical U.S.-manufactured items.
</TEXT>
