<FIRST>r f PM-AutoSafety     11-02 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Safety,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rear-Seat Belt Requirement Being Extended to Light Trucks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal requirement that cars have rear-seat
shoulder and lap safety belts will be extended to light trucks and
convertibles, Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner said.
   Skinner also said Wednesday his department will extend to light
trucks and ``multi-purpose passenger vehicles,'' such as vans and
four-wheel-drive utility vehicles, the existing roof
crush-resistance standards for passenger cars.
   The new requirements will be made final after a 60-day public
comment period.
   ``Light trucks are being used more and more to transport people
instead of property,'' Skinner said in a statement. ``These new
rules will help ensure that occupants are adequately protected,
particularly in rollovers.''
   Spokesmen for the Big Three auto manufactuters said they already
were meeting one or both of the proposed standards or would by the
1992 model year, when the rules are to take effect. They would
apply to cars made after Sept. 1, 1991.
   The department's National Highway Traffic Safety Administration
acknowledged in a statement that most light truck manufacturers are
voluntarily meeting the level of roof crush resistance required for
passenger cars. But the agency said extending the standard would
ensure ``total compliance'' by current and future manufacturers.
   Under the proposed roof crush rule, roofs would have to
withstand a force of 1{ times the unloaded weight of the vehicle.
During a test, a vehicle's roof could not be depressed more than
five inches.
   The rule would apply to multi-purpose passenger vehicles and
trucks with a gross vehicle weight rating of 10,000 pounds or less.
   Skinner announced the regulatory changes in a speech to the
National Safety Council in Chicago.
</TEXT>
