<DOCNO> AP891102-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 0124EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Economy     11-02 0690</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Economy,0715</SECOND>
<HEAD>Purchasing Managers' Survey Indicates Manufacturing Sector Remains
Soft</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. economy continued to slow in the third quarter as the
manufacturing sector weakened for the sixth straight month,
according to new reports from the nation's purchasing managers and
the Commerce Department.
   Analysts said the data provides further evidence that the
economy's growth has softened since an unexpectedly brisk summer
and could remain sluggish in the months ahead.
   The Purchasing Manager's Index, a widely watched economic
barometer, rose to 47.6 percent in October from 46 percent in
September and 45.2 percent in August, the group said Wednesday.
   A reading below 50 percent indicates the manufacturing sector of
the economy is in decline while a reading above 50 percent
indicates growth, according to the association.
   It was the sixth straight decline in manufacturing but the
second consecutive month where the rate of decline was less than in
the previous month, said the National Association of Purchasing
Management.
   A huge increase in defense orders helped boost U.S. factory
orders in September, the government said in a separate report
Wednesday, although without defense contracts such orders actually
declined, while construction spending remained flat during that
month.
   ``This confirms what is essentially a weak economy,'' said
Lawrence A. Veit, an economist with the investment firm Brown
Brothers Harriman &amp; Co.
   A survey by the Federal Reserve of the nation's economic growth
largely reinforced the other data. Results of the six-week survey
concluded that the economy is growing at a slow to moderate pace
with manufacturing and construction weak in some sections of the
country, consumer spending mixed and resource industries, including
energy and agriculture, improving.
   The monthly purchasing managers report is based on a survey of
purchasing executives in more than 250 industrial companies. The
index is a composite of responses regarding six separate
indicators, including new orders, production, vendor deliveries,
inventories, prices and employment.
   The Commerce Department, meanwhile, said orders for durable and
nondurable manufactured goods totaled a seasonally adjusted $236.7
billion. Excluding the jump in defense orders, orders actually
declined 2.1 percent.
   In a separate report, the department said construction spending
was unchanged in September after surging by 1.5 percent in August.
Residential, non-residential and government construction spending
totaled a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $415.6 billion in
September.
   Spending spurted in August because of a strong 5.3 percent
increase in government building and a 2.9 percent gain in
non-residential construction.
   Contributing to the decline in the October purchasing managers
survey was a steep drop in the export orders growth rate. While
export orders remained relatively brisk last month, the index fell
to 55.5 percent from 60.5 percent.
   ``If you keep short-term interest rates high eventually they
will affect exports,'' said Thomas F. Carpenter, an economist with
ASB Capital Management.
   The manufacturing and housing sectors of the economy have been
hit hardest by high interest rates as the Federal Reserve tightened
credit in an effort to slow inflation.
   However, the survey also indicated a sharp turnaround in new
orders growth after a four-month decline. Robert J. Bretz, chairman
of the association's Business Survey Committee, said the reversal
``hints of a possible continued easing in the overall future rate
of decline in the manufacturing economy.''
   New orders is one of six variables considered in the purchasing
managers' survey. The new orders index rose to 51.4 percent from
45.4 percent in September.
   Nevertheless, while U.S. manufacturing is sluggish, some
economists said the purchasing manager's survey has overstated the
weakness.
   ``All this says is that the manufacturing sector is weaker than
the economy as a whole,'' said Giulio Martini, an economist with
Sanford C. Bernstein &amp; Co. Inc.
   ``Fundamentally the manufacturing sector is strong,'' Carpenter
said. ``You just need a drop in interest rates of about a half
percentage point and we wiil start to see a release of the pent-up
demand pressures that have been building.''
   Indexes for vendor deliveries, production, prices and employment
all declined, according to the survey.
   The seasonally adjusted indexes for the six separate indicators
represent the net change between those reporting positive, negative
and similar responses from the previous month.
</TEXT>
