<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 0907EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Japan-Fujitsu     11-02 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Fujitsu,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fujitsu Tries To Withdraw Another One-Yen Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KOZO MIZOGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just days after Fujitsu Ltd. failed in its attempt
to escape a contract for which it bid 1 yen, or about 0.7 of a U.S.
cent, the Japanese computer giant said it was trying to withdraw
from another 1-yen deal it says lacks ``common sense.''
   Akira Imagawa, a spokesman at Fujitsu's headquarters in Tokyo,
said Wednesday that company officials in the Nagano prefecture in
central Japan had asked local authorities to cancel a contract the
company won last month with a 1-yen bid.
   Both cases have attracted the attention of Japan's Fair Trade
Commission, whose officials say they are considering an
investigation into whether the unusually low bids constitute unfair
trade under the Anti-Monopoly Law.
   In the Nagano deal, Fujitu and electronics giant NEC Corp. made
identical 1-yen bids for a contract to design software for the
prefectural libary's computer system, local officials said.
   The prefectural government had set aside 16 million yen, or
about $112,000, in its budget for the project, the officials said
on condition of anonymity.
   ``Front-line salesmen desperately wanted to win the contract ...
but lacked common sense,'' Imagawa said.
   In the earlier case, Fujitsu officials said their 1-yen bid to
design software to map the Hiroshima city water supply system
represented a long-term investment. But later they appeared to
change their minds and asked the city to cancel the contract. The
city had budgeted $78,000 for the project.
   City officials refused, although they said their decision would
depend on the outcome of a possible Fair Trade Commission
investigation.
   ``We will continue to seek the city's understanding to retract
the contract,'' Fujitsu's Imagawa said.
   Meanwhile, officials of the Ministry of International Trade and
Industry cautioned Fujitsu on Tuesday about business practices that
were ``beyond common sense,'' said an official of the ministry's
Electronics Policy Division.
   The official, who spoke anonymously, said the ministry also
urged major member companies in the Japan Electronics Industry
Development Associaton, a industrial grouping of computer and
electronics makers, ``not to make discount sales at irrational
prices.''
   Companies competing for both the Hiroshima and the Nagano
contracts reportedly saw the projects as a way to get a head start
on computer systems expected to be linked up throughout the country.
   But Makoto Sakata, a noted commentator, said the cases also
demonstrated that corporate ethics lag behind generally accepted
rules of behavior, with companies emphasizing their relations with
local officials rather than profitability.
   ``Looking at what Japan's leading high-technology companies like
Fujitsu and NEC are doing, It's painfully clear that modernaization
of Japanese corporations is superficial and that they in fact
remain unchanged from the feudal age,'' Sakata said.
</TEXT>
