<FIRST>r f BC-Spain-Drexel     11-02 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Spain-Drexel,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Securities Commission Fines Drexel's Spanish Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Securities Commission Thursday
recommended the Spanish unit of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. be
fined the maximum amount for fraudulent trading practices.
   The watchdog agency recommended the Economy Ministry fine DBL
Capital Markets Espana SA 65 million pesetas _ or $556,725 _ or
five times the amount of the operation's gross profits, which is
the maximum fine under law.
   The Spanish branch of the U.S. securities firm was liquidated in
June.
   The commission said its investigation ``sufficiently proved''
the trading company had committed ``a very serious infraction''
during the partial privatization of shares of the state-controled
Repsol oil group last May.
   The Spanish investigation, made public last June, was an
embarrassment to Drexel, which earlier this year had pleaded guilty
to six U.S. felonies brought under a U.S. insider trading probe and
agreed to pay more than $650 million to settle criminal securities
charges.
   The commission also said it had turned over evidence to a local
court to determine whether the infraction also constituted criminal
fraud.
   Drexel's Spanish unit allegedly created false clients through
unauthorized use of names of Spaniards in order to secure the
maximum number of shares allowed to brokers for resale. Instead,
Drexel sold the shares to just 17 foreign institutional investors,
the investigation showed.
   Last July, Drexel's chief executive officer said the firm had
ordered its 27-employee Spanish unit closed down after the
announcement of the investigation, which the firm described as
``improper behavior.''
   Under Spanish law, the Spanish unit's parent company is legally
responsible for the fine since the unit has been liquidated.
</TEXT>
