<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0333</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market turned downward today as
traders awaited the latest reading on the state of the economy.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 10.24 to
2,635.66 in the first half hour of trading.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 7 to 5 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 375 up, 524 down and
524 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 19.56 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   The Labor Department is due to report Friday morning on the
employment situation for October.
   Advance estimates call for the figures to show a relatively
modest increase in nonfarm payroll employment, reinforcing recent
evidence of slowing economic growth. That would presumably give the
Federal Reserve extra leeway to relax its credit policy soon,
encouraging interest rates to fall.
   But brokers said investors were still worried about unexpectedly
weak earnings reports issued by many companies for the third
quarter.
   A good many Wall Streeters believe profits and dividends may
suffer further this winter, even if the economy is able to achieve
a ``soft landing'' rather than any severe slump.
   Uneasiness on that score was heightened today when Compaq
Computer projected lower fourth-quarter profits. Compaq shares were
delayed in opening.
   UAL rose 2 to 179 following word late Wednesday that Reliance
Group sought clearance to increase its interest in the company to
more than 15 percent.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped .45 to 188.39. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was up .10 at 372.24.
   On Wednesday the Dow Jones industrial average edged up .82 to
2,645.90.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 5 to 4 on the
NYSE, with 841 up, 632 down and 475 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 154.24 million shares, against 176.10
million in the previous session.
