<HEAD>Zenith Gets Five-Year Computer Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLENVIEW, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zenith Data Systems, which has already
supplied many of the personal computers in use at the Defense
Department, has won a five-year contract to provide support
services for those machines.
   Company officials of Zenith Electronics Corp.'s computer
products subsidiary said Wednesday the contract should result in
more than $534 million in revenues over seven years.
   Under the terms of the contract, Zenith Data Systems will supply
advanced peripherals and software, plus training and maintenance
services for the Personal computers the company has supplied to the
Army, Navy, Marine Corps, Air Force, Defense Logistics Agency and
other defense organizations.
   The government has the option of receiving maintenance, training
and support services from Zenith for an additional two years beyond
the five-year span of the contract, officials said.
   Zenith announced last month that it is selling its computer
business to Groupe Bull of France, subject to stockholder approval.
