<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 1134EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-SIA-Downey     11-02 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SIA-Downey,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Downey Says Problems In Securities Industry Not Pervasive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The securities industry needs to work harder to
safeguard the marketplace and address program trading and index
arbitrage, strategies accusedc of causing wide swings in the stock
market, the newly nominated chairman of the Securities Industry
Association said today.
   ``Our organization needs to sit down and do something about it.
We need to look at the pros and cons,'' said Robert N. Downey,
partner with Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. and a former member of the
Municipal Securities Rulemaking Board.
   Downey, 53, was named to succeed Hardwick Simmons as 1990
chairman of the trade group, which represents more than 625
securities brokerages and investment banking firms in the United
States and Canada.
   The SIA board will vote on the nomination at its annual meeting
on Nov. 29 in Florida.
   In recent days, several major Wall Street brokerages have said
they will curb program trading that critics claim is dangerously
distorting the stock market and scaring away small investors.
   In program trading, millions of shares of stocks are traded
almost instantaneously by computerized systems used mainly by huge
institutional investors such as banks, mutual funds and pension
funds.
   ``Our policy has to be to address'' controversial strategies,
Downey said.
   However, he said many of the problems facing the industry have
been overstated.
   ``We've had these outside factors and we have insider trading
scandals and things of that nature that maybe involve just a few
people, but they are magnified and thought to be pervasive, but
they're not,'' Downey said.
   Also nominated to the SIA board were John L. Steffens, president
and chief executive of of Merrill Lynch, Pierce, Fenner &amp; Smith
Inc., as vice chairman; Richard B. Fisher, president of Morgan
Stanley Group Inc. and Addison L. Piper, chairman fo chief
executive of Piper, Jaffray &amp; Hopwood, both renominated as vice
chairmen.
   Simmons, vice chairman of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., will
continue to serve as an officer and director of SIA.
