<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   11-02 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Gain In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices rose slightly in
early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade amid concern
about the Brazilian soybean crop and expectations for new export
business.
   A survey released Wednesday of Brazilian soybean growers showed
just 2 percent of the crop planted compared to an average of 11
percent for the same date in recent years.
   Brazil is the world's second-largest soybean producer after the
United States. Analysts say economic troubles are forcing South
American farmers to reduce their plantings of both soybeans and
corn.
   Indications of new export business supported the soybean and
wheat markets. News of Soviet interest in buying U.S. meat has
spurred speculation that the Soviet Union may increase its imports
of other commodites, too.
   In early trading, wheat futures were 1 cent to 2{ cents higher
with the contract for delivery in December at $3.99 a bushel; corn
futures were } cent to 3 cents higher with December at $2.40{ a
bushel; oats were 1\ cents to 1} cents higher with December at
$1.44} a bushel; soybeans were 1} cents to 5 cents higher with
November at $5.64{ a bushel.
   Pork-belly futures surged in early trading on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, extending a three-day rally linked to Eastern
European demand for U.S. meat. Cattle futures were mostly lower.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .17 cent lower with December at
74.27 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .20 cent lower
with November at 82.92 cents a pound; hogs were .07 cent to .25
cent higher with December at 47.90 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .78 cent to 1.80 cents higher with February at 59
cents a pound.
   Pork futures advanced sharply on Wednesday while cattle futures
retreated.
</TEXT>
