<FIRST>r f PM-JapaneseBuy     11-02 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japanese Buy,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Group Buys Houston Office Buildings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese investors snapped up another piece of
America, joining with a Dallas group to buy a high-rise office
complex in Houston's most expensive real estate deal.
   Taikichiro Mori, one of Japan's most famous developers, said
Wednesday the group he heads will pay about $300 million for 85
percent of the Four Oaks Place Development in partnership with the
Lehndorff USA Group of Cos.
   Interfin Corp. will retain a 15 percent stake in the 18.5-acre
project.
   The four office buildings are in Houston's Galleria area, a
financial and residential high-rise district.
   News of the deal came two days after another Japanese company,
Mitsubishi Estate Co., announced it was buying controlling interest
in Rockefeller Center, a New York landmark, for $846 million.
   ``The people who have been the last to take a long, hard look at
Houston have been the Japanese,'' said Marilee Wood, spokeswoman
for Interfin Corp., developer of Four Oaks.
   Ms. Wood said while other investors have begun returning to the
Houston marketplace in recent months, buying offices, apartments
and industrial buildings, the Japanese have shied away from new
deals in the once-beleaguered oil city.
   She said the deal indicates the city is on the recovery path.
   The last big purchase by Japanese investors in Houston was in
December, when Shintech bought a prime block of downtown real
estate from Campeau Corp. for about $7.3 million. The land was
being used as a parking lot.
</TEXT>
