<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 1154EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Compaq     11-02 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Compaq,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Compaq Stock Halted Following Poor Earnings Forecast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Compaq Computer Corp.'s stock plunged nearly 15
percent today after the company announced fourth-quarter earnings
will be below expectations.
   Shortly before 11 a.m. EST, Compaq was off $15.37{ at $90.62{ in
heavy New York Stock Exchange trading. In the last year, the stock
traded as high as $112.50 a share and dipped as low as $52.
   ``October sales came in about 10 percent below our expectations,
leading us to believe that the results of our fourth quarter would
not meet analysts' expectations,'' Compact Chief Executive Rod
Canion said today. ``Sales for the full fourth quarter, however,
are still expected to grow 15-20 percent over the previous year.
   ``And, as a result of the normal, tightly controlled financial
environment in which the company is managed, we believe our overall
performance will be consistent with the company's long-range
objective of 8-to-10 percent profit after tax.''
   A week ago, Compaq stock tumbled 8 percent after the computer
maker disclosed it uncovered two minor flaws in the i486
microprocessor made by Intel Corp. The chip will be the brains of a
major new computer Compaq is introducing next week.
   Canion blamed lackluster sales on a slowing growth rate in the
American market, limited availability of new products and continued
uncertainty about the new i486 chip.
   Intel, which said the two flaws had been discovered by an
unidentified customer, said it would begin shipping a fixed version
of the chip by the end of this month.
   One flaw involves trigonometric functions and another involves a
feature that detects irregular operations, like attempting to
divide by zero. Both occur only under special conditions and would
not affect most users, the company said.
   Compaq also reported last week its earnings jumped 51 percent in
the third quarter, but part of the increase came from a gain in the
carrying value of its investment in a disk-drive maker Conner
Peripherals Inc. The earnings were at the low end of analysts'
expectations.
</TEXT>
