<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 1248EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-US-JapanCable     11-02 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Japan Cable,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trans-Pacific Cable Gets OK</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pacific Telecom Cable Inc. received
final federal approval to install the western end of the first
digital fiber-optic cable that will stretch directly from the
United States to Japan.
   Pacific Telecom Cable, a majority-owned subsidiary of Pacific
Telecom Inc., said Wednesday it received a final license from the
Federal Communications Commission. It had received a conditional
FCC license in April 1987.
   The license will enable the company to link Pacific City, Ore.
and Seward, Alaska with the international fiber-optic cable network
by the target date of December 1990, company President Dennis
Elliott said.
   The cable project is a joint venture between Pacific Telecom
Cable of the United States, International Digital Communications
Inc. of Japan and Cable and Wireless PLC of the United Kingdom.
Pacific Telecom owns the U.S. portion of the project.
   The 5,200-mile project is the largest fiber-optic cable network
authorized for the Pacific Ocean region and the first to provide
direct service between the United States and Japan, the company
said. Currently, telephone services are routed through Hawaii.
   The network will link the U.S. domestic digital network,
trans-Atlantic fiber optic cables, and fiber optic networks serving
Japan, Asia and the Pacific Rim.
   The cable can carry up to 85,000 telephone conversations
simultaneously on 17,010 circuits.
   The increase in capacity will allow users to place calls easier
and the digital fiber-optic materials will make the connections
clearer, said Stephen E. Lovas, Pacific Telecom Cable
vice-president of sales and marketing.
   The system will also provide the first digital fiber-optic link
between Alaska and the rest of the U.S. mainland through an
underwater branching unit 700 miles south of Seward. Currently,
analog satellite systems are used.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
