<DOCNO> AP891102-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 1302EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-RetailSales     11-02 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Retail Sales,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>October Sales at Big Retailers: Mixed Bag</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's big retailers today reported mixed October sales
with results at some general merchandise stores hurt by consumers'
reluctance to spend freely on expensive goods, such as furniture or
home appliances.
   Clothing retailers fared better than major national chains that
depend heavily on sales of ``big-ticket'' durable goods.
   But in some parts of the country, particularly the Northeast,
unseasonably mild weather discouraged shopping for winter apparel.
   ``They were generally modest kinds of sales gains that continued
the basic trend of the past several months,'' said analyst Jeffrey
Feiner of Merrill Lynch &amp; Co.
   ``The department stores and some of the specialty retailers
outperformed the durable-goods dependent retailers, such as Sears
and K mart,'' Feiner said.
   Sears, Roebuck and Co., the largest U.S. retailer, said its
sales edged up 0.7 percent in the four weeks ended Oct. 28 to $2.53
billion from $2.51 billion a year earlier.
   But sales at Sears stores open at least a year, called
same-store or comparable-store sales, were flat.
   Retailers and analysts regard same-store sales as a better
reflection of a company's performance than tallies that include the
take at newly opened stores.
   Feiner said results for some of the retailers looked slightly
worse than they were because they were being compared with a strong
month last year.
   Analysts said it was difficult to generalize about last month's
retailing business because the results varied so widely. Economists
track retailers' results closely for clues about spending patterns;
consumer spending accounts for about two-thirds of total U.S.
economic output.
   ``The numbers were really mixed, more so than we've seen in
previous months,'' said retail analyst Jeffrey Edelman of Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Within the apparel category alone there were variations.
Moderate to higher-priced clothing merchants posted fairly strong
results while apparel sales at discounters lagged, analysts said.
   The figures reported today by major general merchandise chains
and apparel retailers differ from the government's monthly retail
sales figures. The Commerce Department report is more comprehensive
and covers sales at auto dealers, supermarkets, restaurants and
elsewhere.
   Among some of retailers reporting were:
   _K mart Corp., the second-largest retailer, said its October
sales increased 5.3 percent to $2.07 billion from $1.97 billion in
October 1988. Its comparable-store sales were up 2.1 percent.
   _Third-ranked Wal-Mart Stores Inc. reported a 22 percent
increase in October sales to $2.19 billion from $1.79 billion.
Wal-Mart's same-stores sales grew 8 percent.
   _J.C. Penney Co. Inc. reported a 9.6 percent October sales gain
to $1.28 billion from $1.17 billion. Penney's same-store sales rose
8.2 percent.
   _Dayton Hudson Corp. reported October sales went up 16.2 percent
to $969 million from $834 million. Its same-store sales rose 8.5
percent.
   _Limited Inc., a leading specialty apparel retailer, said its
sales rose 9 percent to $334.9 million from $307.7 million. On a
comparable-store basis, Limited's sales were up 6 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
