<FIRST>u f AM-IntegratedResources     11-02 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Integrated Resources,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sale Set on Core Business But State Regulators Clamping Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Integrated Resources Inc. agreed Thursday to
sell its key businesses for up to $225 million but regulators in
Iowa and Colorado clamped down on two life insurance subsidiaries
in moves that could block the deal.
   The sale to Broad Inc., a Los Angeles-based financial services
company with $7 billion in assets that include the SunAmerica
insurance groups, is subject to price adjustments at the time of
closing. The deal would be worth $170 million if completed Thursday.
   The deal would cap Integrated's months of attempts to sell its
core businesses to raise money to help meet payments on about $1.75
billion in debt and avoid a bankruptcy court filing.
   State insurance officials said Thursday they had placed Des
Moines, Iowa-based Integrated Life Insurance Co. and Denver-based
Capitol Life Insurance Co. under supervision and required prior
approval for any sale.
   Iowa's insurance commissioner has advised Integrated that the
Broad sale does not meet regulators' approval and the state is
considering issuing an order to take over the assets and operations
of Integrated Life next week.
   Integrated said discussions were under way with the state and
Broad to restructure the sale to meet the insurance commissioners'
unspecified demands.
   Colorado's Insurance Division on Wednesday required Capitol Life
to obtain state approval before taking any actions outside the
normal course of business, such as selling assets, merging with
another company or investing funds.
   Chad Collier, the division's chief of financial affairs, said
the state had received calls and letters from Capitol Life
policy-holders concerned about the company's fate.
   ``It's making their policy-holders real nervous and I can
understand why,'' he said. ``We would not want the parent company's
problems solved by taking assets out of its subsidiary. ...We want
to see the company sold to another solid buyer.''
   The planned sale to Broad also includes Integrated Resources
Asset Management Corp., an investment adviser; Integrated Resources
Equity Corp., which recently was transferred to two company
executives and renamed; and Resources Trust Co.
   Under terms of the deal, Broad can call off the sale within 30
days after Integrated provides financial and other information.
Until then, Integrated is free to seek other offers for the
businesses and will pay Broad $3 million if the deal falls through.
   The sale price is far below the $450 million Integrated had
hoped to obtain several months ago for its core financial
businesses.
   In an effort to stanch a sales force exodus, Integrated last
month transfered its main broker-dealer subsidiary to two
executives and changed its name from Integrated Resources Equity
Corp. to Royal Alliance Associates Inc. Integrated in June
defaulted on nearly $1 billion of its roughly $1.75 billion in
total debt. Integrated has not paid any principle or interest to
bondholders since then.
   The company's problems stem from difficulties in diversifying
out of real estate into financial services.
   Broad Inc.'s life insurers are Sun Life of America, Anchor
National and First SunAmerica. The company's financial services
group includes broker-dealers Anchor Financial and SunAmerica
Securities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
