<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Kodak     11-02 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Kodak,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kodak Earnings Decline 25 Percent; Third Consecutive Decline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILARY APPELMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. said Thursday its
earnings declined 25 percent in the third quarter, the third
consecutive decline this year.
   Kodak Chairman and Chief Executive Colby H. Chandler blamed the
continued slide on higher operating costs and no improvement in
productivity, despite record sales for the quarter.
   ``Everything had very sluggish qualities to it, although
individual businesses performed well,'' said financial analyst Mark
Obenzinger of Trinity Trading Co. in New York.
   In another adverse development for Kodak, the International
Union of Electrical Workers has said it is planning a drive at
Kodak, which has long staved off organization attempts by offering
workers generous bonuses and benefits.
   IUE organizers have been working on Kodak for the past four to
six weeks and have distributed thousands of leaflets at the plant
in the past week, said union organizer Edward E. Young.
   The company announced earnings of $329 million, or $1.02 per
share, for the quarter ended Oct. 1, compared to $435 million, or
$1.35 per share, in the same quarter last year. The company
reported record sales of $5.11 billion for the third quarter, up 2
percent from last year's record $5.03 billion.
   Earnings fell 23 percent in the first quarter and then 85
percent in the second quarter, when they were depressed by the
expenses of a streamlining program. Analysts said it is too early
for the effects of the restructuring to show up in the company's
earnings.
   Kodak said its results will be depressed again in the fourth
quarter by costs of a restructuring program announced in August.
The company announced plans for 3,500 job cuts _ about 3 percent of
the company's worldwide employment _ wage freezes, the sale or
consolidation of many of its businesses, and other cost-cutting
measures.
   ``The productivity issue and rates of return on the business are
being addressed aggressively by action under the company's recovery
plan, which is on target,'' Chandler said.
   Net earnings for the first three quarters of 1989 were $589
million, or $1.82 a share, down 46 percent from $1.09 billion, or
$3.35 a share, in the first three quarters of 1988. Those earnings
were reduced by $227 million in restructuring costs recognized in
the second quarter. Sales for the first three quarters of 1989 rose
8 percent to $13.5 billion from $12.5 billion a year earlier.
   The company said operating earnings on overseas sales were
reduced by foreign currency rate changes, but those changes were
offset by marginally higher prices.
</TEXT>
