<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 2021EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-CrayResearch     11-02 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Cray Research,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cray Founder Formalizes Split With Founder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cray Research Inc. has formalized its split
with Seymour Cray, the company's founder who is designing the
supercomputers once considered its key hope for the early 1990s.
   Having already pumped $106 million into his Cray-3, Cray
Research said Wednesday its $98.6 million contribution to spinoff
firm Cray Computer Corp. hinges on Seymour Cray's continued
affiliation with the new supercomputer company.
   Gary Smaby, an analyst who follows Cray Research for the
Minneapolis-based Smaby Group, said, ``The most revealing
disclosure is that the deal is off if Seymour leaves the firm or
dies.''
   Cray, 64, is to be chairman and a computer developer for Cray
Computer, a 241-employee firm based in Colorado Springs. The
spinoff is to occur Nov. 15 through a distribution of stock to
existing stockholders of Minneapolis-based Cray Research.
   Like Cray Research, Cray Computer will develop high-speed
scientific computers known as supercomputers. Its machines will
sell for $15 million to $30 million each.
   The disclosure of Seymour Cray's financial importance to Cray
Computer was one of several key points Cray Research revealed
Wednesday in an information statement on the new company.
   In addition to hinging on Seymour Cray's presence, the $98.6
million financial gift from Cray Research depends on no individual
acquiring more than 20 percent ownership in the new firm, Cray
Computer continuing to pursue the Cray-3 project and the avoidance
of bankruptcy by the new firm.
   The split places the hopes for the 1990s of Minneapolis-based
Cray Research squarely on the C-90 supercomputer design under way
in Chippewa Falls, Wis.
</TEXT>
