<FIRST>u f BC-BritishStocks 1stLd-Writethru f0038 11-02 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0038,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity, closing indices;
No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed modestly lower Thursday after
London's confidence was shaken by unconfirmed rumors of an
insider-trading scandal touching the government and by continued
declines on Wall Street.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index lost 6.0
points, or 0.27 percent, to close at 2,154.1, roughly midway
between its session low of 2,146.3 and high of 2,160.3. The key
index moved around its closing level for much of the afternoon,
although it hit the day's highs on a brief flurry of technical
buying in early afternoon trading.
   Volume was 348.4 million shares, down from 379.9 million on
Wednesday.
   The widely circulated insider-trading rumor was tied to a report
in a Scottish newspaper that a British television network was about
to name at least one senior government official in a report on
insider dealing. The rumor prompted speculation of further
upheavals within the government and sent London shares lower at the
outset.
   The specific focus was on Transport Minister Cecil Parkinson,
who strongly denied the rumors.
   The denial helped ease the market's worries, but dealers said
more wind was taken out of London's sails by a subsequent
announcement that Ford Motor Co. reached an agreed bid of 850 pence
a share, or 1.6 billion pounds, for British automaker Jaguar PLC.
   The news, along with a statement from General Motors Corp.,
ended most of the speculation over a bidding war for the luxury
automaker.
   Wall Street's early declines kept London under pressure for much
of the afternoon, dealers said.
   ``The insider-trading rumors really kept the market at bay,'' a
senior dealer with Kleinwort Benson Securities said. ``It set the
tone. But mostly people were just not too keen to rush and buy it.
And they weren't too keen to sell it, either.''
   The big stock feature of the day, however, was Jaguar at 30
million shares traded.
   The FT 30-share index settled 6.8 points lower at 1,731.3. The
FT 500-share index was down 3.72 at 1,195.09.
</TEXT>
