<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain Futures Rise Amid Export Talk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans posted
moderate gains Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade, supported by
market rumors of pending export sales of U.S. grain to the Soviet
Union and China.
   ``It was mostly a Russian day,'' said trader Victor Lespinasse
of Dean Witter Reynolds Inc., referring to talk that the Soviets
were seeking to buy 4 million metric tons of U.S. corn and 200,000
to 500,000 metric tons of U.S. soybean meal.
   The Soviet Union also was rumored to be shopping for wheat and
analysts said the Agriculture Department was expected to announce
it is targeting China for sales of 1 million metric tons of U.S.
wheat at subsidized prices.
   The soybean market also benefitted from a survey showing
Brazilian soybean planting running well behind the normal pace.
   Brazil is the world's second-largest soybean producer after the
United States. Analysts said economic troubles are forcing South
American farmers to reduce their plantings of both soybeans and
corn.
   Wheat futures settled unchanged to 4 cents higher with the
contract for December delivery at $4.02 a bushel; corn was
unchanged to 3 cents higher with December at $2.40{ a bushel; oats
were 1} cents to 2 cents higher with December at $1.45\ a bushel;
soybeans were 5 cents to 8 cents higher with November at $5.66} a
bushel.

