<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 1553EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-UAL Bjt   11-02 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UAL, Bjt,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>Steinberg Stake Could Be Catalyst For New UAL Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investor Saul Steinberg is unlikely to lead a
takeover bid for UAL Corp., but he could play a big supporting role
in the next act of the UAL buyout saga, industry analysts said
Thursday.
   Steinberg, who is said to be a close friend of UAL Chairman
Stephen Wolf, took center stage Wednesday when his Reliance Group
Holdings Inc. filed for federal antitrust clearance to buy more
than 15 percent but less than 25 percent of UAL's stock.
   Such a request often signals that the petitioner seeks an active
role in the target company and usually a measure of control. But
because of his association with Wolf, analysts said Steinberg
probably was positioning himself to help UAL's chairman attempt
another buyout or a corporate restructuring.
   Chicago-based UAL is the parent of United Airlines, the nation's
second-largest carrier and one of its most profitable.
   UAL stock surged in early trading on the New York Stock Exchange
but the rally faded to a gain of only 75 cents a share by midday,
with the stock trading at $177.75.
   The stock had traded as high as $294 a share last month when it
appeared that a $6.75 billion buyout proposal by Wolf, United's
pilots union and British Airways PLC would succeed. The deal soured
three weeks ago when the group said it couldn't get adequate
financing for the $300-a-share bid.
   Steinberg helped lure Wolf to run Tiger International Inc. when
Steinberg was a director and major investor in the air cargo
company. Its subsidiary Flying Tiger, which has since merged with
Federal Express Corp., became profitable under Wolf _ who went on
to join UAL, then called Allegis Corp., in 1987.
   Now Wolf is the one needing help and Steinberg may be looking to
return the favor, said Jack Hunter, an analyst with Howe Barnes
Investments Inc. in Chicago.
   ``He (Steinberg) might be the catalyst to say, `Hey, this
company is a good company, its undervalued, let's get the unions
and everybody together and see if we can all walk forward,'''
Hunter said.
   Support from United's unions, especially the pilots and the
powerful Machinists, is believed to be crucial to any transaction,
whether instigated by UAL's board of directors or an outsider.
   The Machinists union bitterly opposed the proposed
pilot-management buyout, but union officials have recently taken a
conciliatory stance and say they are willing to compromise to
prevent an outside takeover.
   But the Machinists, who represent more than a third of UAL's
workers, expressed wariness Thursday about Steinberg.
   ``It looks like he's looking to run UAL stock up again,'' said
union spokesman James Conley in Washington, D.C. ``We will probably
take a look at everything that comes down the road but ... we're
opposed to running UAL stock up again to the point where we feel
the stock is overpriced.''
   Hunter figured a fair price for UAL stock is $190 to $220 a
share.
   Neither the pilots nor United's flight attendants would comment
on the Steinberg development. The flight attendants joined the
pilot-management group last month after British Airways dropped out.
   Analyst Kevin Murphy of Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. in New York said
recent high-volume trading of UAL stock indicated that another
party may have acquired a substantial stake in the company.
   That party's identity might be revealed in the next several
days, he said, through a Securities and Exchange Commission filing
required of investors who make large purchases of a company's stock.
   If a takeover-minded third party does surface, Murphy said, the
employee-management group may feel compelled to make a new buyout
bid at a lower price.
   As for Steinberg, he said, ``I think he's being prepared to
perhaps be allied with his old business friend Steve Wolf in the
event there is a bid.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891102-0288 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 2332EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d f BC-BusinessJournals     11-02 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Business Journals,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Publishing Company to Move</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of American City Business
Journals Inc., which operates 21 local weekly business
publications, is stepping down and the company is moving its
headquarters to Charlotte, N.C.
   Michael K. Russell, American City president who founded the
company in 1982 with his longtime business partner William H.
Worley, said Wednesday he was stepping down as president effective
Nov. 30.
   The loss of the publishing headquarters will affect about 20
jobs in Kansas City, although an undetermined number of employees
may be transferred to Charlotte, Russell said. An additional 40
jobs, at the firm's Kansas City Business Journal, will not be
affected, he said.
   Shaw Publishing Inc., a Charlotte-based publishing company, owns
30 percent of American City and has agreed to purchase an
additional 25 percent from the E.W. Scripps Co. in 1990.
   Ray Shaw, the head of Shaw Publishing, became American City's
chairman and chief executive officer in June.
   Russell, 50, said American City's headquarters was being moved
to Charlotte to consolidate administrative operations with Shaw
Publishing. The move was expected to be completed over the next two
months, he said.
   When asked why he was resigning, Russell, a native of Kansas
City, Kan., said, ``I don't want to move to Charlotte.''
   Shaw said in a statement that he would assume Russell's
responsibilities is a successor isn't selected by Nov. 30.
</TEXT>
