<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     11-02 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed in Worldwide Trading</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede BC-LONDON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished mixed in light trading
Thursday as dealers awaited the release of fresh data on the
economy.
   The price of gold, spurred by new foreign appetite for the
metal, rose sharply. On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold
bullion for current delivery rose $6.20 a troy ounce to close at
$380.40 an ounce. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a late
bid for gold of $378.80 an ounce, up $5.90 from Wednesday's late
bid.
   The dollar fluctuated in a narrow range as dealers awaited
Friday's release of U.S. unemployment figures for October.
   Kevin Lawrie, a vice president at Bank of Boston's New York
office, said currency dealers were looking for a slight increase in
unemployment, which would prove bearish for the dollar.
   ``Higher unemployment generally signifies a slowdown in the
economy, possibly moving toward a more recessionary atmosphere''
and pressuring the Federal Reserve to lower interest rates, he said.
   Lower interest rates make U.S. securities less attractive to
foreigners and dampen their need for dollars.
   Much of the day's trading centered on other currencies,
particularly the British pound, which took a beating following
rumors that one or possibly two government ministers had resigned
because of insider-trading offenses.
   Despite a denial issued by the prime minister's office, the
pound still lost more than 1.5 cents against the dollar. Traders
said the West German mark and Japanese yen directly benefitted from
the pound's troubles.
   Earlier in Tokyo, the dollar closed at 143.75 yen, up from
143.08 yen on Wednesday. In London late Thursday, the dollar ended
lower at 143.65 yen. In New York, the dollar finished at 143.43
yen, down from 143.80 yen late Wednesday.
   In London, one pound cost $1.5660, cheaper for buyers than
Wednesday's late $1.5815. In New York, one pound cost $1.5695, less
expensive than $1.5755 on Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Wednesday's
late rates, included: 1.8424 West German marks, down from 1.8505;
1.6162 Swiss francs, down from 1.6260; 6.2490 French francs, down
from 6.2740; 1,354.75 Italian lire, down from 1.358.75; and 1.1733
Canadian dollars, down from 1.1743.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with Wednesday's
late rates, included: 1.8485 West German marks, up from 1.8377;
1.6140 Swiss francs, up from 1.6132; 6.2670 French francs, up from
6.2305; 2.0860 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0790; 1,356.00 Italian
lire, up from 1,348.50; and 1.1725 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1742.
   Trading in gold bullion was light. In London the metal finished
at a bid price of $375.25 a troy ounce, up from Wednesday's late
$374.25. The closing bid price in Zurich, Switzerland, was $375.00,
up from $373.40. Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $373.85 bid,
up from $373.65.
   Silver prices were mixed. On New York's Comex, silver bullion
for current delivery rose to $5.255 a troy ounce from $5.150 on
Wednesday. Silver traded late in London at $5.17 bid a troy ounce,
down from $5.18.
</TEXT>
