<HEAD>Oil Futures Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices finished lower Thursday,
unable to sustain a brief midday technical rally.
   The December contract for West Texas Intermediate, the U.S.
benchmark grade of crude oil, ended at $20.01 a 42-gallon barrel on
the New York Mercantile Exchange, down 6 cents from the previous
session. January crude fell 7 cents to $19.71 a barrel.
   Refined products traded on the exchange also declined. Wholesale
unleaded gasoline for December delivery lost 0.69 cent to end at
52.20 cents a gallon, while the January contract declined 0.25 cent
to 52.46 cents a gallon.
   December heating oil finished 0.37 cent lower at 59.99 cents a
gallon and the January contract lost 0.30 cent to 59.65 cents.
   Energy brokers said crude oil prices rallied earlier in the day
on technical factors but stopped short of piercing the
$20.40-a-barrel level.
   ``I haven't seen anything that would have caused the rally,''
said Brian Tagler, a trader with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Analysts said the rally fizzled in afternoon trading as
investors began liquidating and taking profits.
