<FIRST>u f AM-Ford-Jaguar 1stLd-Writethru   11-02 0693</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ford-Jaguar, 1st Ld - Writethru,0712</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jaguar In Surprise $2.5 Billion Takeover Agreement With Ford</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf pvs, But General... to CORRECT price to $13.35
sted $13.58. Picks up 10th graf, ``After an...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jaguar PLC said Thursday it was joining the Ford
Motor Co. fleet in a $2.5 billion buyout, a surprising reversal
that saw Ford winning over a venerable luxury car maker that once
labeled it an unwanted suitor.
   The deal, which combines the vast resources of the American
automaker with the high style of the much smaller British firm, is
expected to further the interests of both companies in the growing
international market for luxury cars.
   ``The partnership we are proposing will enable Jaguar to grow
and become increasingly competitive,'' Lindsay Halstead, chairman
of Ford Europe, said at a news conference.
   To win over Jaguar, Ford had to beat back a challenge from its
chief rival, General Motors Corp., which had been negotiating for
months to acquire a stake in Jaguar.
   Soon after the deal was announced, GM, the world's biggest
automaker, said it would not bid against No. 2 Ford for the company.
   Jaguar shareholders must approve the $13.35-a-share takeover
offer by a 75 percent majority. A shareholder meeting is scheduled
for the end of the month.
   Jaguar, which has roots dating to 1922, had been expected to be
the target of a multibillion-dollar bidding war between General
Motors and Ford after the British government announced Tuesday that
it was prepared to waive its ``golden share'' power to veto any
Jaguar takeover.
   Ford owns 13.2 percent of Jaguar and had indicated it would
mount a buyout bid once takeover restrictions were dropped. General
Motors had acquired regulatory approval to buy up to 15 percent of
Jaguar and its friendly talks with the automaker had been expected
to result in a GM stake of possibly 30 percent.
   But General Motors concluded Jaguar was not worth the $13.35 a
share Ford offered to pay.
   ``After an intensive review of Jaguar's products and plants and
in view of the losses currently being sustained by them, together
with Jaguar's significant future cash and other requirements, GM
concluded that the maximum value that could be assigned to all of
the Jaguar shares was very significantly below the 8.50 pounds
($13.35) being offered...'' a GM statement read.
   Jaguar finished at the equivalent of $13.02 a share Thursday on
London's Stock Exchange, down from Wednesday's close of $14.26.
   Analysts said that although Ford was not Jaguar's first choice,
the British carmaker should thrive under its ownership.
   Jaguar saw its pretax profit drop by nearly 6 percent in the
first half of 1989, largely due to slumping U.S. sales. It has been
looking for 18 months for a partner to provide financial and
technological support to expand its narrow product line and compete
better.
   Jaguar Chairman Sir John Egan told a news conference Thursday
that he regretted Jaguar's loss of independence, but he said Ford
offered a good price and made guarantees about operating
independence.
   Jaguar will be run as a separate entity, will retain an
independent board of directors, its production in Britain will
continue and Jaguar's dealer network will be maintained, the
companies said. Egan also will remain for the immediate future.
   ``To put it simply, the board had a very good offer indeed,''
Egan said. ``They were prepared to make satisfactory guarantees
about how Jaguar would be operated in the future.''
   Some Britons immediately regretted the loss of a truly British
institution.
   The opposition Liberal Democrats accused the government of
scuttling Jaguar's negotiations with General Motors by dropping its
veto power. Party member Matthew Taylor accused the government of
``sending the autonomy of the British car industry to the scrap
heap.''
   Ford's Halstead said there was considerable potential to
increase sales volume by expanding Jaguar's product range in
Europe, the United States and elsewhere.
   He said Ford would inject an unspecified amount of funds into
Jaguar to develop the company's existing product range and boost
its research and development. Jaguar also will be able to use
Ford's worldwide engineering, purchasing and manufacturing
technologies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
