<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     11-02 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gold Hits Three-Month High As Stocks Sink</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The gold futures market drew strength from the stock market's
decline Thursday, hitting three-month highs on New York's Commodity
Exchange amid growing fears of a worsening outlook for equity
investments.
   On other commodity markets, copper futures fell sharply;
stock-index futures sank; pork bellies surged for the fourth
straight day while livestock futures retreated; grains and soybeans
advanced; and oil futures fell.
   Gold settled $6 to $6.20 higher with the contract for delivery
in December at $382.90 a troy ounce, its highest settlement since
July 26. Silver finished 10.2 cents to 10.6 cents higher with
December at $5.29 a troy ounce.
   The gold market's gains more than offset its modest losses in
each of the three previous sessions.
   Analysts said the strength stemmed partly from the stock
market's steep intraday losses, although stock prices rebounded
after the gold futures market closed.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials finished with a 14-point
loss after falling as much as 33 points during the session.
   The stock market's volatile performance in recent weeks has sent
many investors running to the perceived safety of precious metals
and gold stocks, and Thursday's drop in stock prices encouraged the
trend.
   ``This is a thrust and it's intensifying,'' said Bette
Raptopoulos, metals analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
in New York.
   Gold was also supported by the dollar's weakness and the
inflationary implications of generally higher commodity prices on
Thursday.
   August Arace, co-manager of Freedom Gold and Government Trust
Fund, said gold's gains in the past week also reflected new buying
by Russian citizens worried that recent moves to devalue the ruble
could lead to greater inflation in the Soviet Union.
   Copper futures weakened on news that a contract dispute at a
Chilean copper mining complex had been settled.
   Copper settled 90 cents to 3.35 cents lower with the contract
for delivery in December at $1.134 a pound.
   Stock-index futures closed with moderate losses on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange. The contract for December delivery of stocks
in the Standard &amp; Poor's 500 index settled 3.8 cents lower at
339.50. The contract is worth $500 per point.
   Frozen pork-belly futures rose sharply on the Chicago Merc in
anticipation of new demand from Eastern Europe. Yugoslavia recently
bought some U.S. pork bellies, the Soviets are interested in buying
some and the United States was scheduled to sign an agreement
Friday that would lead to the shipment of up to 10,000 metric tons
of bellies to Poland.
   Pork bellies finished .05 cent to 1.12 cents higher with
February at 58.72 cents a pound; live cattle were .20 cent to .60
cent lower with December at 73.75 cents a pound; feeder cattle were
.15 cent to .40 cent lower with November at 82.72 cents a pound;
hogs were .10 cent to .58 cent lower with December at 47.17 cents a
pound.
   Grain and soybean futures posted moderate gains on the Chicago
Board of Trade, supported by market rumors of pending export sales
of U.S. grain to the Soviet Union and China.
   Wheat settled \ cent to 3{ cents higher with December at $4.01{
a bushel; corn was unchanged to 3 cents higher with December at
$2.40{ a bushel; oats were 1} cents to 2 cents higher with December
at $1.45\ a bushel; soybeans were 4} cents to 8{ cents higher with
November at $5.66{ a bushel.
   Oil futures prices finished lower on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, unable to sustain a brief technical rally at midday.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 1 cent to 7 cents
lower with December at $20.01 a barrel; heating oil was .26 cent to
.37 cent lower with December at 59.99 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline waas .05 cent to .69 cent lower with December at 52.20
cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
