<FIRST>u f AM-KLM-NWA     11-02 0169</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-KLM-NWA,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>KLM Reduces Stake in NWA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   KLM Royal Dutch Airlines on
Thursday announced it was reducing its planned stake in the parent
of Northwest Airlines in compliance with U.S. regulations.
   The Dutch flag carrier, which operates a worldwide network from
its base at Amsterdam's Schiphol airport, will reduce by $300
million its stake in NWA Inc., to $150 million, a KLM spokesman
said.
   KLM, which joined the European airline stampede for U.S.
partners earlier this year, is a participant in a $3.8 billion bid
to take over NWA by a group of U.S. investors led by Los Angeles
financier Alfred Checchi.
   KLM's announcement comes only weeks after British Airways PLC
abandoned its efforts to take a substantial interest in UAL Corp.,
the parent of United Airlines.
   The attempt by Western European carriers to gain a foothold in
the North American market has drawn fierce congressional criticism
in the United States, and the U.S. Department of Transportation has
set strict guidelines governing such moves.
</TEXT>
