<DOCNO> AP891102-0301 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 2231EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Herald-Rivals     11-02 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Herald-Rivals,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Other Papers Vie for Herald-Examiner's Readers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Herald-Examiner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newspapers scrambled Thursday to capitalize
on the death of the Herald Examiner by adding news racks, snaring
prize comics and courting advertisers.
   But analysts and newspaper officials said most papers in the
area will be little affected, and even if they pick up readers they
will have to wait at least six months before they can pass on the
costs of printing additional papers to advertisers.
   ``I would think there will be some costs before there are some
benefits,'' said newspaper industry analyst John S. Reidy at Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc.
   In addition, many of the Herald's ads are already carried by
other papers.
   ``The surviving newspapers are going to get some additional
readers but are not going to get much incremental advertising,''
said J. Kendrick Noble, who follows the media industry for Paine
Webber Group Inc.
   Papers geared up immediately after Hearst Corp. announced
Wednesday it would close the Herald, which published its last issue
Thursday after years of big losses.
   Thomas J. Wafer Jr., general manager of Copley Los Angeles,
which owns The Outlook in Santa Monica, The Daily Breeze in
Torrance and The News Pilot in San Pedro, said, ``We intend to beef
up all three to pick up as much advertising as we can.''
   The Long Beach Press-Telegram said it will increase the number
of its news racks and may launch an advertising campaign. ``I'm
sure all of us will be vying for a piece of those readers,'' said
Mack Quintana, senior vice president of sales and marketing.
   The Herald Examiner's syndicated features and comics also went
up for grabs, and former competitors quickly moved in.
   ``The Los Angeles Times has agreed to pick up several of our
biggest features, including Beetle Bailey, Hagar the Horrible and
Hi &amp; Lois,'' said Ted Hannah, director of advertising and public
relations for King Features in New York.
   The Times said it would purchase more than 10,000 of the Herald
Examiner's news racks. Officials estimated the paper would pick up
at most 50,000 of the Herald's 238,000 readers.
   ``We hope to convert them to Times readers,'' said Times
publisher David Laventhol.
   But, he added: ``You are dealing with a relatively small pie
here, and it probably won't affect the marketplace. It's sad but
true.''
   David J. Auger, publisher of the San Fernando Valley-based Daily
News, agreed, saying the Herald's circulation was spread over the
entire greater Los Angeles area and was relatively insignificant in
suburban areas like the Valley and Orange County.
   ``The impact is fairly negligible in our area,'' Auger said.
</TEXT>
