<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 0054EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-PSNHBid     11-02 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-PSNH Bid,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>N.E. Electric System Withdraws Bid for PSNH</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New England Electric System announced Wednesday it
has withdrawn its $2 billion bid for the financially troubled
Public Service Company of New Hampshire and its share of the
Seabrook nuclear power plant.
   John Rowe, New England Electric's president and chief executive
officer, said the prices being offered for PSNH by two other
bidders and the rate levels needed to support those prices are too
high.
   PSNH is operating under the protection of federal bankruptcy
laws.
   New England Electric is a public utility holding company based
in Westborough with three subsidiaries that serve customers in
Massachusetts, Rhode Island and New Hampshire.
   PSNH owns the largest single share in the Seabrook nuclear power
plant in New Hampshire, which continues to fight for a generating
license as its price tag continues to climb, standing now at about
$6.3 billion.
   The other bidders for PSNH are United Illuminating Co. of New
Haven, Conn., and Northeast Utilities of Hartford, Conn.
   United Illuminating has offered a bid it values at $2.29
billion, while Northeast Utilities put its bid at $2.25 billion.
   Public Service spokesman Bill Morrissey said the utility expects
the two bidders to raise their bids.
</TEXT>
